<FIRST>r a AM-HUD-Pool     07-01 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Pool,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>LI Town Cancels HUD-Financed Swimming Pool</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato's hometown on Long
Island will return $1 million in Department of Housing and Urban
Development funds that were earmarked to build a swimming pool, The
New York Times reported.
   Island Park officials requested earlier this week that their
application for the pool be withdrawn, citing local opposition to
the project and rising costs, the Times reported in its Saturday
editions.
   The officials denied that the cancellation was spurred by a
federal inquiry into HUD-sponsored projects on Long Island,
including in Island Park, the Times said.
   Island Park was awarded the $1 million in grants for the pool
last year after D'Amato, a village resident, personally lobbied
then-HUD Secretary Samuel R. Pierce, the Times said.
   The money for the pool came from Pierce's discretionary fund. In
a letter to village residents last fall, DAmato praised Pierce's
``wise decision to approve this grant,'' the Times reported.
   The pool was to have been built near a beach.
   An assistant to HUD secretary Jack Kemp said Kemp was pleased the
pool project was dead.
   ``We think the funds can be used for a purpose that will be more
in line with assisting low-income individuals,'' Mary Brunette, the
assistant, told the Times.
   The Times said it got no answer to telephone calls made to
D'Amato's office Friday afternoon.
   In Island Park, investigators are looking into allegations that
HUD-sponsored houses went to politically connected residents instead
of to minorities, as had been planned.
</TEXT>
