<FIRST>r a AM-GangViolence 1stLd-Writethru a0808 07-01 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gang Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0808,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Renew Mass Gang Sweeps on Eve of July Fourth Holiday Weekend</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Police made ..., to UPDATE arrest totals, restore
dropped first reference for Detective Tony Celli.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH COTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police swarmed through gang-infested
neighborhoods Friday night in the first widespread dragnet for
drug-dealing street thugs since the highly-publicized sweeps dubbed
the ``Hammer'' last summer.
   The eight-hour operation on the eve of the July Fourth holiday
weekend targeted gangs in the three neighborhoods terrorized by
gangs.
   Assistant Chief Robert Vernon told 300 officers at a 4 p.m. roll
call that they should remember many residents are law-abiding
citizens.
   Portable booking trailers were set up at the Police Department's
Southeast Division station in the heart of the Watts district which
was ravaged by riots in 1965.
   Police made 70 arrests in the first four hours of the operation,
30 of them narcotics felonies, and 19 of those arrested were
identified as gang members, said police Detective Tony Celli. Twenty
vehicles lacking current registration tags were impounded, he said.
   ``We are here to enforce all the laws that are applicable,'' said
Celli.
   Community outcry over gang thugs who keep residents prisoners in
their own homes prompted the first full-scale police assault in
April 1988. The 1,000-officer weekend sweeps continued at intervals
through the summer.
   Mayor Tom Bradley, a former police lieutenant sworn to a fifth
term Friday, vowed during the first of the 1,000-officer gang task
force sweeps 15 months ago: ``We are going to take these terrorists
off the streets of Los Angeles.''
   Gang violence continued unabated.
   More than one person died in a county gang-related killing for
every day of 1988. There were 452 gang-related slayings in Los
Angeles County in 1988, surpassing the 387 gang-related murders
reported the year before.
</TEXT>
