<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 0133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-VegasCurfew     07-01 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vegas Curfew,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Hope To Cope with Strip Cruising</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Faced with the wrath of crabby cabbies, miffed
motorists and irate casino owners, officials hope a new curfew will
detour thousands of cruisin' teens who transform the glitzy Las
Vegas Strip into a giant parking lot.
   Two years ago the teen-agers were considered a nuisance by Las
Vegas Metro Police as they tried to control cruising and
congregating.
   ``Then we were talking about 500, maybe 1,000 kids on a weekend
night,'' said Metro Capt. Barbara Connett, who is commander of the
police detachment covering the Strip area. ``It was a manageable
number. Now we're talking upwards of 4,000 kids on a given night.
The problem has mushroomed out of proportion.''
   The problem is blamed on the Strip's growing popularity among
teens and the growth of the city _ from 300,000 eight years ago to
more than 700,000 today.
   ``The numbers were overwhelming,'' Connett said. ``We tried to
control the blocking of the Strip, but all we could do was herd them
up and down the Strip, unless people were willing to hire 500 more
officers'' to bolster the current Strip contingent of 16.
   Casino owners are unhappy because the teens sometimes hassle
tourists, often bumping them into the busy Strip traffic, Connett
said.
   Cab drivers complain it takes forever to drive a few blocks as
teens drive side-by-side down the six-lane road at 5 to 10 mph,
exchanging conversations, obscenities, even passengers.
   The traffic problem is compounded by the fact that 45 percent of
the city's visitors come here by car _ leaving more than 10,000
cars, hundreds of cabs and scores of tour buses jockeying for
position on any given weekend.
   In addition, teen-agers who used to cruise past casinos on
Fremont Street, also known as Glitter Gulch, now drive the Strip
because they were chased away by anti-cruising forces in the late
1970s.
   Flooded with letters from upset tourists and hammered by those
who make a living from the city's $2.5 billion tourism industry, the
Chamber of Commerce huddled with county officials and police in
search of a solution.
   ``It came down to finding a way to get the kids off the Strip
earlier,'' Connett said. ``What we're talking about here is an
`adults only' park in a manner of speaking.''
   The answer was a curfew restricting those under 18 from the Strip
after 9 p.m. Fridays, Saturdays and holidays, unless accompanied by
an adult.
   The curfew went into force June 23 and police reported many
warnings, but no arrests for curfew violations. Connett said
officers will warn teens about the curfew for an unspecified grace
period before turning offenders over to juvenile authorities.
   Teens with legitimate purposes on the Strip, such as visiting
restaurants, are exempt as long as they can explain their presence.
Violators will be detained until their parents pick them up and
repeat offenders will be sent to Juvenile Hall.
   Unhappy teens, who have become accustomed to sharing the
neon-bathed Strip that some call a ``Disneyland for adults,'' have
responded to the cruising ban with the generations-old response ``We
have no place to go, nothing to do.''
   ``That's idiotic,'' Connett says. ``It's the dumbest thing I've
ever heard out of a kid's mouth. This city has probably done as much
or more for its kids than any city in the country.
   ``Some children could be in the center of Disneyland and say they
have nothing to do,'' she said. Connett noted the city has snow
skiing and water skiing 30 minutes away plus a water theme park,
free parks, recreation centers, movies, ice and roller skating
rinks, arcades and other attractions.
   But Las Vegas teens _ or at least a vocal minority _ want to head
for the flashy Strip to mingle with some 100,000 tourists who flock
here each weekend.
  
</TEXT>
