<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 0140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-JunkDispute     07-01 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Junk Dispute,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elderly Woman Fights City in Dispute Over Can Collecting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honey Breske is trying to make ends meet by
recycling, but prosecutors have taken the 92-year-old widow to court
over the pile of trash in her yard.
   Now she is looking for a job to earn the money for the court
battle.
   ``Spry ... widow seeking any employment,'' her advertisement
reads. ``Need funds to fight Housing Court. They won't let me
recycle cans for cash.''
   Mrs. Breske placed the ad in a weekly newspaper after the city
went to court to force her to clear debris from her yard, where she
keeps aluminum cans, boxes and other junk she recycles to supplement
her $369 monthy Social Security income.
   Her neighbors complained about the mess.
   ``I don't think it's fair. These things didn't happen until our
husbands died,'' Mrs. Breske said. ``Then they started picking on
us.''
   One of Mrs. Breske's friends, Jean Dunlap, is in trouble with the
city for the same reason. The court has issued a permanent
injunction against storing debris in her yard and issued more than
$10,000 in fines over the last 12 years.
   ``I can't pay nothing,'' said Ms. Dunlap, 70.
   City attorneys handling such cases say many elderly residents are
turning up in Housing Court, accused of creating dangerous piles of
refuse in attempts to earn money.
   ``We have one to two cases every week with this type of
problem,'' said Dolores Quiroz, the assistant corporation counsel
prosecuting Mrs. Breske. ``And that's a conservative estimate.
Sometimes it's one or two a day.''
   The city gets involved in cases where debris poses possible fire
and health hazards.
   ``It was not just a matter of cans and things like that,'' she
said. ``The problem is that they keep collecting it, and it's
causing serious problems with the neighbors.''
   Mrs. Breske finds recyclable items by rummaging through alleys in
her neighborhood. She started collecting about 10 years ago just
after her husband, Harry, was hospitalized for a heart attack.
   He died five years later, leaving Mrs. Breske with a $45,000
hospital bill. She emptied her bank account and sold jewelry to help
pay it.
   ``I went looking for a job a couple of times. When I told them my
age, they said, `What do you want to work for?''' she said. ``So I
got tired of that. I said, `I'll just go pick cans.'''
</TEXT>
