<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-Jet     07-01 0123</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Jet,0126</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Jet Carrying 212 People Forced to Land in Saskatchewan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SASKATOON, Saskatchewan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Airlines 767 jet en route
to Alaska from Chicago was forced to land Friday in Saskatchewan
because of engine trouble, airline officials said. None of the 212
people on board the jetliner were injured.
   Airport manager Bill Restall said the passengers had to wait in
the plane more than an hour after landing Friday afternoon while
customs officers processed the unexpected visitors.
   Because United decided to repair the broken engine in Saskatoon,
the airline arranged overnight hotel accommodations for the
passengers, Restall said. The flight was expected to continue on to
Alaska on Saturday, he said.
   No cause of the engine trouble was given.
