<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Superior Court Judge Laurence J. Rittenband,
the ``judge of the stars'' who once vowed to remain on the bench
until director Roman Polanski returned for sentencing, has turned in
his gavel.
   Rittenband, 83, whose legal career spanned 60 years, presided
over Elvis Presley's divorce, Marlon Brando's child custody battle
and a paternity suit against Cary Grant.
   ``I can't wait that long,'' Rittenband said Friday of his vow to
wait for Polanski, the film director who fled to France in 1978
rather than appear for sentencing after he'd been convicted of
having unlawful intercourse with a 13-year-old girl.
   Rittenband said he has not forgotten Polanski.
   ``I'll quote a Gilbert and Sullivan opera: `I've got him on my
list. I've got him on my list. He won't be missed. He won't be
missed.'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Zsa Zsa Gabor has been
charged with three misdemeanors, including battery, for allegedly
slapping a policeman who pulled over her $215,000 Rolls-Royce
Corniche and arrested her.
   Los Angeles County Deputy District Attorney Eldon S. Fox said the
misdemeanor charges lodged against Ms. Gabor on Friday accuse her of
battery on a peace officer, disobeying a peace officer and having an
expired driver's license.
   There were also two infractions, which are violations of the
Motor Vehicle Code, alleging that she had an open container of
alcohol in a vehicle and had an expired registration when stopped
June 14.
   The charges carry various sentences upon conviction ranging from
a $100 fine for the violations of the Motor Vehicle Code to a $2,000
fine and a year in jail on the battery charge.
   The actress maintains she was roughed up unnecessarily during the
June 14 arrest and has threatened to sue the Police Department. She
is scheduled to appear in Municipal Court on July 12.
