<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 0154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChappaquiddickJurors     07-01 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chappaquiddick Jurors,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jurors Say They Were Held Back In Kennedy-Chappaquiddick Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 20 years after Sen. Edward Kennedy's car
plunged off the bridge at Chappaquiddick Island, several grand
jurors who investigated the accident have come forward to say the
district attorney hindered their probe.
   One of the jurors, Robert E. Maciel, said Friday that there was a
``cover up'' in the case, but said he believed Kennedy was the
victim, not the perpetrator.
   ``I think the man is innocent,'' Maciel said. ``I don't believe
Kennedy was driving that car. I think he took the blame for somebody
else.''
   Mary Jo Kopechne, a 28-year-old secretary, was a passenger in
Kennedy's Oldsmobile when it skidded off Dike Bridge in Martha's
Vineyard on July 19, 1969. Trapped in the vehicle, she drowned in 8
feet of water in a tidal pond.
   The Massachusetts Democrat, who did not report the accident to
police until 10 hours later, received a suspended sentence for
leaving the scene.
   Maciel and the grand jury foreman, Leslie H. Leland, said former
District Attorney Edmund Dinis prevented the 23-member jury from
calling several key witnesses, including Kennedy and his cousin,
Joseph Gargan Jr., because they had previously testified at an
inquest.
   Leland, a 49-year-old pharmacist on Martha's Vineyard, said
Dinis, the Dukes County prosecutor, also refused to let the grand
jury read the transcript of the inquest.
   ``When those two avenues were closed off, there was nothing for
us to do really but go home,'' Leland said.
   Dinis, who is now in private practice in New Bedford, did not
return telephone calls from The Associated Press to his home and
office Friday.
   He previously has denied stonewalling the investigation and has
said there was not enough evidence to justify indicting Kennedy for
manslaughter.
   Leland and Maciel said they have spoken out after two decades
because they want the truth to come out and to clear the grand
jury's name.
   ``I've lived with this thing for 20 years, and there have been
all these innuendos that we were bought off,'' Leland said. ``The
bottom line is, the grand jury tried its hardest to get to the
truth, but we were not able to do our job.''
   Kennedy has said he made a wrong turn that night and ended up on
the narrow Dike Bridge. He also has said that he and a friend
repeatedly dove to the car in unsuccessful rescue attempts, and that
afterward he was ``exhausted and in a state of shock.''
   Maciel, who owns a boatyard on Martha's Vineyard, said he did not
believe that Kennedy, a frequent visitor to the island, would have
made that wrong turn. He said he did not know why Kennedy would have
taken the blame for someone else, ``unless it was someone very
young.''
   The Standard Times of New Bedford also reported Friday that
several other jurors have backed statements by Leland criticizing
the investigation.
   ``It was a coverup,'' said Lloyd Mayhew, a grand juror now living
in Mattapoisett. ``I support every single word Mr. Leland said.
Everybody covered for Kennedy.''
   Leland was quoted in the July 3 issue of Newsweek as saying that
two unidentified ``key lawmen'' took him for a ride and told him
there was no need for a thorough investigation.
   He said Friday he stood by that account.
   Helen Mosher, a Tisbury housewife, told the New Bedford newspaper
that the jury experience left her ``disgusted.''
   ``What took place, took place, but it should've been handled
differently,'' she said. ``I got a lot of questions from people, but
I'd say nothing. People said `you got paid off' and all that, but I
let it go over my head.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890701-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 0219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HUD-Probe Bjt   07-01 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Probe, Bjt,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inspector General Says HUD Ignored Warnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban
Development's inspector general says the agency ignored repeated
warnings for tighter controls on lenders in a troubled program now
under House investigation.
   ``On at least five occasions ... we have reported to HUD
management and to Congress that program improvements were needed,''
said HUD Inspector General Paul A. Adams as the House Government
Operations housing and employment subcommittee began hearings Friday
on the program.
   The program, known as ``coinsurance'' because the government
assumed part of the liability on loans with lenders, showed signs of
problems two years after it was instituted in 1983 as a hallmark of
Reagan administration efforts to turn the functions of many
government programs over to private business.
   A November 1985 internal audit of eight projects showed
``inappropriate lender underwriting practices caused inflated
mortgages,'' Adams said.
   The subcommittee has been examining possible abuse,
influence-peddling and mismanagement in HUD programs during the
Reagan administration.
   HUD officials promised to ``improve lender monitoring processes
and enforcement actions,'' although they rejected Adams' assessment
of the problems and said controls he suggested were so strict they
would discourage participation, he said.
   Lenders are paid an annual fee of about 4 percent of a project's
operating income as an incentive to repair, rehabilitate or build
low- and moderate-income multi-family housing.
   If a borrower defaults, lenders are responsible for about 20
percent of the loss while HUD picks up the tab for the remaining 80
percent.
   HUD now faces more than $100 million in claims against bad loans
made in the program, said Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., subcommittee
chairman.
   In the most recent audit in March 1989, Adams found the Benton
Mortgage Company of Knoxville, Tenn., had misrepresented mortgage
amounts and rents on 14 projects it had underwritten, creating an
estimated $22 million in excessive mortgages, said Adams.
   He said the government would pay excessive subsidies of $37
million over the 15-year period of contracts for rental housing
Benton had coinsured.
   Benton is one of three companies which has been placed on six
months' probation from the program. Three companies have been
suspended and three others are under review by HUD, Adams said.
   Adams revealed Friday that Benton is the subject of a grand jury
investigation, which he said he would not discuss.
   Adams said his first report of problems in the coinsurance
program was sent to then-Assistant Secretary of Housing Phil Abrams,
one of several former HUD employees who was paid as a consultant on
projects funded under the moderate rehabilitation program.
   Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn., observed that ``Abrams used Benton
in all of his deals,'' in that program.
   Meanwhile, congressional pressure is mounting for a complete
review of the housing department.
   One staffer said Senate Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs
Committee Chairman Donald Riegle, D-Mich., has sent a letter to
panel members seeking authorization for an investigation.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., chairman of the Banking, Housing
and Urban Affairs subcommittee on housing, said Friday he would vote
for a probe of the ``scandal-ridden'' department.
   And House Banking Committee Chairman Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas,
said HUD Secretary Jack Kemp would testify before his panel July 12
to discuss reform measures being developed in the agency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890701-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 0222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SpacePlane     07-01 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Plane,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Space Council: Don't Kill Space-Plane Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Space Council has decided to urge
President Bush to keep the ``space plane'' alive but limit its
development program to the testing of unproven technology.
   The program is aimed at the development of a plane capable of
taking off from a conventional runway, going into orbit and landing
on a regular runway.
   President Reagan called it the ``Tokyo Express'' for the
projected two-hour flight time from New York to Tokyo.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney proposed eliminating the project or
transferring to the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
most of the $427 million proposed by Reagan in the Pentagon budget
for the next fiscal year.
   The council recommended the project get $254 million next year,
shared equally by NASA and the Defense Department, The Washington
Post said in its Saturday editions. A spokesman for Vice President
Dan Quayle, chairman of the council, said Friday night he did not
have dollar figures for the recommendations.
   The Senate Armed Services Committee recommended $412 million,
with $127 million from NASA.
   A council staff member who spoke on condition of anonymity said
the program's focus had expanded over the past four years, so that
nuts-and-bolts questions like payload were being considered before
researchers had proven with an experimental craft that the plane
would be able to fly at 25 times the speed of sound.
   Nearly $2 billion has been spent on the program over the past
four years. Potential contractors have spent $700 million of their
own funds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890701-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 0223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-PentagonReorganization     07-01 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon Reorganization,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney to Overhaul Pentagon Bureaucracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney is proposing a
broad overhaul of top Pentagon committees that would give a small
group the power to make major decisions, according to an
administration source.
   Cheney, responding to President Bush's request for a review of
defense management, recently sent the White House a proposal to form
an ``Executive Committee'' that would assume many of the powers of
the current Defense Resources Board, the source told The Associated
Press late Friday.
   ``We are waiting for the president's decisions,'' the source said.
   The Defense Resources Board, which advises Cheney on major
weapons and budgetary decisions, would become the Defense Planning
and Resources Board with a broader planning task.
   It would be subordinate to the Executive Committee, which would
be comprised of the secretary, the deputy secretary, the
undersecretary for policy, the undersecretary for acquisitions, the
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and the secretaries of the
Army, Navy and Air Force.
   ``These are the people who are setting the policy anyway,'' said
the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Cheney also would reorganize the Defense Acquisitions Board in an
effort to ``streamline the lines of authority in procurement in
carrying out acquisition policies down through the service
acquisition chiefs and program managers,'' the source said.
   The acquisitions board would scrutinize the cost and performance
tradeoff decisions made in the early stages of a weapons program.
   The service secretaries would be dropped from the acquisitions
board, ``cut out of the loop, but at the same time they would be put
back in at the top'' through membership on the Executive Committee,
the source said.
   The source largely confirmed an account of Cheney's plans first
reported Friday night by Defense News, a weekly journal of defense
policy and politics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
