<FIRST>r w PM-US-PLO     07-01 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-PLO,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Hopes Tunis Talks Will Lead to PLO Help With Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration says it is looking for
help from the Palestine Liberation Organization in holding elections
on the West Bank and Gaza.
   ``If they can be responsible and constructive here in helping,
great,'' Margaret Tutwiler, the State Department spokeswoman, said
Friday while defending two unannounced meetings in Tunis with Salah
Khalaf, the second-in-command to PLO chairman Yasser Arafat.
   But supporters of Israel accelerated their criticism of the
expanded dialogue U.S. Ambassador Robert Pelletreau is having in
Tunisia with PLO officials.
   Thomas A. Dine, executive director of the American Israel Public
Affairs Committee, said ``we are deeply distressed to learn that the
administration has conducted secret meetings with the founder of
Black September, one of the most brutal terrorists of recent years.''
   Dine said in a statement that Khalaf, known also as Abu Iyad,
``has publicly boasted of his terrorist deeds against Americans and
Israelis and bragged about his ability to deceive the United
States.''
   The head of the pro-Israel lobbying and research group called the
meetings in Tunis ``a blow to the confidence necessary to move the
peace process forward.''
   Seymour D. Reich, chairman of the Conference of Presidents of
Major American Jewish Organizations, called Khalaf a ``notorious
terrorist'' and said bringing him into the talks ``can only breed
mistrust and cast suspicion on the depth of our country's
longstanding commitments to Israel.''
   On Thursday, Israeli Ambassador Moshe Arad, registered his
government's regret and disappointment in a meeting with Assistant
Secretary of State John Kelly. Arad told the U.S. specialist on the
Middle East the meetings hurt prospects for holding the elections.
   The elections were proposed by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir and endorsed by President Bush and Secretary of State James
A. Baker III as a way of getting peace talks started.
   The idea is to have the 1.4 million Palestinian Arabs living
under Israeli control on the West Bank and in Gaza choose leaders
who would negotiate temporary and local self-rule. Israel, the
Palestinians, Egypt and Jordan would negotiate a permanent
settlement in a second stage of talks.
   The PLO has publicly criticized the plan as a device to prevent
creation of a Palestinian state.
   Spokeswoman Tutwiler claimed only limited progress in the talks.
``I have no reason to believe that it has not been constructive,''
she said.
   The U.S. official said Pelletreau had held several unannounced
meetings with various PLO officials and was likely to hold others.
   ``Our objective in the dialogue is to advance the peace process
and to underscore our expectation that the PLO will adhere to its
renunciation of terrorism,'' she said.
</TEXT>
