<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 0231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-GenericDrug     07-01 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Generic Drug,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Maker Says Product Safe Despite Lack of Full Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York pharmaceutical company says its
employees appear to have won government approval for one of the
firm's generic drugs for treating high blood pressure by
substituting the brandname product for its own in comparison tests.
   ``It would appear that that is the case,'' Roger W. Jordan,
president of Vitarine Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Springfield Gardens,
N.Y., said Friday.
   Jordan said he believes the company's drug, which has been
recalled, is safe.
   A congressman, however, said the case raises questions about the
drug's safety as well as the government's drug approval process.
   The drug is a generic Dyazide, a widely prescribed treatment for
high blood pressure. SmithKline Beckman Corp. of Philadelphia
developed Dyazide and marketed it for 20 years before the first
generic version was approved two years ago. Vitarine was approved in
February 1988.
   Vitarine recalled its product a month ago. At least three
employees have been suspended, the company said.
   However, Jordan said, preliminary results of a just-completed
comparison study measuring the rate and extent of absorption of the
two drugs shows that Vitarine's product falls within an ``acceptable
range.''
   ``Vitarine has no reason to expect any safety or efficacy
problems with this product. Vitarine has produced millions of dosage
units since the product was first introduced in February 1988 and as
of this date has received only six adverse experience reports,'' he
said.
   Jordan declined to elaborate on the findings of the company's
internal investigation, except to confirm that the company told the
FDA it suspected Dyazide was substituted for Vitarine's product in
comparison tests. As a result, Dyazide would have been tested
against only another sample of Dyazide.
   The chairman of the House Energy and Commerce investigations
subcommittee, which brought the possibility to public light
Thursday, said the case raises questions about how the FDA approves
generic drugs.
   ``Events suggest that we can no longer be assured that the
products tested are the products marketed,'' said Rep. John Dingell,
D-Mich., subcommittee chairman.
   ``That such a simple but apparently effective fraud could have
gone undetected raises some serious new questions about the safety
and efficacy of these drugs, and about the law,'' he said.
   The FDA acknowledged that it is investigating the company, but
spokesman Jeff Nesbit said he couldn't comment on the inquiry or
address the safety of the Vitarine drug.
   An FDA source, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said the
agency doubted the generic version was unsafe because it had
undergone other tests and no problems with people using it had been
reported.
</TEXT>
