<FIRST>r w PM-SexScandal     07-01 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sex Scandal,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged White House Tour for Male Prostitutes is Focus in Sex Ring
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Secret Service does not know who authorized
a private White House tour allegedly given to members of a
homosexual prostitution ring now under federal investigation, a
spokesman says.
   The focus on private White House tours came after The Washington
Times reported that prominent Washington lobbyist Craig J. Spence
arranged tours of the White House _ once around midnight _ for
friends and business associates.
   The paper reported in its Friday editions that one such group
included two male prostitutes from escort services that are now the
subject of an investigation by U.S. Attorney Jay Stephens.
   Secret Service spokesman Allan Cramer said Friday that staffers
holding White House passes can escort guests through the West Wing,
site of the Oval Office, at special times. But he said records from
the Reagan administration, when the tour in question allegedly
occurred, are no longer available.
   One unidentified man quoted by the Times recalled a tour late on
the night of July 3, 1988.
   Cramer said the Secret Service did not know who vouched for the
party that night because all White House records from the period,
including visitors' logs, have been shipped to California for
eventual placement in the Ronald Reagan library, which has yet to be
constructed.
   The Times said credit card records it obtained show that Spence
frequently patronized a homosexual prostitution network that ran the
escort services.
   Spence, once a registered foreign agent for Japan, is known as a
Washington power-broker whose parties during the Reagan
administration attracted prominent individuals including former CIA
Director William Casey, journalist Ted Koppel and James Lilley, the
ambassador to China.
   Stephens and the Secret Service confirmed Thursday they are
investigating possible credit card fraud involving the escort
services, which operated under names such as ``Dream Boys'' and
``Man to Man.''
   The investigation is based on records seized in raids on a house
in an upscale Washington neighborhood that police say was used by
the services. Police seized numerous bank statements, credit card
slips and a diary of the business.
   The Times reported the ring was patronized by Reagan and Bush
administration officials and congressional aides. Paul R. Balach
resigned his job as Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole's political
personnel liaison to the White House on Thursday after his name
appeared in the Times' original story on the investigation.
   Spence spent thousands of dollars on the escort services, the
Times said. On Oct. 5, 1988, for instance, he made four separate
payments totaling $1,525 with his American Express card for male
escorts from Professional Services Inc., it said.
   In the Bush administration, White House staff members can bring
guests on private tours of the West Wing on Monday, Wednesday and
Friday between 7 p.m. and 10 p.m., after 1 p.m. on Saturday and all
day on Sunday, Cramer said.
   Before a guest is cleared into the White House compound, a staff
member must provide agents with information such as a date of birth
and Social Security number.
</TEXT>
