<FIRST>r w PM-North-Juror     07-01 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North-Juror,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge's Ruling Leaves North Sentencing Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has cleared the way for Oliver
North's sentencing next Wednesday in the Iran-Contra scandal.
   North, facing up to 10 years in prison and $750,000 in fines,
lost a bid for a mistrial Friday.
   U.S. District Court Judge Gerhard Gesell said no evidence existed
that a juror who gave the court inaccurate information was biased
against the former White House aide.
   Juror Tara Leigh King responded `no'' last Feb. 1 when asked
whether she or relatives had been involved in court proceedings or
an investigation.
   North's lawyers disclosed after his trial that one of King's
brothers had served time in prison for armed robbery and that the
woman had testified before a grand jury in connection with the
criminal investigation of her brother.
   She testified Wednesday she forgot about the episode when she
answered the courtroom questionnaire Feb. 1. Gesell said in a
nine-page order that King's testimony probably wasn't believable,
but that it didn't matter in deciding whether she was biased against
North.
   ``The court cannot credit King's testimony ... Her omission was
knowing, but she had no desire to help or to hurt North or the
prosecution,'' Gesell said in a nine-page order.
   `No proof was presented indicating that King was unfair or that
she failed in any way to serve conscientiously,'' he added.
   North was convicted May 4 for aiding and abetting an obstruction
of Congress, altering and destroying documents and illegally
accepting a gratuity.
   North had moved for the mistrial, saying King was prejudiced
against North.
   `She voted to acquit North of many felony counts,'' Gesell said
of King.
   North was acquitted on nine other charges.
   The judge said that embarrassment and a desire to serve on the
jury, rather than forgetfulness, were the reasons King failed to
disclose the background information last February.
   North's lawyers hired a private detective agency to investigate
her background after she told a television interviewer she had used
drugs, adding that she had stopped months before North's trial.
   ``Situations of this type arise with some frequency in cases when
the defense has ample resources,'' said the judge. ``They must be
resolved in favor of the verdict when bias against the defendant has
not been established in fact or by implication.''
</TEXT>
