<FIRST>r a PM-LukensSentencing     07-01 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lukens Sentencing,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Sentenced In Sex Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Donald E. Lukens is confident of
winning an appeal despite receiving a 30-day jail term for having
sex with a 16-year-old girl, an aide said.
   The 58-year-old Republican was freed on a $100,000 surety bond
Friday.
   Franklin County Domestic Relations Court Judge Ronald Solove
sentenced Lukens to the maximum penalty on the misdemeanor charge of
contributing to the unruliness of a child, but overturned Lukens'
conviction of contributing to the delinquency of a minor.
   William Jarrell, Lukens' chief of staff, said in an interview
from Washington that the dropping of the delinquency charge was a
``very good sign for our appeal.''
   Solove, citing Lukens' apparent lack of remorse, told the
congressman he was ``convinced you are a sex offender.''
   The court was ``struck by the unwillingness of the defendant to
recognize that he was not the victim,'' Solove said. ``You have
refused to take that degree of responsibility.''
   Lukens, who is divorced, was convicted May 26 for paying Rosie
Coffman $40 to have sex with him at his Columbus apartment on Nov. 6.
   Solove sentenced him to 180 days in jail and a $1,000 fine, but
suspended all but 30 days of the sentence and $500 of the fine.
Lukens was placed on probation for one year.
   Solove said the suspended sentence and fine depend on whether
Lukens follows terms of his probation, which require him to
participate in sex offender programs and submit to testing for
sexually transmitted diseases.
   Lukens left the courtroom without commenting to reporters. But
Jarrell said the congressman had no need to show remorse.
   ``When Congressman Lukens' conviction is overturned at the
appeals level, Judge Solove will then understand why he showed no
remorse. He is innocent,'' he said.
   Mrs. Coffman, whose complaint about Lukens led to his indictment,
was escorted from the room immediately after the hearing. She is
serving a jail term for violating probation stemming from a 1983
drunken driving conviction.
   Conviction on a misdemeanor does not automatically bar Lukens
from Congress. He has vowed to remain in office and pursue his
appeal.
   Local Republicans have called for Lukens to resign, and the House
Ethics Committee has been asked to investigate the case.
   Lukens served two terms in Congress from 1967 to 1970, when he
lost a bid for the GOP gubernatorial nomination. After 15 years in
the Ohio Senate, he was returned to Congress by voters in 1986.
</TEXT>
