<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionConvention     07-01 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Convention,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Action Urged Against Growing Acceptance of Euthanasia ^With PM-Abortion
Consent, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARREN MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Right to Life Committee's
convention turned its aim from abortion to euthanasia, and members
were urged to fight what one speaker called ``institutionalized
heartlessness.''
   ``Euthanasia is a clear and present danger in America,'' James
Bopp Jr., general counsel of the committee, said Friday on the
second day of the group's annual convention.
   Many who have strong convictions that abortion is wrong haven't
taken such a firm stand on euthanasia, said John Dolan, a member of
the steering committee of the University of Minnesota's Program in
Human Rights and Medicine.
   ``We have to protect the elderly and disabled as we would protect
ourselves,'' Dolan said.
   ``There is a movement toward institutionalized heartlessness,
contempt and disdain for caring. Euthanasia is the necessary
terminus of this movement,'' he said. ``People have died of
deliberate dehydration. The patients did not ask to be starved to
death and were not terminally ill.''
   Dr. Allen Jay argued that artificial administration of nutrition
and hydration is not the same as using extraordinary medical means
to keep a patient alive. The San Diego physician gained national
attention when he refused a court order to withhold food and water
from a 92-year-old Alzheimer's patient whose daughter wanted to end
her life.
   Jay said it was important that physicians know they have the
right to follow their moral and ethical conscience.
   ``Having a physician's role in society defined by legislators or
attorneys is a terrible, terrible thing,'' he said. ``We are all
responsible for our own actions regarding our own conscience.''
   David N. O'Steen, the committee's executive director, urged
members to oppose euthanasia as strongly as they do abortion.
   Withholding artificial administration of food and water ``is
really starving people to death,'' said O'Steen. The logical next
step would be lethal injection, he maintained.
   ``When we come to this point, it will be too late,'' he said.
``The time to act is now because society at large has not yet
accepted the stark reality of what is being done.''
</TEXT>
