<FIRST>u i BC-China-Tiananmen     07-01 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Tiananmen,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tiananmen Square Re-Opens to Tourists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tiananmen Square re-opened to the public Saturday,
nearly four weeks after army tanks rolled into the vast grounds in a
bloody suppression of China's pro-democracy movement.
   Hundreds of people who had obtained special permission filed
through the square in orderly lines, gazing at the Forbidden City's
Gate of Heavenly Peace and the few soldiers who patrol the square.
   Hundreds of cheerful tourists also gathered on the rostrum above
the gate itself, where China's revolutionary founder, Mao Tse-tung,
declared the founding of the People's Republic four decades ago.
   There was no sign of the terror and grief that engulfed Tiananmen
June 3-4, when the People's Liberation Army stormed the square,
shooting its way through hundreds of thousands of unarmed protesters.
   The government says about 300 people were killed, half of them
soldiers. Chinese witnesses and Western diplomats say the deaths
were in the thousands.
   Chinese tourists paid 10 yuan ($2.70), two days' wages for many
workers, to stand atop the gate, which along with the square was
re-opened to mark Saturday's 68th anniversary of the founding of the
Communist Party of China.
   Many enthusiastically snapped photographs and sought autographs
from a senior military commander and a deputy mayor of Beijing.
   Groups of a dozen soldiers armed with AK-47 rifles marched by the
gate every minute.
   Tiananmen opened a day after former Communist Party chief Zhao
Ziyang was stripped of his last government title.
   Zhao, ousted as party general secretary a week ago, was dismissed
by senior leader Deng Xiaoping as vice chairman of the State Central
Military Commission. Deng is chairman of the commission.
   Zhao was effectively ousted more than a month ago, after he paid
a tearful visit on May 19 to students on a hunger strike in
Tiananmen. He has not been seen since.
   President Yang Shangkun, who spent his career in the military,
reportedly was seeking to replace Zhao on the commission. The
commission's senior vice chairman is second only to Deng in the
government's military command hierarchy.
</TEXT>
