<FIRST>r a PM-StatenIsland     07-01 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Staten Island,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Legislature Lets Staten Island Vote on Secession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York state's Legislature voted today to
let Staten Island residents vote on whether they want to secede from
New York City and form their own government.
   Residents of the smallest of New York City's five boroughs can
vote in November 1990 if the bill is signed by Gov. Mario Cuomo.
   The bill allowing the secession vote passed the state Assembly
early today by a 116-22 vote after passing the state Senate.
   Cuomo has not indicated how he will act on the measure, said his
spokesman, Gary Fryer.
   The secession movement gathered force earlier this year after the
U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the city's Board of Estimate was
unconstitutional because it gave Staten Island, with fewer than
400,000 residents, equal representation with Brooklyn, the most
populous borough with more than 2.2 million residents.
   The restructuring being prepared under the ruling could diminish
Staten Island's voice in city government.
   The other New York boroughs are Manhattan, Queens, and the Bronx.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
