<FIRST>r a PM-ChurchClosings     07-01 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church Closings,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reverend Celebrates Last Mass Because of Church Closings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY L. ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest who celebrated his last
Mass as an inner-city pastor said he saw a new beginning in the
merger of his church with another one closed by the Detroit
Archdiocese.
   Rev. Edward J. Farrell is losing his post at St. Agnes Church
because it is merging with St. Theresa, a 300-member parish two
miles away. St. Theresa closed its doors Friday, the 17th church to
shut down as part of the Archdiocese's plan to close 30 inner-city
churches.
   Farrell ended his 12-year pastoral duties at St. Agnes Friday
amid tears of joy and sorrow from about 20 parishioners. Although he
said he was sorry to leave, Farrell said he was encouraged about the
new start for the church, founded in 1914.
   ``Today's mass was a joyful occasion,'' said Farrell, who will
become a director at the Institute of Ministry at the nearby Sacred
Heart Seminary. ``It is an ending and a new beginning for all.''
   The new parish, as yet unnamed, will celebrate its first joint
Mass Sunday.
   At least one parishioner was angry.
   ``I disagree strongly with the closings, and especially with the
way it's being handled,'' said Patricia Dorsey, a parishioner for 5
years. ``The Roman Catholic Church needs smaller bases such as this
one to have a greater affect on the surrounding community.''
   Dorsey was among the throng of Catholics who packed a courtroom
Wednesday when Circuit Judge James Hathaway refused to block the
closings. The group took its plea for an injunction to the state
Appeals Court on Friday. The court isn't expected to rule before the
middle of next week.
   Ernie Haywood said the merger will allow the parish to survive on
its own collections.
   ``We have been depending on the cardinal to keep the doors to our
church open, now we can become a viable part of the community,''
said Haywood.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
