<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 0425EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos     07-01 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dialysis Machine Keeps Marcos Alive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand Marcos' fever has subsided but doctors
say they can't tell yet whether his condition has improved after an
operation to remove his transplanted kidney.
   The former Philippines president was being kept alive by daily
dialysis treatments, which do the job of his failed kidneys and
extract waste from the blood, Eugene Tiwanak, assistant
administrator at St. Francis Medical Center, said Friday.
   The operation was performed Thursday because doctors believed
Marcos' life-threatening fever of up to 104 degrees was caused by
his body's rejection of the donated kidney he received in 1984.
   Marcos' temperature subsided to around 100 degrees, but he
remained semicomatose and was unable to recognize people, Tiwanak
said.
   ``The doctors feel it's too soon to say there has been an overall
improvement in his condition as a result of the surgery,'' said
Tiwanak. Marcos was still in very critical condition and the
prognosis remained poor, he said.
   Earlier, Marcos spokesman Roger Peyuan said three doctors told
Imelda Marcos her husband was slightly better following surgery.
   ``He's a little better. Just so-so. Still very critical,'' Mrs.
Marcos said as she left the hospital early Friday morning.
   But she was unresponsive to reporters when she returned to the
hospital Friday night. When asked how her husband was doing, Mrs.
Marcos said she was at the hospital to sign a release for Marcos'
medication.
   Tiwanak said Marcos could survive indefinitely with the use of a
dialysis machine. Marcos also was hooked up to a resirator and other
life-support equipment, Tiwanak said.
   Marcos suffered liver failure Wednesday, and suffered heart, lung
and kidney failure in May. He has remained in the hospital since
being admitted Jan. 15.
   One of Marcos' doctors, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said the exiled leader's condition has generally worsened over the
past five months.
   ``It's like a stair step,'' the doctor said. ``He gets worse,
levels off, gets worse and levels offs, but sooner or later he'll
fall off the steps.''
   Another doctor, also speaking on the condition of anonymity,
called Marcos' survival remarkable.
   ``He really does have a tremendous will to live,'' the doctor
said. ``I can honestly say that just about any other person in his
condition would have been dead months ago. There's no real
explanation.''
   The Marcoses were indicted in New York last year on federal
racketeering charges. They stand accused of stealing more than $100
million from their homeland to buy art and real estate in Manhattan.
   Marcos' illness has led him to be separated from the case. Mrs.
Marcos is free on $5 million bail.
   The couple fled here in 1986 when a popular revolt swept Corazon
Aquino into the presidency. She has refused Marcos' many requests
for permission to return home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890701-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 0423EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LeninLibrary 1stLd-Writethru a0436 07-01 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lenin Library, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0436,0732</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virginia Company Computerizing Lenin Library In Moscow</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Chachra's company..', to UPDATE with name of
library director; picks up 5th graf, `The work...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet citizens looking for books at the
Moscow library where Lenin, Dostoyevsky and Chekhov once studied
will soon be using computers programmed at a Virginia university.
   Virginia Tech Library Systems President Vinod Chachra sees it as
more than a technical challenge to computerize the card catologue of
the massive Lenin Library. The project will encourage the Soviet
policy of openness, or glasnost, and help further business relations
between the superpowers, he says.
   ``This is really opening up access to information,'' Chachra
said. ``In one sense, this is bringing in more equality with the
technology. By automating the system, it greatly increases the
access to all people.''
   Chachra's company, which is controlled by a non-profit arm of
Virginia Tech, announced last month that the Soviets had chosen its
software system to automate their national library. Chachra will
meet with the library's director, Nikolai Semyonovich Kartashov, in
Blacksburg on July 18 to discuss the start of the project in
November.
   The work is expected to take up to four years and cost $1
million, he said.
   The Lenin Library, located just off Red Square, has 35 million
books in 247 languages and 3,000 employees. Its 18 reading rooms,
many of them with ornate, high ceilings and lit by chandeliers, seat
more than 2,300 people and are visited by more than 7,000 readers
each day.
   In comparison, the Library of Congress in Washington has 26
million books and the New York Public Library has 6 million books,
Chachra said.
   The library was founded in 1862 as the Rumiantsev Library, named
after a count whose collection accounted for most of its original
holdings. It was renamed in 1925 after the father of the Russian
revolution.
   In addition to Lenin, famous Russians who have studied in the
library include authors Leo Tolstoy, Fyodor Dostoyevsky and Anton
Chekhov.
   Chachra visited the library during a recent five-day trip to
Moscow.
   ``I was struck by the number of people waiting outside the door
for the library to open,'' he said. ``There aren't that many
libraries in the Soviet Union. The users are dedicated.''
   They have to be. Checking out a book is a lengthy and frustrating
process, and just finding the right card catalog file is an ordeal
because there are separate catalogs for various subcollections,
Chachra said.
   After finding the right catalogue, the user must write the title
and author on a slip of paper and stand in line for up to an hour to
give the note to a circulation clerk. The clerk sends the note to
the book retrieval area via pneumatic tubes.
   ``It can take anywhere from a half a day to five days to get a
book,'' Chachra said. ``Occasionally, the book has been lent to
someone else, and after waiting that long you find out you can't get
it anyway.''
   Under the planned automated system, people looking for a book
will step up to a U.S.-made computer running on software designed by
Chachra and his staff. For many, it will be their first experience
with a personal computer, Chachra said.
   Users will be able to make a book request directly from a
terminal and find out right away whether the book is checked out,
Chachra said.
   The current system restricts access to information because of its
cumbersome nature, Chachra said, but that will change.
   ``By the nature of the technology, it will be in favor of the
user,'' he said. ``The software is designed for open access.''
   Chachra said it remains to be seen whether Soviet officials will
give access to some books that are now off limits to users,
presumably for political reasons.
   The Lenin Library will be the first Soviet library to
computerize, but it will be the sixth national library to automate
with software from Virginia Tech Library Systems. The company has
computerized the National Gallery of Art Library and the National
Agricultural Library in the United States, as well as libraries in
Scotland, Malaysia and Finland.
   The company has computerized nearly 100 other libraries,
including that of the U.S. Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890701-0035 </DOCNO>
