<FIRST>r a PM-ChineseFugitive     07-01 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chinese Fugitive,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Wanted in China Says He'll Work for Democracy in Exile</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALTHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shen Tong, one of the student leaders being
sought by Chinese authorities for their part in the pro-democracy
movement, says he intends to carry on fighting for democratic
reforms in exile.
   ``This movement for democracy has won a complete victory,'' said
Shen, 20, who escaped China and landed in this country June 11.
``It's a grand scale self-education of what democracy really is. ...
The seeds of democracy have been sown.''
   The lanky, self-assured fugitive, who is now studying biology at
Brandeis University, broke a self-imposed silence Friday and gave an
interview before holding a press conference in which he declared the
Chinese student movement victorious.
   Shen was among five executive members of an organizing committee
for the April 27 demonstration at Beijing University, where he was a
student. The demonstration was staged in response to a critical
editorial the previous day in The People's Daily.
   Shen was also a founder and leader of the Beijing Area Colleges'
Dialogue Delegation, which tried unsuccessfully to negotiate with
Chinese Premier Li Peng on May 18 on conditions for the students to
leave the square they occupied for weeks until troops moved in.
   He was about one mile from Tiananmen Square June 4, the day
Chinese troops bore down with tanks and guns on the demonstrators.
Although the protest focused on the square, the killing of thousands
occurred throughout the streets of the city, Shen said.
   Men standing beside him were shot dead, one man through the head.
He saw tanks bearing down on an angry, disbelieving throng.
   ``Beijing people were very brave,'' Shen said. ``They didn't
leave the street but walked around the bodies and in front of the
soldiers. All of the soldiers were crazy, shooting people.''
   Shen escaped China under circumstances he refused to reveal.
   Several other leaders of the democracy movement escaped,
including Wu'er Kaixi, a top student leader; Yan Jiaqi and Su
Shaozhi, leading dissident intellectuals; and Wan Runnan, head of
China's first private high tech company, Stone Corp.
   Shen had already won a place as a Wien scholar at Brandeis before
the massacre.
   During the interview Friday, he wore a blood red T-shirt bearing
the black outline of the Goddess of Democracy, the plastic likeness
of the Statue of Liberty the student demonstrators erected in
Tiananmen Square.
   Shen said he intends to continue to work for the democratic
reform of his homeland.
   ``We have to try our best,'' Shen said. ``This movement is still
a movement.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
