<FIRST>r a PM-BusWreck     07-01 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Wreck,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Bus Involved in Wreck Was Speeding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARFIELD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chartered bus clipped the rear of a
tractor-trailer and overturned, injuring 42 passengers, police said.
   The bus, taking a New York church group to Disney World in
Orlando, Fla., hit the truck Friday afternoon while trying to pass
on Interstate 85, said state Trooper D.W. Ezell. The bus crossed the
lane, went off the shoulder and flipped on its side.
   ``It was scary,'' said passenger James Harrington, 16. ``We hit
the truck and the bus rocked this way, and that way, and then, bam,
we were over the side.''
   Ezell said the bus driver, Jesse Bookhart of Bloomfield, N.J.,
was charged with reckless driving.
   The bus, which had 47 people aboard, was traveling at 65 mph when
it hit the United Van Lines truck, the trooper said. The accident
occurred one day before the state raised the speed limit for buses
on rural interstates from 55 mph to 65 mph.
   A side of the bus was ripped open, and clothes and other personal
belongings were strewn along the highway. The interstate was closed
for about 3{ hours after the accident, which occurred about 50 miles
south of Richmond.
   All of the injured were taken to Community Memorial Hospital in
South Hill, said hospital administrator John M. Faulkner.
   Faulkner said one person was admitted to Community Memorial for
observation and three were transferred to the Medical College of
Virginia Hospital in Richmond for treatment of broken bones. The
others, who had injuries ranging from bloody noses to scrapes and
cuts, were treated and released.
   Bob Maslen of the Brunswick Volunteer Rescue Squad, who was on
the first of 10 ambulances that responded to the accident, said the
passengers ``had helped each other out of the bus. I think they were
worried about the fire hazard. They were helping each other. They
knew not to move the injured too much and were making shade.''
   The bus was one of two chartered buses that left Rush Temple
A.M.E. Zion Church in New York's Queens borough Friday morning, said
Dorothy Midgett, a passenger on the second bus that was about 20
minutes behind the vehicle that crashed.
   Officials were making arrangements for another bus for passengers
who wanted to continue the trip.
</TEXT>
