<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--Revlon-AnimalTesting     07-01 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Revlon-Animal Testing,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Revlon Joins Avon in Ending Cosmetics Testing On Animals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Revlon Inc. says it will no longer test its
cosmetics and other products on animals, joining Avon Products Inc.
in submitting to the wishes of animal rights groups.
   Revlon also said Friday that it will not contract with
independent laboratories that use animals to test product safety.
   Actress Doris Day, a leading animal rights activist, praised
Revlon's decision. Avon made similar concessions last week.
   ``This is so exciting. We are finally making major strides and
headway,'' Day said. ``I salute Revlon and some of the other
companies which have now adopted good alternatives and are saving
animals from needless pain and torture.''
   Revlon said that instead of animal testing it will rely on the
judgment of scientists to make sure its products meet government
regulations.
   Revlon said it already had sharply reduced its testing
requirements prior to the announcement.
</TEXT>
