<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     07-01 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Strike Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms moved across parts of Nebraska and Kansas
today, while heavy rains soaked parts of Texas and Florida.
   An upper air disturbance moving through the central Plains
produced thunderstorm winds gusting up to 66 mph at Goodland, Kan.
Winds from 70 to 80 mph were reported at Downs, Kan. A flash flood
watch was in effect for eastern and north-central Kansas.
   Golf ball-size hail fell from a thunderstorm near McCook, Neb.
   A cold front produced thunderstorms over the northern Rockies. In
Montana, dime-size hail pelted Superior and winds gusted to 62 mph
in the Polson area.
   Showers and thunderstorms continued from eastern Texas across
northern Louisiana and Arkansas into southern Missouri. The rain was
associated with a low pressure area over north-central Texas that
once was Tropical Storm Allison.
   More than 4 inches of rain fell across Grimes County, Texas,
early Friday evening, causing some creeks and streams to overflow.
   Flash flood watches were in effect across eastern Texas, western
Louisiana and southern Arkansas.
   Thunderstorms over the Florida Peninsula and the eastern Gulf
Coast also dumped heavy rain.
   Showers and thunderstorms were diminishing early today across
southeast Minnesota and west-central Wisconsin. An upper air low
pressure system off the northern Pacific Coast continued to produce
showers across the Pacific Northwest.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included nearly 2 inches at Tallahassee, Fla, 1} inches at Memphis
and 1\ inches at New Orleans.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms over
Florida, the southern Appalachians, much of the Gulf Coast, the
lower Mississippi Valley, the Tennessee Valley and the lower
Missouri Valley; and scattered showers across the northern Pacific
Coast and parts of northern New England.
   Highs were expected to be in the 60s and 70s over much of New
England, parts of the upper Mississippi Valley, parts of the
northern Rockies, the Pacific Northwest and along the California
coast; in the 90s over the central and southern Rockies, western
parts of the central and southern Plains and inland parts of
California; in the 100s from the Rio Grande Valley of Texas to the
desert Southwest; and in the 80s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 41
degrees at Houlton, Maine, to 94 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 73 foggy; Boston 65 partly cloudy; Buffalo 57
fair; Charleston, S.C. 69 fair; Cincinnati 67 fair; Cleveland 56
fair; Detroit 56 fair; Miami 74 partly cloudy; New York 66 fair;
Philadelphia 63 fair; Pittsburgh 60 fair; Portland, Maine 53 cloudy;
Washington 66 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 70 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 73 partly cloudy;
Denver 65 fair; Des Moines 70 fair; Indianapolis 63 partly cloudy;
Kansas City 73 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 67 fair; Nashville 72
cloudy; New Orleans 74 cloudy; St. Louis 76 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 75 fair; Anchorage 58 showers; Las Vegas 84
windy; Los Angeles 64 fair; Phoenix 94 fair; Salt Lake City 77 fair;
San Diego 65 fair; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle 55 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 64 fair; Toronto 63 fair.
