<FIRST>u i PM-Mexico-Elections     07-01 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Elections,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Elections in Michoacan to Test Mexico's Governing Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORELIA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party and its leftist opposition face an unusual test Sunday _
whether the Michoacan state legislative elections will be clean.
   The pre-election rhetoric has been harsh as both sides have
poured money and energy into the race in this western Mexico farming
state.
   The governing party, known by its Spanish initials PRI, has been
in power in Mexico for 60 years and has often been accused of
winning elections through fraud.
   The leftist Democratic Revolutionary Party, founded earlier this
year by native son Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, has been saying Sunday's
balloting will likely be rife with vote-tampering.
   ``The PRI and fraud are synonymous,'' Democratic Revolutionary
Sen. Roberto Robles Garnica told a news conference Friday.
   The state Electoral Commission, controlled by PRI, has called out
the army to guard the polls. Robles and other Democratic
Revolutionary leaders said the move is an attempt to intimidate
voters by ``fabricating a specter of violence.''
   However, top PRI officials say there may indeed be violence and
call the troop deployment a preventive measure. ``This isn't a
ghost; it's reality,'' one of them, Jorge Medina Viedas, said in an
interview.
   In addition, legislative elections will be held Sunday in
Zacatecas, Chihuahua, Campeche, and Baja California state, which
will also elect a governor and mayors. Fair balloting is also at
issue in the other states.
   Much attention has focused on Michoacan, which is seen as a key
contest.
   In the last election in 1986, the PRI won 18 of 24 seats in
Michoacan's single-house legislature, and four small opposition
parties took the rest.
   But in July last year, Cardenas polled 64 percent of Michoacan's
vote in the presidential election, and his coalition's candidates
took both Senate seats and 12 of the state's 13 national Chamber of
Deputies from the PRI.
   Although Cardenas came in second behind President Carlos Salinas
de Gortari nationwide, it was a stunning blow for the PRI in the
state.
   In addition, Cardenas supporters mounted sit-ins last December at
about half the state's 113 city and town halls to demand the ouster
of Gov. Luis Martinez Villacana. They accused him of corruption.
   The protests prompted him to quit and take a job as director of
the Federal Toll Highways and Bridges Administration. Several PRI
mayors also resigned.
   The new governor, Genovevo Figuero Zamudio, issued a statement
Friday promising ``honest, free, clean and safe'' elections. He said
the party had overhauled its leadership and image.
   As part of that new image, the PRI for the first time put forward
candidates in open convention. However, they were then nominated by
party leaders behind closed doors.
   Despite PRI's efforts, opposition representatives are still
complaining of purported irregularities in voter registration rolls
and screening of poll watchers.
   The conservative National Action Party, weaker in this state, is
also fielding candidates.
   About 1.5 million voters are expected to cast ballots at 2,330
polling stations in this state from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. Sunday.
Official results are expected a week later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
