<FIRST>r a PM-HUD-CamdenProbe     07-01 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Camden Probe,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Probe Camden Housing Agency, Florio Camp Cries `Politics'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators are probing
allegations that a development agency used federal housing funds to
finance campaigns of local Democratic officials, a newspaper
reported.
   At least five federal investigators Thursday night searched the
home of Bernard C. Madrack, chief operating officer of the Greater
Camden Development Corp., and seized 34 boxes of records, The
Philadelphia Inquirer reported in today's editions.
   The now-disbanded corporation was a non-profit agency that
processed federal housing money from 1983 to 1986.
   Hours after subpoenas were issued Friday in the probe, Rep. James
Florio, the Democratic gubernatorial nominee, called for a speedy
investigation and suggested Republicans initiated the inquiry for
political purposes.
   Camden County is Florio's political base and the agency under
investigation was run by Democratic leaders with ties to Florio.
Madrack spent seven years on Florio's staff.
   County Freeholder Michael J. DiPiero, a Republican, prompted the
investigation by writing HUD Inspector General Paul Adams and
alleging widespread abuse of HUD funds and criminal activity at the
agency, the Inquirer reported.
   Investigators said Florio was not a target of the investigation
and there was no evidence of his personal involvement, The New York
Times reported in today's editions. The investigators said Florio's
political organization in Camden County and a number of his
associates are under scrutiny, the newspaper said.
   U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito said his office is probing various
HUD matters in New Jersey, but would not comment.
   Florio said he received a telephone call Friday evening from
Alito confirming the Camden probe, but said there were no individual
targets.
   The investigation comes as a congressional panel is looking into
possible influence peddling and misuse of funds at the Department of
Housing and Urban Development by prominent Republicans during the
Reagan administration.
   DiPiero and Michael Leonard, a former employee of the development
agency, told investigators at least $30,000 in federal money may
have been diverted to Democratic campaigns, the Inquirer reported,
citing unidentified officials familiar with the probe.
   DiPiero also told investigators some HUD money was used by agency
employees to buy cocaine, the Inquirer reported.
   The Times said investigators were probing allegations that money
was diverted to Democratic campaigns and used for personal reasons,
including vacations.
   Madrack's attorney, Charles N. Riley, said his client was told he
is not a target of the investigation. The documents were in his home
because he is their legal custodian, he said.
   Florio noted the disclosure of the Camden investigation followed
by days the resignations of two top advisers to the Republican
nominee for governor, Rep. Jim Courter, because of their ties to the
HUD scandal.
   The two events ``are so coincidental ... that I cannot help but
wonder if there are political motivations involved in the leaks,''
Florio said. He demanded federal officials determine how news of the
investigation was leaked.
   Political strategist Roger Stone stepped down from the Courter
campaign earlier this week after a partner in his firm, Black,
Manafort Stone and Kelly, acknowledged the firm received more than
$300,000 to obtain nearly $31 million in HUD funds for a Seabrook
housing project that was opposed by local officials.
   Media analyst Greg Stevens, who also resigned, has said he made a
telephone call to connect Stone's firm with state housing officials.
   Courter spokesman Gordon Hensley said the campaign was not
involved in starting the Camden investigation.
</TEXT>
