<FIRST>r i PM-PlaneUnlucky     07-01 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Unlucky,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Passengers Balk at Reboarding Problem-Filled Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of vacationers on a trip from
Britain to Hawaii endured hours of delay, a malfunction that forced
their plane to dump its fuel, an unscheduled stop and a fire on
their bus.
   Hot under the collar, 53 of them finally just said ``no'' and
refused to head for home Friday night on the same chartered plane
that spilled its fuel into the Pacific Ocean earlier this week.
   ``I value my life more than I want to get on that plane,'' said
Joanna Harris-Brown, a travel consultant from Liberpool, England.
   She was among 480 passengers on the U.S. Orion Airlines Boeing
747 that dumped fuel en route back to Manchester, England, and
landed Thursday night at the Edmonton International Airport after a
loss of oil pressure in the engines.
   On their way to the flight home Friday night, their bus caught
fire. A passing fire truck put out the blaze, which was blamed on a
leak of power-steering fluid.
   The mishap was another in a series of incidents and
inconveniences to plague the passengers from the moment they began
their trip two weeks ago.
   Before leaving Manchester, they were delayed more than an hour.
They waited 16 hours to board in Honolulu on the return flight.
   After the oil pressure problem forced the plane down, the
passengers once again waited five hours because they were told
customs officials had not arrived.
   Many were openly hostile when a representative for the British
consulate broke the news Friday night they would be leaving on the
same plane.
   ``It's been repaired four times by competent engineers, and it's
still not working,'' claimed passenger Malcolm Fletcher from
Birmingham, England.
   ``I'm frightened to take my 1-year-old son on the plane,'' he
said. ``We're going over the Atlantic next; that's what frightens
me.''
   The plane was scheduled to leave today with those passengers
willing to board.
</TEXT>
