<FIRST>r a PM-FlagBurner     07-01 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Burner,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Puerto Rican Nationalist Says Flag Decision Should Erase His Conviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jailed Puerto Rican nationalist has filed a
petition for freedom under a Supreme Court decision he claims
condones his burning of an American flag two years ago.
   In what may be the first direct result of last week's court
decision, Carlos Mendoza-Lugo, an inmate at the U.S. penitentiary in
Atlanta, filed a petition in federal court Friday demanding the
government show cause for keeping him in prison.
   Mendoza-Lugo burned a flag in front of a U.S. post office in
Puerto Rico in 1987, as a protest for Puerto Rican independence.
   ``It wasn't an act of vandalism; I was protesting,'' said
Mendoza-Lugo, 36. ``It's unconstitutional for me to be in jail when
I was making use of my freedom of speech.''
   A lawyer in the Supreme Court case said Mendoza-Lugo was the
first jailed flag-burner to seek freedom since the high court issued
the June 21 decision.
   ``This guy should not be in jail any longer if that's (flag
burning) the basis for his conviction,'' said lawyer David Cole, who
represented flag-burner Gregory Johnson in the Texas vs. Johnson
case.
   The Supreme Court ruled in favor of Johnson, saying the
Constitution's guarantee of free speech protects people who burn the
flag as a form of political protest.
   In response to the ruling, President Bush this week began
pressing for a constitutional amendment prohibiting desecration of
the American flag.
   The number of people in jail for flag-burning is so small that
the federal Bureau of Prisons doesn't keep statistics on it.
   Mendoza-Lugo pleaded guilty to flag desecration and began serving
a maximum one-year sentence last December. A staff member for the
Puerto Rican magistrate handling the case said Mendoza-Lugo's
sentence was shortened recently to seven months, making him eligible
for release this month.
</TEXT>
