<FIRST>r a PM-GangViolence     07-01 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gang Violence,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>235 Arrested On First Day Of Gang Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH COTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested more than 200 people on drug,
weapons and other charges in the year's first sweep of gang-infested
areas, and they promised to keep up the pressure over the holiday
weekend.
   The latest dragnet ``is to let the gang members know they are not
going to control the streets,'' said police Lt. Jim Tatreau, who
organized the eight-hour sweep that ended early today.
   Some 235 people, 136 of them reputed gang members, were arrested
during the sweep of the city's south side, said Teri Dixon, a police
analyst who recorded the arrests. The number far exceeded the 150
that Tatreau had projected.
   ``We expect tomorrow night to be even a little busier,'' Ms.
Dixon said. ``We'll see.''
   Forty-nine arrests were for felony narcotics violations and two
were for misdemeanor narcotics violations.
   Other arrests involved such things as weapons charges,
outstanding felony warrants and driving under the influence, Ms.
Dixon said.
   Portable booking trailers were set up at the Police Department's
Southeast Division station in the heart of the impoverished Watts
district, the site of deadly riots in 1965.
   The effort represented the first massive dragnet aimed at
drug-dealing street thugs since last summer's highly publicized
``Hammer'' sweeps, which also targeted the city's drug- and
gang-infested south side.
   The sweeps will resume again this evening and continue through
the holiday weekend, with police shifting their focus west toward
beach communities as the weekend progresses, officials said.
   ``Nice people will be going to the beach. We're trying to keep
the dirt bags away,'' said Detective Tony Celli.
   Despite last year's sweeps, the number of gang-related slayings
increased to 452 in Los Angeles County last year from 387 in 1987.
</TEXT>
