<FIRST>r a PM-OilSpillRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0448 07-01 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0448,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grounded Tanker Headed for Repairs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf to RESTORE first reference to Whitten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tanker that spilled 420,000 gallons
of heating oil into Narragansett Bay was released for repairs and
the ship's Greek captain was freed on $50,000 bail.
   Earlier Friday, a helmsman aboard the tanker told a federal
inquiry board he saw a warning buoy on the wrong side of the ship
before it ran aground, but he didn't warn the captain.
   The ship's chief mate praised the captain as one of the best to
work for and apologized for the spill, which scientists said caused
less environmental damage than first feared.
   Meanwhile, officials in New Jersey prepared to lift a state of
emergency on the oil-soiled Delaware River, where a tanker spilled
an estimated 300,000 gallons of heating oil after running aground
last weekend.
   In Providence, Federal Magistrate Jacob Hagopian late Friday
released the World Prodigy. Hagopian said his order would contain a
provision that the ship be towed.
   Lt. Paul Wolf said the Coast Guard expected to release the ship
today to New York Shipyard, which runs a yard in New York City.
Divers discovered the ship had a gash on either side, extending as
long as 200 feet down the 560-foot vessel.
   The magistrate also freed Captain Iakovos Georgudis, 43, after
the ship's owners wired $50,000 bail. Georgudis had been confined
aboard the ship and faces two misdemeanor charges he violated
pollution laws.
   Helmsman Konstadinos A. Paraskevopulos, speaking through an
interpreter, said he saw the red buoy marking the reef ``a little to
the left'' as the tanker headed into the harbor.
   Warning buoys should be kept on the right for ships entering a
harbor, but Paraskevopulos said nothing about warning the captain.
   Given the discipline on board the ship, ``The helmsman wouldn't
dare make any suggestion to the master,'' Coast Guard Capt. David H.
Whitten said.
   Human error was ``a pretty good conclusion,'' said Whitten, who
ran the board of inquiry with two National Transportation Safety
Board investigators.
   Whitten said it would be six months before he finished a final
report, and NTSB investigators said theirs could take as long as
nine months. Whitten said the biggest gap was lack of testimony from
the captain.
   Testimony at the hearing showed that harbor pilots often board
ships well past the point where state law requires them to board.
   The chief mate, Georgios Vlahos, showed investigators a symbol on
a British chart that corresponded to a pick-up point for harbor
pilots that was inside the line set by the state. The World Prodigy
was well inside that line and had no pilot on board when it grounded.
   Vlahos also apologized for the accident.
   ``I am very sorry for this happening. I don't know what else to
say. I think it was a very bad time and all else is in your hands,''
he told the board.
   Paraskevopulos said the captain was tied up with radio traffic to
the harbor pilot just before the grounding.
   The two men testified under federal immunity. Vlahos also
testified before a grand jury investigating possible violations of
the state's harbor pilot and pollution laws.
   State, federal and University of Rhode Island scientists said
there apparently had been little permanent environmental damage.
About 150 young lobsters, 500 crabs, 15 birds and numerous mussels
have died, they said, but most small animals critical to the food
chain, such as zooplankton, survived.
   In New Jersey, the tanker Presidente Rivera leaked up to 1,500
barrels more oil while being cleaned and emptied, but officials said
most of the oil was mopped up with a boom and a skimmer.
   Officials anticipated lifting the emergency status from the
Delaware River over the weekend.
</TEXT>
