<HEAD>Long Island Town Reportedly Cancels HUD-Financed Swimming Pool</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A seaside Long Island village is scrapping plans
to build a swimming pool and will return $1 million to the U.S.
Department of Housing and Urban Development that had granted for the
project, a newspaper reported today.
   Officials in Island Park requested earlier this week that their
application for the pool be withdrawn, citing local opposition to
the project and rising costs, The New York Times reported.
   The officials denied the cancellation was a response to a federal
inquiry into HUD-sponsored projects on Long Island, the newspaper
said.
   Island Park was awarded the funds for the pool last year after
Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato, a village resident, personally lobbied
then-HUD Secretary Samuel R. Pierce.
   The funds came from Pierce's discretionary fund. In a letter to
village residents last fall, D'Amato praised Pierce's ``wise
decision to approve this grant.''
   An assistant to HUD Secretary Jack Kemp said Kemp was pleased the
pool project was dead.
   ``We think the funds can be used for a purpose that will be more
in line with assisting low-income individuals,'' said Mary Brunette.
   The Times reported that telephone calls to D'Amato's office
Friday afternoon were not answered.
   Federal investigators are looking into allegations that
HUD-sponsored houses went to politically connected residents in
Island Park instead of minorities, as had been planned.
