<HEAD>Airport to be Renamed for Victims of U.S. Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The airport in the southern city of Bandar
Abbas will be renamed to honor the passengers on an Iranian airliner
shot down a year ago by the United States, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency said today.
   The report, monitored in Nicosia, did not give the new name for
the international airport.
   All 290 people aboard the Iran Air Airbus en route from Bandar
Abbas to Dubai across the Persian Gulf were killed on July 3, 1988,
when the plane was shot down by the warship USS Vincennes.
   The Navy said the plane's crew mistook the airline's radar image
for that of an attacking jetfighter.
   The missile attack occurred during the eight-year Iran-Iraq war
when the United States and other Western nations regularly deployed
warships in the gulf to protect neutral shipping. The war ended in a
cease-fire last August.
   The Iranian news agency also said the anniversary of the attack
would be marked Monday with air force and navy planes dropping
flowers in waters where the plane crashed.
   Another ceremony with the families of the victims will take place
in Bandar Abbas, it said.
