<FIRST>r a PM-FatherKilling     07-01 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Father Killing,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abused Teen Found Innocent of Murdering Father</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The post-traumatic stress defense used by
some wives accused of killing their husbands also can apply to
juveniles, a judge ruled in finding a teenage girl innocent of
killing her abusive father.
   Attorneys agreed the case set a legal precedent, but 15-year-old
Diana Goodykoontz said she was surprised a judge rejected the
prosecution's claim that she committed murder because she was
influenced by heavy-metal rock 'n' roll music.
   ``I thought they were going to do something to me, anyway, 'cause
... I like the music,'' said Ms. Goodykoontz. ``It's not fair to
judge somebody just because of what they listen to.''
   Circuit Judge John Kuder on Friday ruled that the teen-ager acted
in self defense when she shot her father, Navy Chief Petty Officer
Dennis Goodykoontz, in the family's Pensacola home.
   The judge said Ms. Goodykoontz suffered from battered-child
syndrome, similar to the disorder that afflicts battle-shocked
veterans and wives who have been abused by their husbands. She had a
reasonable belief she was in danger although her father took no
overt physical action just before he was shot with his own handgun,
Kuder said.
   ``I'm unaware of any decision by a judge that's set this
precedent in Florida,'' said Assistant Public Defender Elton Killam,
who represented Ms. Goodykoontz.
   His co-counsel, Paul Mones of Los Angeles who is writing a book
about abused children slaying their parents, said he knew of no
other similar decision by a juvenile court in a non-jury trial, but
he said juvenile court decisions aren't always publicized.
   Kuder also said the state failed to prove any connection between
heavy-metal music and the July 23 shooting. He took nearly two
months to review the case.
   During a four-day, non-jury trial that ended May 4, Ms.
Goodykoontz testified her father had made sexual overtures and she
was afraid he was going to rape her. The judge also heard testimony
that the father had a history of violence against his wife and three
children, including a threat to kill the entire family on the day he
died.
</TEXT>
