<FIRST>r a PM-Bush 1st-LdWritethru a0431 07-01 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0431,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Starts Holiday Weekend With Morning Jog</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Tops with 13 grafs to update; further lead prospects uncertain.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush started his long
holiday weekend with a brisk morning jog today, saying he had no
official meetings scheduled during the vacation but added, ``You
know me, I get restless.''
   He said he had a pile of briefing papers to review for his
upcoming summit trip to Europe, which begins July 9 in Poland.
   National Security Council aide Robert Gates was with him for the
five-day stay in Kennebunkport.
   When asked by a reporter who ran with him if he planned to fly in
any other officials, Bush said he had no specific plans to do so.
   ``But you know me,'' he added, ``I get restless.''
   Bush was joined on his early morning run by his daughter, Dorothy
LeBlond, and the first dog, Millie.
   Regarding the first family's well-publicized objections this week
to Washingtonian magazine's characterization of Millie as the
ugliest dog in Washington, the president said he at first thought
magazine editors were joking when he received an apologetic note
from them on Friday.
   But Bush said he wrote a note back and brushed the whole matter
off. He had already sent the publication a photograph of himself
with Millie and her newborn puppies, he said.
   Bush ran for about two miles on dirt roads near his family's
Walker's Point compound. He greeted a few neighbors who were out.
   ``Beautiful day,'' he called out as he passed. He also advised
them not to miss the Fourth of July fireworks that are to be set off
on Monday night, July 3, over Walker's Point.
   Bush said he does not know all the neighbors and remarked on how
many houses had been built in the rustic area since he was a boy,
when there were no houses in the beachfront neighborhood where he
ran.
   After his run, he headed off to the sauna and said he was going
for a swim in the pool, then boating later in the day.
   On Friday night he went out fishing on his boat but had no luck,
he said. His daughter said that was because he steered the boat into
the reeds where her fishing line got caught.
   Bush arrived in this resort town Friday afternoon after wrapping
up a day in which he announced his proposed language for a
constitutional amendment against desecration of the American flag,
spoke at a commemoration of the 25th anniversary of the Civil Rights
Act, and met with South African anti-apartheid activist Albertina
Sisulu.
   Bush will remain in Kennebunkport until early Wednesday. He has
no public events scheduled, but plans to view the Fourth of July
fireworks display.
   Bush will be back at the White House for only a few days next
week before leaving for Poland on July 9, visiting Eastern Europe as
a prelude to the economic summit of major Western industrialized
nations in Paris.
   In an Independence Day message to the nation released by the
White House Friday, Bush asked ``all Americans to remember the
precious legacy of liberty we enjoy.''
   Kennebunkport was bustling with vacationers as the president
arrived, most of them strolling around the main town square where
boutiques and curio shops abound. A fairly steady stream of cars
drove slowly past the Secret Service checkpoints on the narrow
coastal road that passes Bush's home.
   Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the traveling White House
was prepared to comment on the Supreme Court's scheduled decision
Monday on a landmark abortion case.
   Bush began the Independence Day weekend with a flag-draped event
Friday at the Iwo Jima Memorial of Marines raising the flag during
World War II, where the president pushed for a constitutional
amendment to allow laws against burning the U.S. flag. The Supreme
Court ruled June 21 that the Constitution's freedom-of-speech
guarantees protect people who burn the flag as a form of political
protest.
   The amendment crafted by the White House and Republican
congressional leaders reads: ``The Congress and the states shall
have power to prohibit the physical desecration of the flag of the
United States.''
   Critics have said such an amendment would open the door for
erosion of the First Amendment to the Constitution.
   But Bush said, ``This amendment preserves the widest conceivable
range of options for free expression.''
</TEXT>
