<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Spy     07-01 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Spy,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pravda Says Spy Missed America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Navy intelligence analyst who killed himself
after defecting to the Soviet Union had missed his homeland and was
irritated by Moscow's chronic shortages of consumer goods, Pravda
said today.
   But Glenn Michael Souther still asked to be buried in his KGB
officer's uniform, the Communist Party daily said.
   The newspaper described the 32-year-old Souther, who committed
suicide in Moscow on June 22, as a top Soviet spy. It said he had
access to ``the most valuable documents on the top-secret plans for
use of the U.S. Navy in a nuclear war against the Soviet Union and
other socialist countries.
   ``He belonged with such outstanding soldiers of the `invisible
front' as Kim Philby and George Blake,'' Pravda said, naming two
famous British intelligence service operatives who spied for the
Soviets.
   The article did not say how Souther died, but it said colleagues
had noticed his occasional bouts of depression but never thought it
could lead to suicide.
   The KGB chief, Gen. Vladimir Kryuchko, said on Wednesday that
Souther committed suicide.
   Souther defected in 1986 when the FBI began investigating him. At
the time, the Hammond, Ind., native was working as a satellite photo
analyst in the Navy's 2nd Fleet headquarters in Norfolk, Va.
   Pravda indicated Souther fled his native land ``with pain in his
heart'' only because he feared the FBI investigation.
   ``Of course, not everything Glenn met in the Soviet land was as
he had expected,'' the newspaper said. ``For example, he could never
comprehend that it is possible to drop into a store and be unable to
find some needed item.''
   The article also quoted a letter Souther left to his colleagues
at the KGB, where he was given the rank of major last year.
   ``Justice demands that you hear my last words. I do not regret
our relationship. It was a longstanding one, and helped me grow as a
person. I wish to be buried in the uniform of an officer of the
KGB.''
   The article did not say whether authorities complied with that
request, but Kryuchkov said that Souther was given a military
funeral on Monday and he was buried in the same section of Kuntsevo
Cemetary as Philby.
   Pravda said he took the name Mikhail Orlov after his arrival in
the Soviet Union, choosing the Russian word for ``eagles'' for his
last name because it symbolized freedom and strength.
</TEXT>
