<FIRST>r i PM-Angola     07-01 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Deny Breaking Truce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebels today denied government
claims that they had violated a week-old truce in country's civil
war.
   In a statement released in Lisbon, the guerrillas affirmed their
``total engagement in the process of peace and national
reconciliation.''
   The Angolan government broke off peace negotiations on Friday,
accusing the rebels of violating a June 24 cease-fire by cutting
power lines to Angola's capital, Luanda, and ambushing convoys of
civilian vehicles.
   The guerrillas belong to the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola and have fought to force the government to
share power since shortly after Angola gained independence from
Portugal in 1975.
   Rebel leader Jonas Savimbi and Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos
Santos signed the cease-fire on June 22 in Gbadolite, Zaire, and
peace talks began on Wednesday in Kinshasa, Zaire.
   The Portuguese state-run RTP network reported Friday that dos
Santos ordered his delegation home and said it would not return
until the rebels explained the alleged cease-fire violations.
   Angola's state news agency ANGOP said Friday that five people
died Thursday when UNITA guerrillas ambushed a convoy transporting
coffee in Cuanza North province.
   The guerrillas' statement said cease-fire instructions may be
taking time to reach all combat units in the field around Angola, a
country twice the size of France.
   The Portuguese news agency Lusa on Friday quoted an unidentified
rebel official as saying power lines from the Cambambe dam's
hydroelectric station were downed Thursday when a cow set off a land
mine protecting high-voltage pylons.
   A rebel statement on Friday, meanwhile, rejected government
proposals for special treatment for Savimbi during a national
reconciliation process agreed on at Gbadolite.
   The statement said the government was trying to divide the rebel
movement.
   Savimbi's future was left unclear by the Gbadolite declaration,
which called for reintegration of rebels into Angolan society.
   The rebel leader has agreed to sit out of Angolan politics for
two years before running in free elections against dos Santos'
Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola.
</TEXT>
