<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan-PLO     07-01 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-PLO,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Appeals for Release of U.S. Journalist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib has agreed to release
an American photographer captured while traveling with Moslem
guerrillas, Palestinian officials said today.
   Najib gave assurances during a meeting Friday with Abu Khalid,
special envoy for PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat, that Tony O'Brien
would be freed, said the officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   ``It is not clear if Mr. O'Brien will go through the legal
formalities before he gets the presidential pardon or will be
released after the trial formalities are over,'' said one official.
   ``It is certain that Mr. O'Brien will see his freedom in the
coming weeks, but I am unable to say exactly when,'' he said.
   O'Brien, who did not have a visa to enter Afghanistan, was
arrested by security forces on June 8 at a rebel hideout in Kabul.
He has not been formally charged.
   The 43-year-old native of Santa Fe, N.M., had been covering the
civil war between Najib's Marxist government and the guerrillas. He
was on assignment for Time-Life Inc.
   A government official, also speaking on condition of anonymity,
said he could not discuss the prospects for O'Brien's release.
   ``It all depends on the president,'' he said.
   The rebels, backed by the United States and based in neighboring
Pakistan, have been fighting to overthrow the government for 11
years.
   Khalid arrived in Kabul on Thursday to discuss a PLO proposal to
end the war. It calls for an immediate cease-fire and peace talks.
   The guerrillas have refused direct talks with the Soviet-backed
government, insisting that Najib and key members of his government
step down. Najib has said he will not step down unless he has
guarantees his departure would bring peace to Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
