<SECOND>PM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0478,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa: Interior Minister More Apt to Win Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with details of meeting of Solidarity
lawmakers, edits to tighten; no pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity-backed lawmakers met today to
decide who to back for president, a powerful new post that Communist
Party leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski says he does not want.
   Solidarity has opposed a candidacy by Jaruzelski, who said on
Friday that he did not want to run because he was too closely linked
to the 1981 martial-law crackdown that crushed the labor union and
forced it underground.
   Jaruzelski recommended Interior Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak for the
office, which is similar to the presidency created in the Soviet
Union for Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said today he believed Czeslaw
Kiszczak had a better chance of winning the post than Jaruzelski.
   The president is to be elected next week by a simple majority of
the National Assembly. Authorities want to have the new president
seated before President Bush's scheduled three-day visit begins July
9.
   ``Whether it's Jaruzelski or Kiszczak is an internal problem of
the government coalition. It seems in this concrete situation that
Gen. Kiszczak has a better chance,'' Walesa told reporters before
the meeting of pro-Solidarity lawmakers.
   ``The general is paying now for everything bad that took place in
Poland. Guilty or not guilty _ let historians think about it _
that's how it is.''
   Kiszczak helped negotiate the historic accord between the
communist-run government and the Solidarity-led opposition that
resulted in the legalization of the trade union, opposition
participation in elections and broad changes in the structure of the
government.
   The 259-member Solidarity delegation in the National Assembly met
behind closed doors. A Solidarity source inside the meeting
lawmakers were discussing the possibility of finding a party or
neutral candidate they could support. The source said the
legislators also debated nominating a Solidarity candidate, an idea
the union so far has opposed.
   At Friday's meeting of the Communist Party's policy-making
Central Committee, officials neither accepted nor rejected
Jaruzelski's proposal that he not run for president.
   But the committee did ask him to reconsider, party spokesman Jan
Bisztyga said. Party representatives to the National Assembly did
the same.
   Outside party headquarters about 500 young anti-Jaruzelski
demonstrators tried to march to the Central Committee meeting, but
riot police blocked them.
   The youths hurled stones, smoke bombs and firebombs at police,
who fired tear gas and bursts from a water cannon in encounters that
lasted for hours. The state news agency PAP said 11 police were hurt
and 14 demonstrators were detained.
   Jaruzelski, 65, said he chose not to run because he was too
closely associated with the crackdown on Solidarity.
   ``The key matter for Poland now ... is national agreement ...
When there is an obstacle to reconciliation and to the uniting of
social forces, there is only one possible solution _ even if that
obstacle is Wojciech Jaruzelski,'' he said in his statement, later
carried by state media.
   Endorsing Kiszczak, sitting a few seats away, Jaruzelski called
him ``a soldier, a politician, a patriot and a man who has been
close to me for many years ... In the eyes of society, including
opposition circles, he is rightly considered a leading
representative of the line of reconciliation.''
   Jaruzelski said nothing about leaving his powerful post as party
chief.
   Also Friday, the government announced a one-month wage-and-price
freeze, halting major price increases until after the new parliament
and government are seated.
   Bisztyga indicated that some legislators in the communist-led
coalition fear that Jaruzelski lacks enough votes in the National
Assembly for a safe election. The coalition nominally has a 300-259
majority over Solidarity-backed legislators, but its internal
discipline is wobbly.
   Bisztyga said a final decision on a nominee will be made at a
later party meeting after consultations with the two junior partners
in the coalition _ the Peasant and Democratic parties.
   ``If decisions of those groups show a safe election calculation,
then there is a possibility'' Jaruzelski would be the nominee after
all, Bisztyga said. Otherwise, Kiszczak would be considered.
   A Jaruzelski loyalist, Kiszczak, 63, is an army general who heads
Poland's extensive police apparatus and helped wage the government's
war against Solidarity for most of the 1980's.
   But he won the confidence of Solidarity's leaders during
negotiations that began last Aug. 31 during a national wave of
strikes.
   In parliamentary elections June 4 and June 18, Solidarity got 99
of its candidates elected to the 100-member Senate, and it won all
the 161 seats available to the opposition in the 460-member Sejm.
</TEXT>
