<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0481 07-01 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0481,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian-Christian Hostilities Escalate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with Iraqi offer to cut off
arms shipments to Christians; picks up 3rd graf, `Syrian gunners...'; DELETES
last two grafs pvs, `The Syrians...the Syrians,' to conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Lebanese Christian gunners
today battled with howitzers and rocket launchers, ignoring Arab
calls to halt 15 weeks of violence. Police said three people were
killed and 16 wounded.
   The latest casualties increased the toll to 385 people killed and
1,515 wounded since the latest round in the 14-year-old civil war
broke out March 8, pitting Christian army commander Gen. Michel
Aoun's units against Syrian and Druse forces.
   In Baghdad, Iraq today declared it is ready to cut off arms
shipments to Lebanon's Christians if other countries stop providing
weapons to Lebanon's Moslems. ``Other countries'' was a reference to
Syria, which has 40,000 troops in Moslem-held territory under a 1976
Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   The Syrians have refused repeated calls by the Arab League to
lift the siege of the Christian enclave, saying they wanted
guarantees that Aoun will not be able to receive war material from
Iraq, their main Arab foe.
   Syrian gunners, deployed in Moslem west Beirut and the
surrounding mountains, pounded the 310-square-mile Christian-held
region northeast of the capital with 130mm howitzers and 107mm
multibarrelled rocket launchers.
   Aoun's gunners responded with 155mm howitzers.
   The spokesman said the Syrian barrage targeted two east Beirut
Christian districts, the coastline north of the capital and the
wooded valleys east of the waterfront, where Aoun's artillery
batteries are deployed.
   He said Aoun's gunners responded against the Syrian artillery
batteries along west Beirut's seaside boulevard.
   A spokesman for Aoun's command, who refused to be further
identified, said his gunners ``scored several direct hits on the
Syrian artillery emplacements in west Beirut.''
   The command of a Syrian army contingent in Beirut refused comment
on losses.
   Witnesses, speaking on condition of anonymity, reported seeing a
Syrian army ambulance rushing to a seaside Syrian howitzer
emplacement in west Beirut shortly before dawn.
   ``Seconds later, the ambulance sped out of the emplacement, which
is hidden behind sand ramparts. I don't know what happened there,''
one witness said.
   The thud of exploding shells and the whistling of rockets echoed
across Beirut and its surroundings.
   The intensity of the barrage sharply decreased around 8 a.m.,
allowing people to leave underground shelters.
   No explanation was given for the escalation in the confrontation,
which came a few hours before a scheduled meeting in the Saudi town
of Jeddah by three Arab foreign ministers to consider a mechanism
for stabilizing Lebanon.
   A full-fledged Arab summit in May urged a settlement to Lebanon's
14-year-old civil war by November.
   The confrontation broke out two days after Aoun blockaded illegal
ports run by Syrian-backed militias south of beirut to salvage about
$100 million in lost customs dues annually.
   The Syrians and their allies retaliated by besieging the
Christian enclave, home for 1 million people.
   Aoun escalated the confrontation by declaring a ``war of
liberation'' on the Syrian force deployed in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
