<DOCNO> AP890701-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CleanAir     07-01 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Air,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Says EPA May Tamper With Bush's Clean Air Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industries with the highest stakes in clean air
legislation are lobbying to make sure stringent enforcement
provisions aren't slipped into the formal bill submitted to Congress
by the Bush administration.
   Industry lobbyists say they believe some Environmental Protection
Agency officials want to be tougher on industry than does President
Bush, who unveiled his clean air plan June 12.
   Lobbyists for the auto, electric utility and petroleum industries
say they are particularly concerned about tougher standards on acid
rain, additional curbs on motor vehicle pollution, and the amount of
flexibility that industry will be given to reduce pollutants.
   The bill promises to be at the center of a major congressional
struggle for at least the next six months.
   ``We're emphasizing the importance of sticking with the
president's program,'' said Dale Brooks, a Chevron lobbyist who has
participated in petroleum industry meetings with administration
officials since Bush outlined his plan.
   ``If they start dragging in cats and dogs ... it will slow down
the process considerably,'' he said.
   EPA spokesman David Cohen responded: ``If the rumor is we're
going off in directions rejected by the (administration's) Domestic
Policy Council, that's absolutely false. We're taking a very
conservative approach to making the president's idea work.''
   The industry lobbyists said their concern was inspired in part by
an early EPA draft of the legislation, which contained measures
industry didn't like, but which preceded Bush's announcement and is
now _ everyone agrees _ outdated. They added that administration
officials listened, but made no specific commitments on legislative
language.
   The industry executives pointed out that Bush only revealed the
broad outlines and goals of his plan, while leaving the legislative
drafting _ where a word or numerical change can make an enormous
difference _ to technical and policy experts.
   ``Our concern is the EPA will try to make the bill more stringent
than Bush indicated,'' said one lobbyist for a large utility who
participated in one meeting and was familiar with several others.
``I would say the effort is low-key, fairly targeted and fairly
discreet.''
   The lobbyist, who spoke only on condition his name not be used,
said utilities are concerned with the acid rain reduction plan
because Bush did not use precise language on the amount of sulfur
dioxide emissions to be permitted by coal-fired power plants.
   Bush said his proposal ``envisions'' an emission standard of 2.5
pounds per million BTUs through 1995. That would be tightened to
``approximately'' 1.2 pounds per million BTUs through the year 2000.
   ``Those words give EPA room to wiggle around'' in achieving the
sought-after 10 million-ton sulfur dioxide reduction, the lobbyist
said, noting that EPA has in the past discussed an even tougher
standard for the 1995-2000 phase.
   The industry official added that at a meeting with EPA officials,
``We didn't accuse them of subverting what the president said, but
EPA knew why were were inquiring about some of these things.''
   The auto industry, which says the replacement of old cars with
new ones will lower motor vehicle emissions, is wary of new tailpipe
standards. The petroleum industry is concerned about how far Bush's
plan for alternative motor vehicle fuels will go.
   Other industry concerns are that EPA might try to impose strong
permit requirements that would be a ``bureaucratic nightmare,''
insert strong federal authority over state and local governments and
give the EPA administrator wider powers.
   There has been no comparable lobbying effort by environmental
organizations, said Casey Padgett, director of Environmental Action.
   ``Trying to lobby EPA would be trying to lobby our friends,''
Padgett said. ``And we don't have the access to OMB (Office of
Management and Budget) that industry does.''
   Richard Ayres, head of the Clean Air Coalition composed of major
environmental groups, said he's willing to wait for the ``fine
print'' before launching any lobbying campaign.
   One oil industry lobbyist said, however, he thinks Bush will keep
his proposal free from tampering.
   ``This president is hands-on'' and ``he's going to want to see it
and understand it,'' said Marc Himmelstein of the American Petroleum
Institute.
</TEXT>
