<DOCNO> AP890701-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Burma-China     07-01 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma-China,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Draw Parallels Between China, Burma Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANERPLAW, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Burmese students who saw their own
dreams of democracy crushed last year, the suppression of
pro-democracy demonstrators in Beijing conjures up bitter memories.
   Several thousand protesters were killed in Burma when the
military put down a nationwide uprising demanding political reform
and an end to a quarter century of economic mismanagement and
authoritarian, one-party rule.
   ``We feel for the Chinese students because the same things have
happened to us,'' said Aung Myint, who was a university student
during the Burma uprising. ``It seems that there isn't much
difference between the military in China and the military in Burma.''
   Unlike ``people power'' struggles in the Philippines and
elsewhere in Asia, force has largely succeeded, at least for the
time being, in stifling popular cries for democracy in Burma and
China.
   But nine months after Burma put down its uprising, the political
climate remains uncertain. Elections have been promised in the
spring of 1990 and oppostion parties have been permitted.
   But the opposition groups complain of harrassment and continuing
arrests, and many doubt the military will be willing to transfer
power in the future.
   ``What we saw in both countries was a challenge to established
authority in a form that they were not willing to countenance,''
said Michael Leifer a Southeast Asia expert in London.
   He said a common factor in both countries, which seemed to lead
to the bloody climaxes, was an older generation of leaders
controlling the events.
   Burma expert Joseph Silverstein notes differences between the top
leaders of the two countries. ``Deng Xiaoping was a whole lot
smarter and (Burma's) Ne Win a whole lot crueler,'' the American
academic said in an interview, noting China's economic progress and
Burma's stagnation.
   Although Brig. Gen. Saw Maung is nominally Burma's head of state,
Western diplomats say 78-year-old strongman Ne Win retains power,
despite his official retirement last July.
   In China, no promise of political change has been indicated. But
both countries have pledged to pursue domestic economic reforms and
open doors to foreign economic influence, which in Burma's case had
been closed since the early 1960s.
   The international community was outraged by both crackdowns and
announced economic sanctions. But within a few months the boycott of
Burma began to erode. Critics say the revival of trade ties, mostly
by Asian countries, has boosted the military government and works
against the democratic movement.
   If maintained, international economic sanctions were likely to be
more damaging to China's more sophisticated economy, Leifer said.
   Years of socialist mismanagement took Burma, once one of
Southeast Asia's richest countries, to the brink of economic
collapse.
   Silverstein believes it was because of this that Burma's uprising
attracted great popular support.
   He believes the Burma ``revolution'' was on the verge of success
until the military became worried about splits within its ranks.
Only then did it move decisively to crush the demonstrators. Some
differences were also reported within the Chinese military, but if
they existed they were finally overridden.
   In Burma, students like Aung Myint are last year's heroes. While
Chinese dissidents are feted in the West and allowed generous visa
extensions, Burmese students complain they are largely ignored.
   Aung Myint was among the estimated 7,500 students who fled the
repression. He said he decided to go after witnessing the killing of
five close friends and many others at the gates of Mandalay
Univerity.
   He now lives at Manerplaw, the jungle headquarters of the Karen
National Union, an ethnic rebel group fighting for greater autonomy.
Several hundred Burmese students are fighting alongside the rebels.
   U.S. congressmen last week voted $2 million in humanitarian aid
to the exiled Burmese, many of whom suffer harsh jungle conditions
and have contracted malaria. The students say more could be done for
them and against the Rangoon government by the international
community.
   Silverstein said the political climate in Burma is more volatile
than in China, ``I don't think for a moment there has been any
settling down, the heavy hand of the military has squashed but not
eliminated,'' he said.
   ``I think ... that while Deng has found his man and the system
will go forward. Ne Win has still to find his man and his system.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
