<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1052EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Turkey-Kurds     07-01 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Turkey-Kurds,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Kurdish Guerrillas Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARDIN, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Kurdish guerillas were killed
Saturday in a clash with security forces, the semi-official Anatolia
news agency reported.
   The agency said the security forces were conducting a search in a
mountainous area near the Syrian border when they encountered the
guerrillas and ordered them to surrender. The rebels opened fire,
the agency said.
   Security forces have launched a massive operation in the
mountains of southeastern Turkey as a result of the increase of
Kurdish attacks over the past two months.
   Kurdish rebels are fighting for an independent Marxist state in
parts of eastern and southeastern Turkey. More than 900 security
personnel and civilians and an equal number of insurgents have been
killed since the Kurds started hit-and-run attacks in 1984, official
reports say.
   Ethnic Kurds make up about one-fifth of Turkey's population of 55
million.
</TEXT>
