<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Chemicals 2ndLd-Writethru   07-01 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Chemicals, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0491,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Bonn</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ship Loaded With Chemicals For Iran To Be Stopped In Dubai</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with ship docking in Dubai; picks
up 5th graf, `Government officials...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iran-bound ship believed to
be carrying a chemical used to make deadly mustard gas docked here
today, sources said. West German television said it would be stopped
before reaching Iran.
   Iran's Tehran radio today denied that the shipment, which is at
the center of a chemical weapons scandal in West Germany, was bound
for Iran.
   The West German-flagged Seacrest Pioneer docked in Dubai today
from Bombay, India, Dubai-based shipping sources said on condition
of anonymity. The sources said the ship was due to leave later today
to return to Bombay, but they had no word on the ship's cargo or
whether any part of it was unloaded.
   The ZDF network in West Germany on Friday identified the ship as
the Seacrest Pioneer and said it was carrying thionyl chloride, a
compound used to make mustard gas. The report quoted unidentified
government sources in Bonn.
   West German prosecutors said Thursday they had opened a criminal
investigation of Rheineisen Chemical Products of Duesseldorf, which
contracted to deliver to Iran more than 250 tons of thionyl chloride.
   Government officials said Friday they had information that the
shipment had left Bombay but gave no further details. Officials of
the company, run by an Iranian family, earlier had claimed they had
halted the shipment on Wednesday in Bombay.
   Rheineisen officials deny any wrongdoing and say they had
government approval for the 257-ton shipment. The company has said
it would cooperate in stopping the shipment.
   The New York Times today quoted an Indian official as saying the
Indian government's State Trading Corp. sold Iran 60 tons of thionyl
chloride in March. The official was quoted as saying the chemical
was shipped from Bombay and the sale did not represent a breach of
local laws because the chemical is a freely traded commodity often
used in pesticides.
   The Iranian Foreign Ministry said Friday it never planned to
purchase chemicals from a West German company to produce poison gas.
   Tehran radio, in a commentary today, denied allegations that a
shipment of chemicals to manufacture chemical weapons was bound for
Iran. It said the reports were perpetrated by the United States and
showed renewed American hostility toward Iran.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia,
quoted an unidentified ministry spokesman as saying the allegations
were ``false, biased and followed particular political propaganda
goals.''
   The spokesman ``categorically denied reports on Iran's intention
to purchase chemical materials for manufacture of chemical weapons''
and accused U.S. and European media of making up the story.
   The news agency also quoted the spokesman as denying the Iranians
had summoned home a diplomat in the case.
   The West German Foreign Ministry said it had asked Iran to recall
the diplomat after receiving information from Washington that he
allegedly was involved in the deal. But the diplomat left before a
formal request was made.
   The Iranian spokesman said the diplomat's tour of duty had ended
more than a month ago and that he had returned to Tehran, according
to the Iranian news agency.
   Sources in Bonn identified the man as Seyed Karim Ali Sobhani and
said he had worked for the Iranian Embassy here since September 1987.
   The Rheineisen disclosures follow an international uproar six
months ago over the involvement of West German companies in building
a factory outside Tripoli, Libya, that Washington said would be used
to make poison gas. Libya said the plant would produce
pharmaceuticals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
