<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TurfBattle     07-01 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turf Battle,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Water District Orders Removal of Unauthorized New Lawns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Owners of 20 new homes have been given one
month to dig up their lawns, planted in violation of drought
restrictions.
   ``What are people supposed to do, tell their kids to run out and
play in the mud?'' developer Mike Rupprecht, one of the people who
planted grass, complained Friday. ``The drought is over. Everbody
knows that.''
   Not true, says the East Bay Municipal Utility District. Despite
spring downpours, reservoirs are still well below normal in the San
Ramon Valley.
   Officials of the two-county utility district mailed notices to
owners of 20 new homes ordering removal of grass. Like everyone who
applied for a permit after May 10, 1988, to hook up to the
district's water system, they were required to agree not to plant a
lawn, water conservation manager Dick Bennett said.
   ``We get about 4,000 new customers a year. Just 20 didn't go
along. We have to be fair to everyone,'' he said.
</TEXT>
