<DOCNO> AP890701-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HUD-MissingMoney Bjt   07-01 0844</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Missing Money, Bjt,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Contractors Held Millions Owed Government but Agency Rarely Noticed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After David Martin, his wife and his attorney
gave up trying to audit the accounts he held as a private closing
agent in Atlanta for the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, the government decided to take a crack at it.
   When HUD auditors finished the math, they said Martin owed the
government more than $1.6 million for the period 1984-1987 but had
only half that in the separate accounts he was required to keep for
proceeds from the sale of single-family homes for the agency.
   Martin's story is like dozens of others, tales that together show
an agency with little control over its private agents and even less
control over its own accounting for the hundreds of millions of
dollars the agents handle.
   In Martin's case, the auditors decided $839,812 was missing from
accounts.
   Martin's attorney protested, reminding the auditors they had
spent time at Martin's home and should be well aware of his ``modest
lifestyle and extremely modest financial base.''
   The attorney, Eugene Novy of Atlanta, said in a letter December
1987 to HUD that Martin could no longer afford to pay for legal
services and that the government's efforts to trace the money ``are
fruitless.''
   The government disagrees, and is trying to recover the money plus
interest in a $7.5 million civil suit.
   Audits of closing agents in Los Angeles, Tampa, Buffalo, Phoenix
and elsewhere produced similar findings: most of the agents were
sending HUD its money late; some weren't sending it at all. HUD,
already strapped for funds because of Reagan administration
cutbacks, was losing millions of dollars a year in interest.
   ``Delays by closing agents in remitting sales proceeds cost HUD
over $16 million in fiscal year 1987,'' the agency's inspector
general's office concluded after a nationwide audit of HUD's sales
and acquisitions of single-family homes, one of numerous agency
programs. The same report said records for the single-family program
had discrepancies involving 38,000 properties and $834 million
dollars.
   The inspector general's report, and related audits of closing
agents in several areas of the country, were obtained under the
Freedom of Information Act. They are receiving close scrutiny by law
enforcement officials and members of Congress as part of
investigations in HUD mismanagement and influence-peddling during
the Reagan years.
   The documents show closing agents, although required to wire HUD
its money within a day of completing a sale, routinely held the
money, in almost all cases at first for a few extra days and then,
as the mounting indiscretions went unnoticed, for longer periods _
weeks then months and in many cases two or more years.
   ``During a 31-month period, the escrow company remitted $109
million of sales proceeds to HUD an average of 47 days late,'' a Los
Angeles audit found. ``The delays cost HUD $1.1 million in lost
potential interest income.''
   That company, U.S. Escrow Co. of Downey, Calif., made just one of
the 1,576 payments it handled over the nearly three-year period on
time; some were up to 258 days late, HUD records show.
   The owner claimed he did not know about the payment deadline; HUD
records show it was listed in his contract with the agency and had
on other occasions explicitly discussed it with the company.
   Melvin Parsons, president of the U.S. Escrow, said in a telephone
interview that the company disputed the findings of the audit but
settled the case last year for $250,000.
   ``It was cheaper for us to settle it than to go into court,'' he
said Thursday.
   A review of 37 cases in Tampa, Fla., found that late payments
cost the government more than $18,000.
   In Buffalo, N.Y., an audit of a onetime HUD broker found that he
withheld payments, overbilled and paid himself advances from HUD
money. When he died two years ago he was almost $73,000 in arrears
to the government, and his widow later withdrew money from a HUD
escrow account, according to department records. She has agreed to
repay the money, HUD officials say.
   In Montgomery, Ala., auditors said Rick's Lind-Davis Real Estate
Co. failed to pay HUD $2 million and was late in remitting an
additional $3.8 million from sales between August 1984 to November
1987, costing the government more than $320,000 in interest.
   Federal authorities still are trying to recover that money,
according to HUD officials.
   Some of the agents mingled HUD money with private and other
checking accounts, conceivably earning interest that should have
been going to the government, according to documents.
   HUD was not detecting the late payments because of sloppy or
nonexistent record-keeping. Some office kept records on index cards;
others had so few computers that workers had to go from the first
floor to the ninth of a regional HUD office to use one.
   Many offices accepted slips requesting wire time to transfer
money to HUD instead of actual transmittal receipts from closing
agents _ many of whom never actually transferred the funds, the
documents show.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
