<DOCNO> AP890701-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China Bjt   07-01 0848</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China, Bjt,0870</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Announces Investigation into Behavior of Members</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's Communist Party celebrated its 68th
birthday Saturday by announcing an investigation into how its
members behaved during the recent protests for democracy. It said
some could be severely punished.
   Thousands of people took vows as new party members in Tiananmen
Square. Tourists flocked to the Gate of Heavenly Peace, which
overlooks the square and was opened to civilians for the first time
since the military crackdown last month.
   With the party's image at a new low because of widespread
corruption and the crackdown, party leaders turned to aging veterans
of the 1949 revolution to lead the internal investigation.
   Newly appointed party chief Jiang Zemin told a gathering of
several dozen semi-retired officials, most in their 70s or older,
that they were expected to help in an ``earnest rectification
extending from ideology to (party) organization.''
   The meeting was shown on national television. Not a single
youthful official was seen as the camera panned the room. Many of
those present wore hearing aids or slumped wearily in their chairs.
   The party newspaper, the People's Daily, signaled in a front-page
editorial that the shake-up would not be restricted to the party's
top levels, where it began with the recent ouster of party chief
Zhao Ziyang.
   Some party branches, it said, were ``weak and lax, and did not
carry out their roles as fortresses in battle.''
   ``The recent turmoil ... severely tested every party member,''
the editorial said. ``It is necessary to strictly check on the
performance of every party member in the struggle.
   ``Those deserving criticism and education should be criticized
and educated, and those deserving sanctions should be punished,'' it
said, adding that discipline should be severe. ``The strength of the
Communist Party is not in its numbers, but in the quality of its
members.''
   Since the army entered Beijing on June 3-4 and used tanks and
machine guns to quell student-led protests for a freer society,
party units have held frequent meetings to study the new party line
defending the crackdown.
   However, there have been no reports of party members being purged
on the grass-roots level. Many party members took part in the
student-led marches, and punishment has been expected.
   The Chinese Communist Party was founded in 1921 by a dozen men
who gathered surreptitiously in a girl's school and had flee to a
rowboat in the middle of a lake when police learned of the session.
   The People's Daily acknowledged that some Chinese have lost
confidence in the party in recent years, partly because many members
use their privileged status to sell favors or siphon off official
funds. Strengthening the 47 million-member party is a ``matter of
life and death,'' it said.
   The party also celebrated its birthday in a more lighthearted
manner with dancing and singing in Tiananmen Square, which was
opened to organized groups that had obtained permission from
authorities. The vast square, where students demanding reform staged
rallies in April and May, was filled with people taking party vows
and soldiers who sang, ``Without the Communist Party there would be
no new China.''
   The ornate 17th-century Gate of Heavenly Peace _ Tiananmen in
Chinese _ overlooking the square was reopened to all civilians for
the first time since the crackdown. More than 2,200 tourists, nearly
all Chinese, flocked to the gate, getting autographs from Gen. Wang
Fuyi, one of the army commanders who brought troops in to quell the
protests.
   Plainclothes security men, wearing straw hats or holding
walkie-talkies, stood along the marble railing from which Mao
Tse-tung's portrait hangs.
   The party's birthday celebration coincided with an American
birthday party as the U.S. Embassy celebrated Independence Day early.
   As it does every year, the embassy threw a party American
residents in Beijing. But many Americans fled Beijing when the army
moved in, and only about 200 people attended the bash, compared with
1,500 last year.
   Eight Chinese police with submachine guns took up posts outside
the embassy but refused to say why they were there. They may have
hoped for an appearance by dissident Fang Lizhi and his wife, who
are wanted by police and have been hiding at the embassy.
   Education officials, meanwhile, said more attention would be paid
to ``political attitudes'' when approving student applications to
study abroad, the official China Daily reported. The step appeared
part of a series of measures to prevent people accused of joining
the protests from leaving the country.
   China sends about 8,000 students abroad to study each year.
   Official newspapers also announced the start of the trial of
three men accused of throwing paint May 23 on the portrait of Mao
that hangs from the Gate of Heavenly Peace. The People's Daily said
they were charged with counterrevolutionary actvities.
   The three _ a magazine editor, a teacher and a factory worker _
were turned over to police by student protesters who condemned the
defacing. Authorities hung a new Mao portrait hours later.
   The trial, like most in China, was closed to foreign media.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890701-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Jiang Bjt   07-01 0852</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jiang, Bjt,0877</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Chinese Leader Could Face Insurmountable Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ13</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Jiang Zemin was named head of the world's
largest communist Party, he inherited more than a powerful position
_ he inherited a load of serious problems.
   Jiang, successor to the disgraced Zhao Ziyang, must deal with the
aftermath of the government's suppression of the pro-democracy
movement and with an economy slipping out of control.
   He also must live in the shadow of his two successors, the late
Hu Yaobang and Zhao, both purged for failing to clamp down on the
democratic impulses of youth.
   Jiang's political future seems to rest on the health of
84-year-old senior leader Deng Xiaoping and the desires of other
party elders who strongly believe in the communist ideology that has
ruled China for 40 years.
   ``It depends, as so much has in the last weeks, on what one old
man decides to do. That's where it becomes unpredictable, because
it's one old man,'' said an Asian diplomat who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Jiang already is being compared to Hua Guofeng, China's titular
head during the transitional years of political instability between
the 1976 death of Mao Tse-tung and the rise of Deng.
   There probably will not be more pro-democracy demonstrations in
the near future like the one crushed when soldiers drove thousands
of protesters from Tiananmen Square on June 3-4.
   But the willingness of people to put up with political repression
may be tied to how well the economy performs and to living standards.
   Premier Li Peng last fall announced a two-year austerity plan
designed to slow economic growth to curb inflation, running about 30
percent in urban areas.
   Industry was growing so quickly that it was taxing raw material
and energy supplies. Also, banks were issuing loans for new
construction and expansion without getting old loans back, adding to
the inflationary pressures.
   Li's plan has had modest success. The industrial growth rate has
been shaved from about 20 percent last year to 11 percent, and
inflation has dropped slightly.
   But factories can't pay their bills because credit has dried up,
and exporters are reneging on contracts because they lack the raw
materials needed for production.
   A deepening energy crisis is forcing factories to shut down for
days each week, and severe shortages of some raw materials have
contributed to rampant corruption. Factories often have to pay off
officials who obtain materials at low state-set prices and resell
them for handsome profits.
   Unemployment, which according to official estimates will rise to
3 percent from 2 percent this year, has caused great social despair.
Millions of people, mostly peasants from the countryside, have been
put out of work by the cancellation of construction projects and
have been left to drift from town to town looking for work.
   Premier Li's economic measures have all but stopped economic
reforms, particularly changes crucial to bringing prices in line
with market values and easing serious supply-demand gaps.
   The purge of Zhao, one of the pioneers of China's market-oriented
reforms, and his followers will deprive the nation of some of its
most innovative economists.
   ``Economic thinkers will at best be under a cloud,'' said a
Western diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``There will
be a lot less intellectual energy.''
   Diplomats also speculated that Jiang will, like Premier Li, be
more comfortable with central planning models that Zhao tried to
dismantle.
   That would not bode well for flagging efforts to restructure
China's economic base.
   In the first three months of 1989, before students took to the
streets to demand political reforms, 22 percent of state-run
enterprises lost money. The amount of losses, made up by the state
treasury, was the equivalent of $1 billion, up 120 percent from the
same period in 1988.
   Foreign businessmen who fled when the crackdown began now are
returning, but the political turmoil could seriously affect China's
foreign business relations.
   The U.S. Embassy says a travel advisory urging businessmen and
tourists to stay away from China remains in effect. One embassy
official said safety concerns continue and cited a recent incident
in which troops fired into the air when a car driven by an American
businessman backfired as it pulled away from a military checkpoint.
   Jiang, who worked to attract foreign investment to the city of
Shanghai, where he was party chief before his promotion, may have
been picked by Deng partly to reassure the outside world that China
will keep its doors open to the West.
   But new foreign investment, which China badly needs for its
modernization drive, likely has been severely hurt by the crackdown.
   The United States, Japan and the European Economic Community have
urged international lending institutes to postpone new loans to
protest the crackdown. Such a move would deprive China of billions
of dollars in development money.
   The World Bank has deferred consideration of $780 million in
loans.
   Tourism also has been seriously hurt, cutting deeply into
earnings of more than $2 billion a year that have helped China solve
its chronic foreign exchange problems.
</TEXT>
