<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--IranSizzles     07-01 0104</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran Sizzles,0104</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tehran Temps Top 106, Hottest in 19 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures in Tehran hit a scalding 106,
the hottest weather in the Iranian capital in 19 years, the official
Islamic Republic News Agency reported Saturday.
   IRNA, monitored in Nicosia, said the heat Friday combined with a
high humidity had made the ``discomfort index'' hit 28.5 degrees.
   It gave no details on how the index was calculated, but said,
``Over 50 percent of the people don't feel well when the discomfort
index is between 21 and 24 degrees. But if it is more than 24
degrees, everyone will suffer.''
