<DOCNO> AP890701-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     07-01 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOOERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A horde of illegal aliens swarmed across the
border from Canada into the United States, but officials weren't
doing a thing about the monkey business.
   That's because the border-crashers were Japanese snow monkeys
that escaped Friday from Parc Safari African, a zoo in Hemmingford,
Quebec.
   As many as 100 monkeys swam a moat around the park and dashed
south to the border, just a couple of miles away, officials said.
   Don Dixon, animal control officer for the town of Mooers about
two miles south of the border, said he started getting frantic phone
calls Friday morning from residents reporting the monkeys on the
loose.
   The animals are mischievous but not dangerous, he said.
   State police in nearby Plattsburgh said they were aware of the
monkey invasion but could not spare any troopers to help round up
the animals.
   John Gillen, district ranger for the state Department of
Environmental Conservation, said his office was leaving the roundup
to the zoo's employees.
   Whatever monkeys elude capture by zookeepers probably will return
to the park when they get hungry, Dixon said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fireflies are big game to some hunters
here and one group has made flashy profits from the incandescent
insects.
   Dorothy Anderson and her army of net-wielding firefly hunters
swarm the area nightly for the luminous bugs, which fetch a penny
apiece from a St. Louis chemical company.
   The lightning bug season, which began last month, is ``really
getting pretty doggone good right now,'' Ms. Anderson said.
   Ms. Anderson, 62, leads about 100 members of the Firefly Club of
Princeton, in north central Illinois, which is the largest of
similar organizations in the state. Members range in age from 3 to
75.
   Two years ago the club netted 600,000 lightning bugs, which
brought $6,000 in profits, and by the end of last week it has caught
33,000 fireflies this summer, bringing in $330.
   It's not uncommon for firefly hunters to make $5 every evening in
about 20 minutes, Ms. Anderson said.
   ``It makes good spending money for them,'' she said. ``And at the
same time, it's being done for a good purpose.''
   Ms. Anderson sends the captured fireflies to the Sigma Chemical
Co. in St. Louis. The company removes the section of the insect
containing luciferin and luciferase, chemicals which have hundreds
of medical and scientific uses, including detection of cancer cells.
</TEXT>
