<FIRST>r i AM-Botha     07-01 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Botha,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Botha Says Farewell to Military in One of Last Public Appearances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha addressed a
military awards ceremony Saturday in what was expected to be one his
last public appearances before retiring.
   The 73-year-old leader, reportedly embittered over pressures from
his own political supporters to quit, kept his emotions in check in
a farewell to the South African Defense Forces, with which he has
been associated 23 years.
   But his voice cracked when he said, ``I thank you and greet you.
God bless you,'' at the end of the ceremony. He awarded medals to 21
soldiers for bravery in the conflict against guerrilla forces in
Namibia and Angola.
   South Africa has agreed to grant independence to Namibia, its
colony for 74 years, under a regional peace accord that also
provides for Cuba to draw its 50,000 troops from Angola. The Cubans
backed and helped train fighters of the Southwest Africa People's
Organization, which battled South African forces.
   Botha's appearance at the ceremony came two days after he
declined to attend a congress of his governing National Party, where
delegates approved a reform that envision giving the black majority
a greater voice in national affairs.
   Botha suffered a stroke in January. Party officials cited this as
one reason for replacing him as party chief and urging him to step
down as president after parliamentary elections in September.
   While not referring directly to the party's reform plan, Botha
declared that the country was ``involved in conflict on a front much
broader than just the military. We are called on to stand up and be
counted _ for our national values and interests, our traditions,
religious freedom, private enterprise and our very right to exist as
a free nation.
   ``We know the measure of our freedom depends on our sense of
responsibility and devotion. The whole of South Africa can benefit
from it.''
   Botha served as defense minister before becoming prime minister
and then president.
   Armored personnel carriers, long-range artillery and other pieces
of military equipment were displayed in a two-hour parade past the
reviewing stand in front of Cape Town's city hall, where canopies
protected the dignitaries from the rain.
   Col. Hans Stempsler, chief spokesman for the Defense Forces,
denied press reports the event was arranged especially to bid
goodbye to Botha. He said it was an annual event.
</TEXT>
