<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-01 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Official Says American Photographer Will be Released</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib has agreed to release
an American photographer captured while traveling with Moslem
guerrillas, a senior PLO official said Saturday.
   Najib gave the assurance that Tony O'Brien would be freed in
response to a personal appeal by Palestine Liberation Organization
chairman Yasser Arafat, said Arafat's special envoy, Abu Khalid.
   ``He told me that there will be no trial and that O'Brien will be
released shortly,'' Khalid told reporters.
   He said he met O'Brien and that the American was in tears when he
learned of his imminent release.
   Diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
O'Brien might be released when Arafat visits Kabul this week to try
to mediate a settlement in the Afghan civil war.
   ``He is no more in jail or being interrogated. He is in a
house,'' said Khalid. He did not elaborate.
   O'Brien, who did not have a visa to enter the country, was
arrested by Afghan security forces on June 8 at a rebel hideout in
Kabul. He has not been formally charged with a crime.
   The 43-year-old native of Santa Fe, N.M., had been covering the
war between Najib's soldiers and the U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas,
who are based in Pakistan.
   He was on assignment for Time-Life Inc. when he crossed into
Afghanistan with the insurgents, known as mujahedeen or, Islamic
holy warriors.
   The guerrillas have been fighting to overthrow Afghanistan's
Marxist government for 11 years.
   Khalid arrived in Kabul, the nation's capital, on Thursday to
discuss a PLO proposal to end the fighting. The proposal calls for
an immediate cease-fire and peace talks.
   ``If we can bring them to the negotiating table, that will make
at least the beginning,'' he said.
   The guerrillas have refused direct talks, insisting that Najib
and key members of his government relinquish power. Najib has said
he will not step down until he has guarantees that his departure
will bring peace to Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
