<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1552EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     07-01 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Decides to Wait Before Taking Stand on President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity legislators decided Saturday
against offering Lech Walesa as a presidential candidate because the
political system is not yet democratic enough, a spokesman said.
   The opposition lawmakers also decided to withhold taking a stand
on the communist party's choice for president until just before the
meeting of the National Assembly, which will choose the president.
That meeting is expected sometime this week.
   The legislators said it would be best if there were more than one
candidate.
   ``We are waiting for decisions of the coalition around the Polish
United Workers (communist) Party as to what candidate it will
recommend. Or rather what candidates,'' parliamentary deputy
Bronislaw Geremek told state television after the meeting.
   The leader of the communist party, Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski,
announced Friday he did not want to be a nominee and he endorsed
Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak. The party has asked
Jaruzelski to reconsider.
   Solidarity legislators met Saturday to decide what stand to take
in relation to the election.
   ``As goes for the candidates from the coalition (communist) side,
we will assume our stand on the eve of the election _ that is on the
eve of the first session of the National Assembly,'' Solidarity
parliament deputy Janusz Onyszkiewicz told a news conference.
   During the daylong debate, Solidarity considered putting up its
own candidate. The obvious choice would be Soldidarity leader Lech
Walesa, Onyszkiewicz said, but he added, ``The time is not good for
Walesa now.''
   ``We are not in a democratic system and we don't think that Lech
Walesa should be the president in this system which is not fully
democratic,'' he said. Walesa said in the past that he would not run
for president.
   The president, who is limited to two six-year terms, will be
commander-in-chief of the armed forces and be responsible for
foreign relations. He may dissolve Parliament for new elections and
declare one 90-day state of emergency.
   The Sejm, or Parliament, and the Senate will convene in separate
sessions for the first time July 4. Their first joint session as the
National Assembly is expected later in the week. That is when the
president will be chosen.
   Officials want the president in office before President Bush
arrives for a three-day visit July 9.
   The communist coalition has a 300-259 advantage, but there are
some internal divisions.
   Communist party spokesman Jan Bisztyga said Friday a meeting will
be held to choose between Jaruzelski and Kiszczak before the
National Assembly meeting.
   Among the options considered at the Solidarity meeting were the
possibilities of finding a party or neutral candidate the opposition
could support.
   Some people at the meeting, including Walesa, said it would be
best if there were several candidates, not one, said Onyszkiewicz,
who is also national spokesman for the Solidarity trade union.
   In an interview on state television Saturday, Walesa said the
president needed to be someone who could unite all Poles.
   Jaruzelski is linked to the 1981 martial law crackdown, in which
thousands of union activists were interned. Solidarity was outlawed
the following year. The communist party chief cited this association
in the public eye as his reason for not wanting to be a candidate.
   Kiszczak helped crush Solidarity after martial law, but he won
back confidence from the opposition by leading the government in
negotiations that led to Solidarity's legalization and the elections
for the National Assembly.
   The elections were the freest in Poland since World War II and
included opposition candidates for the first time.
</TEXT>
