<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StatenIsland     07-01 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Staten Island,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York City May Become a Little Smaller</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City's famed five boroughs could
someday become four.
   The Legislature, working into early Saturday morning in an
end-of-session marathon, voted to give Staten Island residents a
chance to say whether they want to secede from New York City.
   If Gov. Mario Cuomo signs the bill, residents of the smallest
borough might be able to vote in November 1990 on whether to take a
bite out the Big Apple. Cuomo said Saturday he hadn't decided what
to do.
   Polls say Staten Island residents overwhelmingly favor secession,
an issue tied up with a court-mandated restructuring of the largest
U.S. city government.
   ``We didn't start out with the idea of leaving the city,'' said
state Sen. John Marchi, a Staten Island Republican. ``We just wanted
to maintain our voice in the city. We didn't have anything against
the city of New York. I ran for mayor there twice.''
   The secession movement gathered steam after the U.S. Supreme
Court ruled in March that the Board of Estimate, which governs city
spending and construction, was unconstitutional because it gave
Staten Island's 400,000 residents equal representation to the more
populous boroughs, such as Brooklyn, with more than 2 million people.
   Staten Island residents fear the city charter revision
commission's plan for revamping city government will shortchange
their borough.
   ``It would reduce us really to colonial status,'' Marchi said.
   Cuomo said he believed the legislators' action was not an
approval of secession, but simply a ``political statement. What they
are saying is `Staten Island ought to be protected.''' Cuomo said he
shared those sympathies, but wasn't sure how to go about providing
such protection.
   Cuomo is from Queens. Manhattan and the Bronx are the other two
boroughs.
   Residents of Staten Island have never considered themselves true
New York City residents, said Elizabeth Connelly, a Staten Island
Democrat who shepherded the secession bill through the state
Assembly.
   She noted, though, that the borough's more upstate character has
lessened since the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge linked it with Brooklyn
and it began absorbing people fleeing high housing costs and other
urban woes in other boroughs.
   Many leaders from the other boroughs, including Mayor Edward I.
Koch, a Manhattanite, fear the loss of tax revenue to the city if
Staten Island secedes.
   Lawmakers who opposed the bill also argued that all New York City
residents should have the right to decide if part of the city should
break away.
   ``It's fundamentally unfair to all the other residents of the
city of New York ...,'' said Assemblyman Anthony Genovesi, a
powerful Brooklyn Democrat. ``I don't think that anyone has
considered the ramification of how it all works out.''
   Connelly argues that Staten Island residents never had a say in
the 1898 decision by the Legislature that made the island a borough
of New York City.
   The 1989 bill calls for Staten Island voters to decide two
questions: whether Staten Island should break from New York City and
whether it should form a county or city type of government. The
legislation won't allow a secession vote unless a charter revision
is voted on in a citywide referendum this November.
   Even if the secession decision is a long way off and by no means
a certainty, it's already unifying a borough that's been the butt of
jokes, Marchi said.
   ``There is a lot of excitement,'' he said. ``I'm telling you, it
doesn't make any difference _ rich or poor, black or white, fat or
skinny. It doesn't make any difference.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890701-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1626EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest Bjt   07-01 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest, Bjt,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Urges Nation to End Ethnic Disputes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev appealed Saturday
for an end to ethnic strife among Soviet nationalities and said the
state will not tolerate those who stir up unrest.
   Gorbachev spoke for the first 25 minutes of the nightly
television news show Vremya in a rare personal appeal to the nation
that is home to more than 130 nationalities.
   Gorbachev called on all Soviet citizens to bring an end to ethnic
strife that has emerged in several Soviet republics over the past
two years.
   ``As president of the U.S.S.R. Supreme Soviet, I consider it my
duty to warn you about the mounting danger'' of exacerbating ethnic
tensions, Gorbachev said in the speech. He also warned of ``related
consequences for society, for every family and every person.''
   Gorbachev's appeal follows outbreaks of violence in the republics
of Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan and Georgia. Last year, ethnic clashes
erupted in the republics of Armenia and Azerbaijan.
   The most recent violence was in Kazakhstan. Four people died in
the city of Novy Uzen last month when rioters attacked immigrants
from the Caucasus region, accusing them of setting up private
business and finagling privileges in housing and other benefits.
   In June, violence between ethnic Meskhi Turks and native Uzbeks
in the republic of Uzbekistan left about 100 people dead, officials
said. Josef Stalin ordered the migration of the Turks to the
republic in 1944.
   In April, 20 Georgians died in clashes with Soviet troops sent in
to end a a pro-independece demonstration.
   Gorbachev, whose own policies of tolerating greater openness and
dissent have emboldened groups seeking more autonomy, blamed ethnic
violence on the forced migrations of ethnic groups ordered by his
predecessors.
   ``Today, we are reaping the fruits of lawlessness in preceding
decades _ the deportation of whole peoples from their lands and the
burying in oblivion of the national intersts of small ethnic
groups,'' Gorbachev said.
   He said that all people had to obey the laws of the land that
guarantee a citizen's rights and warned that ``the state will uphold
these rights by all means at its disposal.''
   Gorbachev said some people were taking advantage of ethnic
frictions for personal gain. ``This is playing with fire. Those who
have embarked on this path are assuming gravest responsibility
before their own people and before society as a whole,'' he said.
   Gorbachev said most of the violence had taken place in instances
where ethnic groups constitute a minority in small communities.
   ``What will happen if interethnic discord spreads over to regions
where millions of people of other nationalities live along with
people of the indigenous nationality?'' he asked.
   He said every citizen regardless of nationality should have their
rights protected, ethnic groups should be allowed to freely develop
their own language, and culture and political and ethnic reform is
needed in the 15 Soviet republics.
   Gorbachev said Communist Party members and intellectuals should
use their influence to quell ethnic passions.
   ``All of us indeed cannot but be disturbed by the interethnic
intolerance, frictions and even conflicts eupting lately, now here
and now there, disrupting people's lives and resulting in a number
of cases of human tragedies,'' Gorbachev said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890701-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1629EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Prayers     07-01 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Prayers,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Excerpts from Cranmer's Book of Common Prayer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Britain-Cranmer, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Knowen in grf 3 and Jesu in graf 7 cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following are extracts from Archbishop Thomas
Cranmer's 1549 Book of Common Prayer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Collect for the Supper of the Lord
   Almighty God, unto whom all hearts be open, and all desires
knowen, and from whom no secrets are hid, cleanse the thoughts of
our hearts, by the inspiration of the holy spirit, that we may
perfectly love thee, and worthily magnify thy holy name: through
Christ our Lord. Amen.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Second Collect at Evensong
   O God, from whom all holy desires, all good counsels, and all
just works do proceed, give unto thy servants that peace, which the
world cannot give; that both our hearts may be set to obey thy
commandments, and also that by thee we being defended from the fear
of our enemies, may pass our time in rest and quietness; through the
merits of Jesus Christ our saviour. Amen.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Third Collect at Evensong for Aid Against All Perils
   Lighten our darkness, we beseech thee, O lord, and by thy great
mercy defend us from all perils and dangers of this night, for the
love of thy only son, our saviour Jesu Christ. Amen.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   from The Form of Consecrating of an Archbishop or Bishop
   Be to the flock of Christ a shepherd, not a wolf: feed them,
devour them not; hold up the weak, heal the sick, bind together the
broken, bring again the outcasts, seek the lost.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   from The Order for the Burial of the Dead
   I commend thy soul to God the father almighty, and thy body to
the ground, earth to earth, ashes to ashes, dust to dust, in sure
and certain hope of resurrection to eternal life, through our Lord
Jesus Christ, who shall change our vile body, that it may be like to
his glorious body, according to the mighty working whereby he is
able to subdue all things to himself.
