<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1631EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CigaretteLaw     07-01 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cigarette Law,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Cigarette-Machine Ban Gets Last-Minute Reprieve From Judge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-New Laws, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Provisions of a new Utah law prohibiting
cigarette vending machines were put on hold by a federal judge, less
than 12 hours before the law was to have taken effect Saturday.
   U.S. District Senior Judge Aldon J.Anderson issued a temporary
restraining order banning enforcement of the challenged section of
the law after an emergency hearing Friday.
   ``Sales until this matter is resolved will be the same as under
the old law,'' Anderson ruled.
   Four vending-machine companies had filed suit against the state
Friday morning, requesting that the Adolescent Tobacco Prevention
Act, passed by this year's Legislature, be declared unconstitutional.
   Anderson's ruling prevents the vending-machine provision of the
law from taking effect for at least 10 days.
   The vending machine ban, which won widespread support from
lawmakers, is aimed in part at curbing uncontrolled access to
cigarettes by minors. It would prohibit all cigarette
vending-machine sales except in bars, private clubs or offices and
other work areas not open to the public.
   A second hearing was scheduled for July 7 to determine whether a
preliminary injunction should be issued until the law's
constitutionality can be tested.
   The plaintiffs claim a ban on vending machines will drive them
out of business without restricting sales to minors any more than
current law, which already requires employees of businesses having
cigarette machines to check customers' ages before enabling the
machines to work by remote switch.
   The restraining order presented ``no threat of change in the sale
of cigarettes to minors'' since a cashier must still check the age
of the person buying cigarettes, Anderson said.
   The judge made his decision despite the state's claim the lawsuit
is not a proper question for a federal court.
   ``We do not feel there is a constitutional issue and therefore
the plaintiffs cannot prevail on the merits,'' said assistant
attorney general Linda Luinstra, who argued the case involved
questions that should be challenged in a state court.
   But plaintiffs' lawyer Richard Rappaport said the law deprives
his clients of business without any rationale.
   ``There is a public interest in having children not smoke,'' he
said. ``There's no public interest in having adults buying
cigarettes hand-to-hand over the counter instead of having adults
buy cigarettes from a machine after the business owner determines
they are adults.''
   Over the past week and before Friday's ruling, many of Utah's
vending machine companies were busy removing cigarette machines from
restaurants, hotels and other public places in anticipation of the
new law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890701-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1632EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-MonkeyHerpes 1stLd-Writethru a0533 07-01 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Monkey Herpes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0533,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Technician's Death Turns Focus To Lab Research Safety</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf to CORRECT test results expected this
week, sted next week.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATTAWAN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Martin Alsobrooks was hired as an
animal technician at a research laboratory here, nobody told him the
monkeys he'd handle likely would carry a virus that could kill him.
   Less than three months later, one of his co-workers is dead, a
former co-worker is hospitalized and Alsobrooks and about 30 current
or former colleagues are on an experimental anti-viral drug they
hope will stem the rare disease in case they, too, have been
infected.
   The herpes B virus, better known as the monkey virus, is found in
more than 50 percent of rhesus monkeys, a type of macaque. The virus
is harmless to the animals, but more than half of the 30 cases
documented in humans since the disease was first reported 57 years
ago have been fatal. It's commonly transmitted through bites and
scratches.
   ``I try not to worry about things I have no control over, but my
family is worried. My mother is lighting candles,'' said Alsobrooks,
33, whose blood test results were inconclusive.
   Thousands of these monkeys are being used daily in laboratory
experiments nationwide. While progress is being made in the area of
animal welfare rights, the conditions in which lab employees work
are largely unregulated by federal or state law.
   Officials at International Research and Development Corp. say
they have complied strictly with guidelines set by the Centers for
Disease Control in Atlanta and that the two technicians who were
infected did not report their wounds.
   Tom McGeorge, a 23-year-old technician, died June 20, just a few
days after the virus was diagnosed. The hospitalized former
employee, whose name is being withheld, is in serious condition. He
worked at the company only one week before quitting this spring.
   Early detection was impossible since neither man reported his
injuries, which is required by the company, said Francis X. Wazeter
III, IRDC vice president.
   When an employee reports being bitten or scratched by a monkey, a
disinfectant is promptly applied to the wound to kill the virus,
Wazeter said.
   Some employees said bites and scratches were so common and the
pressure to complete studies so great that it was nearly impossible
to report each wound to the company nurse.
   Wazeter denied there was pressure on employees to work fast and
said reporting wounds is mandatory. He also denied allegations by
several employees that the leather gloves used by monkey handlers _
part of the extensive protection gear _ usually had holes and took
months to replace.
   The CDC's guidelines, which are not enforced by any regulatory
agency, were created two years ago after a herpes B outbreak in
Pensacola, Fla., killed two monkey handlers and infected two other
people.
   Some current and former employees at the lab believe a high
turnover rate, poor training, and heavy workloads played a part in
the outbreak of the rare disease, which has been documented only 30
times since the first case was reported in 1932, said Dr. Gary
Holmes, a CDC epidemiologist.
   The disease, which attacks the brain and central nervous system,
frequently leads to encephalitis, an inflammation of the brain, and
then to death. Since the virus has been documented, 16 of the 24
patients who have shown symptoms have died, Holmes said. In one case
in Pensacola, the virus was spread person-to-person.
   Of about 135 blood tests conducted on current and former IRDC lab
employees who had contact with the monkeys in the last two months,
81 were negative and five were inconclusive, Michigan Department of
Public Health officials said. The rest of the results are expected
this week.
   The company, which employs 350 people, does animal research for
medical, pharmaceutical, veterinary and agricultural companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
