<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpill     07-01 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Prepares To Release Damaged Tanker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greek tanker that ran aground and spilled
420,000 gallons of oil in Narragansett Bay last week was inspected
Saturday as its crew prepared to move it to a drydock for repairs,
officials said.
   The Coast Guard's Lt. Paul Wolf said officials from New York
inspected the vessel, the World Prodigy, to make sure there would be
no problem bringing it into New York Harbor for repairs.
   A tugboat was scheduled to arrive late Saturday night and the
ship was tentatively scheduled to leave on Sunday, Wolf said.
   The tanker has been anchored off the south coast of Rhode Island
since it struck a rock on Brenton Reef on June 21, tearing two large
gashes in its side and dumping 420,000 gallons of home heating oil
near the mouth of Narragansett Bay.
   A Coast Guard officer who conducted three days of hearings into
the accident last week concluded the accident was probably caused by
human error.
   The captain, Iakovos Georgudis, 43, has admitted he erred in not
waiting for a pilot before entering the treacherous waters close to
the mouth of the bay.
   A federal magistrate late Friday released the ship and Georgudis,
who faces two federal misdemeanor charges he violated pollution
laws. Georgudis' bail of $50,000 was wired to a local bank. A state
grand jury is also considering charges against Georgudis.
   Magistrate Jacob Hagopian said he released the ship at the urging
of the Coast Guard, which wants to see it repaired. Hagopian said
his order would contain a provision that the ship be towed.
   Wolf, however, said the ship would move under its own power,
accompanied by a tug, to New York Shipyard, on the site of the old
Brooklyn Navy Yard in New York City. He said h was not aware of
Hagopian's order.
   Coast Guard officials would be on board the ship, along with
Georgudis and his crew, for the 20-hour journey, Wolf said.
</TEXT>
