<FIRST>r a AM-JeffersonArson     07-01 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jefferson Arson,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jefferson Arson Acquittal: Back To Square One</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOINA CHIACU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former volunteer firefighter was
acquitted of a series of arson fires that terrorized this community
last summer, and residents say they are troubled once again.
   ``I think the town is going to be in turmoil,'' Fire Chief Jim
Kenison said after a jury in neighboring Lancaster on Friday
acquitted Lance Lalumiere, 23.
   ``I'm scared, I'm scared of what's going to happen,'' said
Kenison. ``I'm concerned that, because of (the verdict),
repercussions are going to happen, one way or the other.''
   Kenison said the community of 800 again will be afraid of the
fires that last summer had residents sleeping in shifts and guarding
property with guns.
   Paige Matson, owner of the Skywood Manor Motel, where Lalumiere
once lived, said Lalumiere's acquittal brings new problems.
   ``I'm scared for him, I'm happy for him,'' Matson said. ``I'm
just praying that they don't come after him again.''
   Matson said she is afraid the fires will start once again
``because they haven't caught the arsonists. I think the fires will
start up stronger.''
   When Lalumiere was asked by reporters what he wanted to do first
after eight months behind bars, he replied, ``Thank God.''
   He said he will return to Jefferson and stay with a brother, Rene.
   The Coos County Superior Court jury reached its decision Friday
in its second day of deliberations, ending a three-week trial.
   Defense lawyer James Quay said he wasn't surprised by the verdict.
   ``Lance has a lot of family support in Jefferson,'' he said.
   Lalumiere was charged with setting 11 fires and trying to set two
others out of 26 fires in the White Mountains community.
   No one was injured in the fires, but they caused about $1 million
in damage. They began with brush fires, but soon escalated to barns
and homes. Most began in the dead of night at the rear of buildings.
   Lalumiere, described by his lawyers as slow, suffering from a
learning disability and functionally illiterate, admitted he set the
13 fires and three others, but later recanted. His lawyers said the
admissions were coerced. Three charges were dismissed before Friday.
   The state was ``disappointed, but we definitely feel the evidence
went in as well as it could,'' said Assistant Attorney General
Andrew Serell.
   ``There is no evidence linking anyone else to any of the charges
(that were filed) against Mr. Lalumiere,'' Serell said. ``If any new
evidence came to light, it would be pursued.''
   Lalumiere is the second person charged and acquitted in the
fires. Larry Coulter Jr., a current Jefferson firefighter, was
charged in October with one count of arson, later reduced to
criminal trespassing. He was acquitted of the lesser charge in April.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
