<FIRST>r a AM-FernaldSuit     07-01 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fernald Suit,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fernald Plant Neighbors Pleased with Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neighbors of the uranium processing plant in
Fernald said they were pleased with the government's proposal to pay
a $73 million settlement in a lawsuit charging the plant polluted
the environment.
   But leaders of the Fernald Residents for Environmental Safety and
Health said Friday that the plant's owner, the U.S. Department of
Energy, must still be watched to ensure it continues to clean up the
1,050-acre site.
   ``We're not done yet,'' said Lisa Crawford, spokeswoman for the
citizens group. ``It took us 4{ years to win this battle. This is
just the first part. The next step is to get it cleaned up.''
   Terms of the settlement, approved by Energy Secretary James D.
Watkins late Friday, will be the subject of a hearing scheduled Aug.
24 before U.S. District Judge S. Arthur Spiegel in Cincinnati. It
calls for the government to pay at least $73 million and no more
than $78 million.
   Mrs. Crawford, who lives two miles from the plant, said the
settlement provides funds for medical monitoring of the residents
and their children to track any adverse effects of radioactive
pollution.
   ``For all of us, it's very important to have medical monitoring
after all that we've been put through,'' she said. ``The biggest
thing is that we've shown the world that the DOE is wrong, that what
they did to these people was wrong.''
   Stanley M. Chesley, the lawyer who negotiated the settlement for
the neighbors, said money is also included for studies to analyze
the extent of cancer in the area and help residents detect it as
early as possible.
   ``Early detection is early cure in cancer,'' Chesley said. ``Now
we can afford an opportunity for everyone to have early detection.''
   Chesley filed a $300 million class-action lawsuit in Spiegel's
court on behalf of 14,000 people living within five miles of the
38-year-old plant where the government processed uranium used in
making nuclear weapons.
   The residents alleged in their suit that pollution from the plant
18 miles northwest of Cincinnati caused them mental stress and
devalued their property.
   Spiegel presided over an unusual mock trial that ended June 15
when a jury's non-binding verdict recommended the residents be
awarded $136 million. Chesley credited the mock trial for
encouraging the settlement.
   The defendant in the case was National Lead of Ohio, the
contractor that operated the plant for the government from 1951
through 1985. The current operator, Westinghouse Materials Co., was
not involved in the suit.
   Chesley said the settlement is significant because it kills the
Energy Department claim that National Lead of Ohio was not liable in
the case because it took its actions on orders from the U.S.
government.
   Under the contract, the government was required to pay damages
assessed against NLO, said Energy Department lawyer Henry Gill Jr.
   The Energy Department has admitted that the plant has released
more than 300,000 pounds of radioactive uranium oxide dust into the
atmosphere through faulty exhaust-air filters during its history.
But the department denies that pollution from the plant has hurt
neighbors' property values.
   ``A lot of that is hysteria,'' said deputy Energy Secretary
Henson Moore. ``There really wasn't, judging by what I heard ... a
lot of hard evidence of anybody losing anything _ as a matter of
fact, almost none.''
   If Spiegel approves the settlement, the government must deposit
the money into four Cincinnati banks no later than Oct. 15, said
Louise Roselle, one of the lawyers who represented the neighbors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890701-0110 </DOCNO>
