<HEAD>Archbishop of Cape Town Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to ADD autobiographical information; No Pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic Archbishop of Cape Town, the
Most Rev. Stephen Naidoo, died Saturday at his sister's home,
officials said. He was 51.
   Naidoo, who suffered from a heart condition, went to London after
being advised by physicians to take three months of rest, the
Catholic Media Office said. He collapsed at his sister's home in
Merton, south London, where he had been resting for two weeks.
   Naidoo's Cape Town archbishopric made him one of the most senior
members of the 2.5-million strong Catholic community in South Africa.
   Born Oct. 23, 1937, in Durban, Naidoo was ordained a priest June
29, 1961. After spending 14 years working abroad, he returned to his
native country in 1974 and was consecrated a bishop on Sept. 15 that
year.
   Naidoo was serving as auxiliary bishop and and vicar general in
the Cape Town diocese in October 1984 when he was chosen to replace
Cardinal Owen McCann as archbishop.
   Although an outspoken critic of Pretoria's apartheid policies,
Naidoo was not as public a figure as other churchmen, including
Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu and Allan Boesak, president of the
World Alliance of Reformed Churches.
</TEXT>
