<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 1806EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BarricadedNuns     07-01 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barricaded Nuns,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three of Four Nuns Barricaded in Monastery Leave After Almost Nine
Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three of four Roman Catholic nuns,
who barricaded themselves in a monastery nearly nine months ago to
protest liberalization of their austere order, ended the standoff
Saturday, a diocesan spokesman said.
   The fourth woman, whose temporary vows expired earlier in the
year, remained in the infirmary at the Monastery of the Most Blessed
Virgin Mary of Mount Carmel, said Timothy Manning of the Paterson
Diocese.
   Five of the 13 Carmelite nuns at the monastery barricaded
themselves in the infirmary Oct. 4, saying they feared eviction for
protesting a new prioress' introduction of television and sweets.
   Manning said Saturday's action was a surprise. ``We're presuming
that the realization finally hit them that if they wanted to save
their vows, they were going to have to leave.''
   Manning said the diocese had planned to deliver an order Monday
demanding the nuns leave the monastery.
   The nuns had maintained they would not leave the building until
they were ordered to by the Apostolica Signatura, the highest court
of the Vatican.
   The nuns have twice ignored orders from lower-level Vatican
officials.
   Lynn Williams, formerly Sister Teresita, was the only nun
remaining at the infirmary Saturday. She hung up the telephone when
reached by a reporter seeking comment. There was no answer at the
main monastery number.
   The location of the other nuns was not known, Manning said.
   Betty Sutton, a lay person who has acted as a spokeswoman for the
nuns, said she did not know where they went.
   ``This came as a total surprise to me,'' Ms. Sutton said. ``I
didn't know they were leaving.''
   She said she spoke to the rebel nuns two days ago and they said
they were frustrated the case had dragged on so long. The remaining
nun had shared that attitude, Ms. Sutton said.
   ``I can't imagine what they're thinking,'' she said. ``Unless
their parents influenced them, but that's just a supposition.''
   Ms. Sutton said she had spoken with Sister Eliane, who lives in
the monastery and has been a spokeswoman for the nuns.
   ``It's very disturbing,'' she said. ``We just don't understand
how this happened so quickly.
   Sister Eliane said in an interview last week that she believed
the nuns would remain until the Apostolica delivered its ruling. ``I
don't see any movement or anything that they're leaving,'' she said.
   The last Vatican letter, received May 31, told two of the nuns to
seek another monastery, informed one that her temporary vows had
expired and allowed a 71-year-old nun to stay on the condition that
she obey the monastery prioress.
   A fifth nun, Nicole Prescott, left the monastery March 19, citing
health reasons. Prescott, then known as Sister John of the Cross,
served as the spokeswoman for the group when their case received
international attention.
</TEXT>
