<FIRST>r a AM-CoalStrike 1stLd-Writethru a0552 07-01 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0552,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>BCOA President Says Strike Threatens Health Benefits</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead, 2nd graf to reflect that not just UMW members on
strike; SUBS 6th graf, `UMW spokesman ...,' to provide first reference
to union.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wildcat strikes by an estimated 37,000
coal miners are threatening the health benefits of 85,000 retired
miners and widows, the president of a coal industry group said
Saturday.
   Joseph Brennan, Bituminous Coal Operators Association president,
said in a statement that health benefits to retirees and widows are
funded through hourly contributions by the coal companies. He said
the wildcat strikes have cut off much of the fund's income.
   ``There must be an end to these strikes _ or the fund will
collapse and thousands of people will lose benefits,'' Brennan said.
   The health benefits program cost $200 million per year or $4,000
per working miner, and the fund has lost $20 million since last
year, Brennan said.
   Miners began wildcat strikes _ strikes without formal union
sanction _ June 12 to protest the Pittston Co.'s refusal to sign a
contract with the union and to protest the past jailing and $3
million fines levied against the union and its members.
   United Mine Workers spokesman Joe Corcoran could not immediately
be reached for comment Saturday on Brennan's allegations. There was
no answer at his home, and he did not return a message left at his
office.
   U.S. District Judge Dennis Knapp ordered the wildcat strikers
back to work, but for the most part, his order has been ignored. Up
to 46,000 miners had been out in 10 states, and as of Friday 37,000
miners in eight states were still out.
   About 1,900 UMW members are on an authorized strike against
Pittston in Kentucky, Virginia and West Virginia.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., joined a growing list
of West Virginia politicians who say they are frustrated with
Pittston's reluctance to resume negotiations with the union.
   On Friday, Pittston formally rejected a second offer by West
Virginia Gov. Gaston Caperton to mediate talks.
   Rockefeller aide Lane Bailey said Friday that the senator has
grown impatient and accused Pittston of ``foot-dragging and
posturing.''
   ``He sees the strike as threatening the major export markets for
our coal, and that's something he's worked very hard on,'' Bailey
said.
   The senator's aide said Rockefeller had been in contact with UMW
President Richard Trumka and Pittston Chairman Paul Douglas urging
the two sides to resume negotiations.
</TEXT>
