<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-01 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>And the Rains Kept Coming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain from Tropical Storm Allison fell over much of the South and
Southwest on Saturday, and remnants of the slow-moving storm flooded
hundreds of Mississippi and Louisiana residents out of their homes.
   More than 100 homes were flooded in Bolivar County, Miss., where
nearly 5{ inches of rain fell since midnight. Up to 3 inches were
expected overnight in the already-saturated northern half of
Mississippi.
   In the southwestern Louisiana town of Oakdale, about 200 people
remained out of their homes because of the threatening Calcasieu
River, said Mayor George Mowad.
   About 40 homes held 6 to 7 feet of water, with less in another 20
to 30 homes, Mowad said. U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service
guards helped Louisiana National Guard troops patrol the streets,
Mowad said.
   Residents of a Lake Charles subdivision took pot-shots at
alligators and water moccasins swimming through 6-foot-deep water
around their houses.
   The storm dumped 15 to 20 inches of rain on west central
Louisiana in the last five days.
   Many streets were flooded in Arkansas City, Ark., after 3{ inches
of rain fell Saturday morning, and thunderstorms dumped 2{ inches of
rain in one hour at Alvin, Texas.
   Rain and thunderstorms also extended from portions of the central
Plains into the Ohio Valley.
   Heavy rain was reported in southeast Kentucky and Florida, and a
severe thunderstorm in Alabama blew trees down at Chatom.
   Scattered showers were reported in the Pacific Northwest and in
extreme northern New England.
   Partly cloudy skies prevailed in the East, where temperatures
ranged from 75 to 85 degrees.
   Clear skies and low humidity across much of the West allowed
temperatures to fall below freezing at some summer resorts Saturday
morning. In the Lake Tahoe area, the mercury at Truckee, Calif.,
fell to 23 degrees, making it the coldest spot in the nation, and in
South Lake Tahoe it was 26 degrees. At Bryce Canyon, Utah, the
temperature was 29 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees in Hoquiam, Olympia, Bremerton and Quillayute, Wash., to 107
degrees in Phoenix.
   The forecast for Sunday called for showers and thundershowers
over eastern sections of the southern Plains, across the lower half
of the Mississippi Valley, the Ohio and Tennessee valleys, the Gulf
Coast states and the south Atlantic Coast states, with showers and
thunderstorms most numerous over Alabama and the Ohio Valley;
widespread showers over the Pacific Northwest; and widely scattered
showers in northwest Montana and northern Maine.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 80s and 90s across most of
the nation, in the 60s and 70s in the Pacific Northwest, in the 70s
along the California coast and in northern Maine, and 100 to 110
degrees from southwest Texas to much of New Mexico and the desert
Southwest.
</TEXT>
