<FIRST>r a AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0588 07-01 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0588,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Relaxes at Maine Vacation Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS hours to holes in 11th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, back at his beloved
vacation home for an extended holiday weekend, spent a vigorous
Saturday recreating by the sea, entertaining family and encouraging
neighbors to watch his fireworks show Monday night.
   ``Beautiful day,'' he called out cheerily to neighbors out
walking their dogs when he took his 6:30 a.m. jog on dirt roads near
his family compound at Walker's Point.
   The president was accompanied on the run by daughter Dorothy
LeBlond, first dog Millie, a couple of Secret Services agents and a
reporter.
   He advised the neighbors he jogged past not to miss a fireworks
display to be set off on Monday night over Walker's Point, site of
the Bush home.
   The president's five-day stay was billed as a mostly private time
for recreation, but he said he would be going over briefing
materials for the upcoming European summit.
   Bush was accompanied on the sunny holiday weekend by wife
Barbara, some of his young grandchildren, and other relatives.
   After his two-mile jog, Bush headed for the sauna and pool, and
his daily intelligence briefing on world events.
   He then took his boat Fidelity out on the sea, whizzing by the
Shawmut Hotel just as White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater
finished telling reporters the president would have no other public
activities for the day.
   However, Bush later played golf at Cape Arundel Golf Course with
longtime friend Spike Heminway and club pro Ken Raynor. As they teed
off, Bush, wearing carnary yellow pants, was asked by reporters if
he was getting tired from the day's activities.
   ``What do you mean?'' he asked, laughing. ``We're just beginning
a five-day marathon.''
   Bush played 18 holes in less than two hours and credited his
improved game to a new type of putter.
   Fitzwater said there has been no resolution of the flap over who
will pay an estimated $40,000 per year that local police must spend
to accommodate the presidential visits.
   Bush has been visiting Kennebunkport since his boyhood, but new
security demands since he has become president have prompted
complaints from local authorities, and a letter from Sen. George
Mitchell, D-Maine, seeking federal financial help.
   Fitzwater said the president wants to help and ``feels very
strongly for Kennebunkport,'' but there is no legal way to spend
federal funds to help the local governments.
   ``It would take an act of Congress that would allow us to give
money for that,'' said Fitzwater, adding that he was unaware of any
special federal help provided other small towns that have served as
presidential vacation spots in past administrations.
   Meanwhile, crowds of tourists crowding the quaint,
boutique-filled center of town appeared to be oblivious to the
president's visit.
   One of the unsolved mysteries this weekend in Kennebunkport is
the identity of the mysterious benefactor paying for what promises
to be a spectacular fireworks show Monday night.
   The show will be produced by pyrotechnics specialist George
Zambelli who counts the president among his fans.
   The state fire marshall's office said the permit was issued in
Bush's name at the request of the Secret Service, but no one is
saying who will pick up the tab, estimated at $5,000.
   Fitzwater said only that it is `an anonymous donor.''
</TEXT>
