<FIRST>r a AM-NakedSailor     07-01 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Naked Sailor,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Ship Jumper Runs Naked Through the Streets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet sailor granted temporary asylum in
the United States was arrested Saturday after he ran naked through a
coastal resort town with an American flag in one hand and a knife in
the other, police said.
   Before running through Rockaway Beach, Alexander Ptitskin, 19,
went on a rampage that included smashing church windows and
destroying church-owned equipment, said Police Officer Gordon Witt.
   ``We don't know what caused it, but it looks like he just went
bananas and started tearing things up,'' said Witt.
   Ptitskin was charged with first-degree burglary, criminal
mischief and disorderly conduct, Witt said.
   Ptitskin, the third mate of the Soviet fishing boat The
Izmurudnyi, jumped overboard in Portland on Wednesday, saying he
wanted to ``try American.'' He told U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service officials he wanted political asylum.
   The Izmurudnyi left Portland on Friday bound for the Soviet Union.
   Around 5 a.m. Saturday, Rockaway Beach residents called
authorities about a disturbance near St. Mary's By the Sea Roman
Catholic Church, Witt said. A man threw a videocassette recorder, a
computer and other electronic equipment belonging to the church
through the window of a church-owned cottage. The man then ran next
door to the church's recreation hall and broke two large windows.
   With an American flag draped over his shoulder and a large knife
in the other hand, the man then went down the street to a motel and
broke a large window near the office. Ptitskin was arrested in the
lobby.
   Ptitskin arrived in Rockaway Beach, a town of about 1,280 people
about 60 miles west of Portland, on Friday evening and was staying
at a small church-owned cottage, said the church's pastor, the Rev.
Morton Park.
   ``We went to dinner and talked about several things,'' Park said.
``He had no money and no luggage and he was in a strange place. I
think he was under a lot of strees and that showed. I didn't expect
this to happen, though.''
   Ptitskin was being held in the Tillamook County jail, where bail
was set at $26,900. He was to appear in court Monday.
