<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Brister 1stLd-Writethru a0576 07-01 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Brister, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0576,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Award-winning Animated Filmmaker Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf, `His latest ...,' to ADD more
on Brister; picks up 6th graf, `Brister, a native ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Tyler Brister, a filmmaker and arts
educator whose animated movies won awards at the Cannes Film
Festival, has died at the age of 38.
   Brister died Wednesday of complications of AIDS, his family said.
   One of his first films, ``Spanish Peanuts,'' is a stop-action
animated film in which a chorus line of peanuts dances across a
stage to a Latin rhythm. It has been shown on NBC's ``Saturday Night
Live'' and HBO and won the Silver Cup Award at the Cannes
International Film Festival in France.
   His ``Mandarin Oranges'' was distributed by the National
Endowment for the Arts Short Film Showcase program. It won an award
at the International Tournee of Animation and received a silver
medallion at the Chicago Film Festival and a gold medallion at the
Miami Film Festival.
   His latest work, ``Punch Film,'' won first prize at the Houston
Film Festival.
   Brister created many other short live-action films, commercials
and multimedia presentations.
   In Salina, Kan., he produced the 360-foot-long ``Buffalo
Crossing'' using the zoetrope style of animation. When viewed from a
moving car, a sequence of 72 life-size drawings merged into one
image of a buffalo galloping alongside the road.
   Brister, a native of Dover, Ohio, graduated with honors from the
Minneapolis College of Art and Design in 1973. He was an
artist-in-residence at schools throughout the country and taught
filmmaking and animation techniques.
   Survivors include his mother, Ruth Brister of Bloomington, and a
sister.
   No services will be held.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
