<FIRST>u i AM-SAfrica-Crash 1stLd-Writethru a0593 07-01 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0593,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede: JOHANNESBURG</HEAD>
<HEAD>50 Killed, 30 Hurt in Bus Crash</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: UPDATES throughout with police saying passengers all laborers
from Transkei, details, background. No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus filled with workers ran off a
road and rolled down a 900-foot embankment in Natal province
Saturday afternoon, killing about 50 passengers and injuring 30,
police said.
   The bus was returning black laborers and domestic workers to the
independent black homeland of Transkei for the weekend when the
accident occurred near Port Shepstone, 60 miles southwest of the
coastal city of Durban.
   About 25 of the injured were in serious condition, indicating the
death toll could rise further, police said.
   South African Broadcasting Corp. quoted Lew Corbet, traffic chief
at Shepstone, as saying the bus left the road, overturned, and
plunged down the embankment.
   The region experienced heavy rain during the day, but it was not
immediately known if weather was a factor in the crash.
   Buses carrying workers frequently are overloaded and not well
maintained.
   The reports said rescuers used four-wheel-drive vehicles to bring
the dead and injured from the bottom of the ravine to the roadway.
The injured were taken to hospitals in Harding, 11 miles away, with
some serious cases taken to Durban.
   It was the second multiple-fatal bus accident in two days. On
Friday, eight people were killed and 53 hurt when a bus ran off a
road and overturned near the Numbi gate entrance of the Kruger
National Park, a wildlife reserve. All of those passengers were
local residents, police said.
</TEXT>
