<FIRST>r i AM-NorthernIreland     07-01 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Policeman, Wound His Elderly Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assailants burst into a home
northwest of the capital and opened fire, killing a policeman and
wounding his elderly mother, police said.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for the attack on the
outskirts of Garvagh, 40 miles northwest of Belfast. Suspicion fell
on the outlawed Irish Republican Army, which has targeted the
security forces in its guerrilla campaign to drive the British out
of Northern Ireland.
   The 57-year-old constable, whose identity was not released, was
to retire this month after 34 years in the Royal Ulster
Constabulary, the British province's police force, said a spokesman
on condition of anonymity.
   The constable had been carrying out courthouse duties, mostly in
Belfast, the spokesman said.
   He was visiting his 80-year-old mother at her home when several
armed men entered through the rear door and opened fire, the
spokesman said.
   The woman suffered a gunshot wound in the stomach and was
hospitalized ``in deep shock,'' he said.
   More than 2,700 people have been killed in 20 years of political
and sectarian violence in the province, where Protestants outnumber
Roman Catholics by a 3-to-2 margin.
   The IRA wants to unite the province with the Irish Republic,
which is predominantly Catholic, under a leftist administration.
</TEXT>
