<FIRST>u i AM-Greece 1stLd-Writethru a0539 07-01 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0539,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative-Leftist Alliance Forms Coalition Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8 pvs, `The 62-year...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with some ministers announced Saturday night. Pick up 9th pvs, `The agreement...'
ADDS 1 graf background at bottom.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative and communist parties ended a
two-week political deadlock Saturday and agreed to form a coalition
government. It was the first time communists have played a role in
determining the formation of Greece's government.
   It appeared, however, that the coalition would govern only three
months and that its sole task would be to clean up Greece's
scandal-ridden political system.
   The decision by the communist-dominated Coalition of the Left and
Progress to join with the conservative New Democracy Party gave that
party's premier-designate, Tzannis Tzannetakis, the support needed
for a majority in the 300-member parliament.
   President Christos Sartzetakis announced that Tzannetakis, a New
Democracy parliamentarian since 1977, would be sworn in Sunday.
   In the June 18 general election, New Democracy won 145 seats. The
Coalition _ an alliance of the Greek Communist Party, disenchanted
socialists and the Eurocommunist Greek Left _ won 28 places.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement, or
PASOK, lost after eight years in power, taking only 125 seats.
   Late Saturday night, the 62-year-old Tzannetakis announced the
first of his Cabinet posts. Only two of those he appointed _ the
justice and interior ministers _ were non-parliamentarians
affiliated with the leftist Coalition. Most others were from the New
Democracy Party.
   Named as deputy foreign minister was George Papoulias, currently
the envoy in Washington.
   In negotiations leading up to the agreement, New Democracy leader
Constantine Mitsotakis had offered the Coalition the Justice and
Interior ministries.
   The agreement came 40 years after the communists, in their bid to
seize power, were defeated in a civil war by U.S.-backed government
troops.
   Papandreou, 70, who was in a hospital for treatment of a heart
and kidney condition, reacted bitterly to the pact between the two
political forces.
   ``This alliance is without principles. It violates the popular
will,'' he said.
   Papandreou had called on the Coalition to join PASOK so the two
parties could set up a government. But Coalition leader Harilaos
Florakis said he didn't want to be associated with a scandal-tainted
group like the Socialists.
   A multimillion-dollar scandal allegedly involving key ministers
in Papandreou's government, and his open affair with a woman half
his age while he was married, contributed to Papandreou's downfall.
   Mitsotakis and Florakis agreed that their coalition would have a
three-month life span and that its work would be limited to
restoring democratic institutions and cleaning up Greek politics.
   Florakis said at the end of the three months, ``we will
re-examine our position and act accordingly.''
   But because of the wide gap in the two sides' political
ideologies, it appeared unlikely the coalition could survive after
its task of purging former PASOK ministers and officials accused of
involvement in scandals.
   If the coalition falls apart, the president will appoint a
caretaker regime to lead the country to natonal elections.
   A newly elected government is needed to deal with pressing
economic problems and complete negotiations with the United States
over the future of its four major military bases in Greece. The
defense pact expired last December but a clause gives the United
States 17 months to either close down the bases or renegotiate a new
agreement.
   The two members of the new coalition differ over the presence of
the U.S. bases. The Coalition has strongly opposed the four bases
and called for their removal. But the New Democracy Party favors
negotiating a new agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
