<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 2151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-China-USDemonstrations     07-01 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-US Demonstrations,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Students in U.S. Protest 68th Anniversary of Party Founding</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese students burned a Communist flag before their homeland's
consulate in Los Angeles, and 5,000 people rallied in San Francisco
on the 68th anniversary Saturday of the Chinese Communist Party's
founding.
   Chinese students and scholars demonstrated in front of the
consulate in Chicago, denouncing Deng Xiaoping and other Chinese
leaders as murderers. At Indiana University in Bloomington, four
Chinese students renounced their membership in the party.
   The rallies were part of a nationwide ``Democracy Day,'' during
which participants urged an end to the crackdown on pro-democracy
activists in China that followed the army attack June 3-4 on
protesters in Beijing's Tiananmen Square.
   In Los Angeles, about 50 Chinese, mostly university students from
Santa Barbara, attended the noon flag burning at the consulate near
downtown.
   ``Down with the Communist party! Down with the murderous party!
Down with the old men's party! Rebuild a new China!'' the students
shouted.
   They stuffed the red and gold Chinese Communist Party flag into a
concrete waste can filled with burning copies of the People's Daily
News, the official Chinese Communist newspaper.
   They later distributed to the news media copies of a letter to be
delivered to consul officials, expressing outrage over ``brutal
suppression of human rights'' in their homeland and asking Chinese
officials to declare pardons and amnesty for pro-democracy students.
   The letter also included a list of Chinese dissidents and asked
the government for an account of their safety and whereabouts.
   Most students did not want to be quoted by name, saying they
feared retribution by their government.
   ``These students are taking a risk by doing this publicly,'' said
University of California at Santa Barbara professor Walter Yuen, a
member of the International Citizenry for a Democratic China, which
organized the event.
   ``They are probably losing their chances to ever go back to China
and could be putting their relatives still in China at risk,'' he
said.
   In San Francisco, an 8-foot replica of the ``Goddess of Liberty''
statue erected during the pro-democracy demonstrations in Tiananmen
Square was unveiled in Justin Herman Plaza, where politicians
addressed an overflow crowd.
   The gypsum cement statue was built by Chinese students at the
Academy of Art College, and is a model of a bronze one that
community groups want to erect in San Francisco's Chinatown as a
permanent reminder of the students who died when authorities used
troops to quell the protests.
   In Indiana, the students resigned from the Communist Party to
protest the attack and the crackdown.
   ``We cannot do many things to protest. This is one thing we can
do,'' said Pan Youfang, 39, a graduate student in computer science
who quit after 16 years of membership.
   Many Chinese students have preferred to keep their party
membership a secret in the United States, fearing prejudice from
Americans or the U.S. government, Chinese students said.
   He Zhou, 35, a graduate student in journalism, said the party
advised Chinese students not to admit their membership when they
applied for visas to study in the United States.
   Now, he said, the students ``identify themselves as communists
only for the purpose of quitting.''
   In Chicago, about 100 Chinese students and supporters paraded
with signs and banners in front of the downtown consulate.
   ``Let our voice be heard,'' said Chun Li, a student
representative at Northwestern University in suburban Evanston.
``The people did not shed their blood in vain. A new page in Chinese
history is now being turned.''
</TEXT>
