<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 2159EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Elections     07-01 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Elections,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Claims Voter Registration Irregularities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders filed complaints
alleging fraud and a civic group pledged to monitor polling stations
in Baja California, where voters elect a new governor Sunday.
Elections also were scheduled in four other states.
   The gubernatorial, legislative and mayoral elections are viewed
as a test of whether the goverment intends to keep the political
process honest.
   The opposition planned to have pollwatchers at all 1,666 polling
stations in Baja California when the border state's 900,000
registered voters vote Sunday, Javier Rivera of the conservative
National Action Party said Saturday.
   In the other voting Sunday, state legislators will be chosen in
Zacatecas, Michoacan, Campeche and Chihuahua. Mayoral elections are
scheduled in Chihuahua. Official results are expected in about a
week.
   In Baja California, the latest polls show a close finish between
Ernesto Ruffo of the National Action Party, or PAN, and Margarita
Ortega of the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI. A
poll published Friday in the Mexico City daily La Jornada showed
Ruffo at 33.7 percent and Ms. Ortega with 32.7 percent.
   Two leftist candidates stand virtually no chance of victory.
   If Ruffo _ a former mayor of Ensenada _ wins, the election would
be the first gubernatorial race the Institutional Revolutionary
Party lost in its 60-year history.
   Juan Manuel Salazar, president of the Action Party's municipal
committee in Tijuana, said Saturday he filed a complaint with the
state election commission alleging that election officials were
preparing to allow multiple voting with forged documents.
   Last week, the electoral commission burned 24,000 voting
credentials, claiming many of them were falsified. Some people even
use the registrations of deceased voters when they cast ballots.
   ``We can see if they are alive or dead. If they don't come, they
probably don't exist,'' said Antonio Rodriguez of the local
electoral commission.
   Opposition officials say their members mysteriously disappear
from the voting lists and are therefore unable to cast ballots.
   Hundreds of people waited all night Friday outside one election
office to obtain their registration cards. Jorge Amaral Munoz said
the wait was worth it.
   ``I'm worried about the political situation in this country,'' he
said. ``What's most important is that we decide through popular
vote. Who wins must do so honestly.''
   Salvador Morales Munoz, president of the Action Party campaign
committee in Tijuana, said 8,000 people still were not registered by
Saturday.
   But Rodriguez of the electoral commission said: ``We'll work up
until the last minute so people can vote.''
   Luis Alvarez, president of the National Action Party, said
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari has promised an investigation
into opposition charges that voter registration lists were padded in
Baja California and Chihuahua.
   Salinas, who took office in December, has vowed to clean up
Mexico's politics.
   ``I have stated that I will uphold the law and that I will
certainly practice it,'' Salinas said recently.
   The president recently announced expensive public works projects
for Baja California, where little more than one-third the voters
cast their ballots for him in last year's presidential balloting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
