<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 2204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Sole     07-01 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Sole,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Early Airmail Flier Dead At 99</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alva Sole, a U.S. Airmail Service pioneer
who delivered mail to Franklin D. Roosevelt and was a friend of
World War I ace Eddie Rickenbacker, died at age 99.
   Sole died in his sleep Thursday.
   In air mail's infancy, Sole would swoop down, aim his
canvas-covered biplane at two posts on the ground, fly between them
and snatch a mail pouch from a wire stretched overhead before
climbing back into the air.
   Highlights of Sole's career included flying mail to Roosevelt at
Warm Springs, Ga., and taking Roosevelt's son, Elliott, on plane
rides. He flew planes with Will Rogers.
   His friends included Rickenbacker, America's top World War I ace
and Eastern Airlines' founder, Jimmy Doolittle, the World War II
flier who led a daring surprise attack on Tokyo in April 1942, and
war correspondent Ernie Pyle.
   Sole was born in Wheeling, W.Va., in 1889 and as a teen-ager went
to work shoveling coal on a train. He landed a job as a mail clerk
on a train and worked his way up to become head of the postal
service's Atlanta office in 1933.
   In the meantime, he obtained his pilot's license, and volunteered
for some of the first airmail flights in the late 1920s and early
1930s. Many of the pilots died, getting lost in fog until their fuel
ran out or crashing into mountains.
   Their most dangerous maneuver was the pickup, when they would
swing down between the posts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
