<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 2218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-EGermany-Libya     07-01 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EGermany-Libya,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany Denies Western Loans Diverted To Libya, Terrorist Groups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist East Germany on Saturday denied
allegations it diverted to Libya millions of dollars in Western bank
loans and that much of the money wound up in the hands of terrorists.
   The state-run ADN news agency, in a one-sentence dispatch, said
the allegations ``do not correspond to the facts.'' ADN said the
statement came from ``the responsible (East German) agency.'' It did
not elaborate.
   A former member of the U.S. National Security Council, Norman A.
Bailey, said a $600 million loan to East Germany ended up in Libya
and that $60 million was given to terrorist groups in Libya,
Northern Ireland, Colombia and West Germany.
   Bailey, a senior director of national security planning from 1981
to 1983, said the loan was arranged by U.S. and other Western banks
in 1985.
   He said the money was traced by the highly secret National
Security Agency, which eavesdrops on international communications
for U.S. intelligence operations.
   Bailey said the deal was closed in London and that the money was
first transferred to East Berlin. He said it was then dispersed to
various front companies and later collected in Libya, where it was
given to terrorist groups.
   Bailey charged some of the money was distributed to terrorists
connected to the April 5, 1986 bombing of a West Berlin discotheque
killed a U.S. sergeant and a Turkish woman and wounded 204 people.
   The official Libyan news agency, JANA, has denied the story.
   White House spokesman Roman Papadiuk said he had no information
to substantiate Bailey's statement.
   Tom Lindeman, a spokesman for the First National Bank of Chicago,
said a $600 million loan to East Germany was organized in 1985 with
the International Bank of Japan.
   About 50 banks from different countries were involved, he said.
   Alan Delp, the Chicago bank's senior vice president in charge of
international banking, said he would be very surprised if the money
went to Libya.
</TEXT>
