<HEAD>Florida Crack Crackdown Nets Nearly 1,500 Arrests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to UPDATE arrest total; INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th
graf, ```From now ...' to UPDATE with drugs, money, cars seized; picks
up 5th graf, `About a third ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Undercover police officers posing as
drug dealers arrested more than 1,700 people in a weekend crackdown
on crack from the Florida Panhandle to the Keys, officials said
Saturday.
   Officers at times made nearly 100 arrests an hour, and it was
expected the total could top 2,000 before the 48-hour operation
concluded after midnight Saturday, Broward County sheriff's
spokesman George Crolius said at the command center here.
   Nearly 1,000 officers in 61 of the state's 67 counties
participated in ``Operation Rock Pile,'' which was organized by the
Florida Sheriffs Association.
   ``From now on, it's going to be war,'' said Broward Sheriff Nick
Navarro.
   By 10 p.m., the crackdown had netted 2,981 pieces of crack,
nearly 10 pounds of cocaine and three pounds of other drugs,
including heroin and steroids, Crolius said.
   Authorities also seized more than $44,300, 291 cars, a boat and
44 firearms, he said.
   About a third of the arrests were in the south Florida area from
Key West to Fort Pierce, including Miami and Fort Lauderdale, said
Crolius.
   But authorities were surprised by the more than 320 arrests
Friday and Saturday in the rural western Panhandle.
   ``We thought that most of the action would be in the cities,''
said Crolius. ``We didn't think we'd see that type of crack activity
in the Panhandle.''
   The effort targeted street-level crack users and dealers, the
spokesman said.
   ``We want to send the message down to the streets that we are
getting serious about crack,'' he said. ``We want to put the fear in
the users that at any time they could be buying from a cop.''
   Crack, a form of cocaine, is also known as rock.
</TEXT>
