<HEAD>Lawsuit Filed Over Tanning Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th, `After a...' to ADD more comment
from attorney; picks up 7th graf pvs, `Beyer does...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTAGE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 45-year-old woman who died after
undergoing a session in a beauty salon tanning booth in order to
treat a skin condition was not warned it could lead to dangerous
complications, her husband has charged in a complaint.
   The ultraviolet treatment _ which was prescribed in tandem with a
drug _ should have been done in a doctor's office or under tighter
controls, the husband's lawyer, Saul I. Ruman, said Saturday.
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration conducted an inquiry into
the death May 24 of Patsy J. Campbell, but the agency did not
recommend action against any individual or business, Clarence
Danielson, investigator at the FDA's Indianapolis office, said
Friday.
   Dr. Carolyn T. Beyer of Chesterton prescribed Oxsoralen-Ultra for
Mrs. Campbell for treatment of psoriasis,according to a complaint
filed Thursday with the state Department of Insurance.
   Mrs. Campbell, of Portage, took the drug two hours before
receiving the ultraviolet treatment as prescribed by Beyer,
according to the lawsuit brought by her husband, Julius.
   After a 25-minute session May 13 at Brenda's Hair Loft in
Portage, Mrs. Campbell suffered extensive burns and subsequent
infection. She died 11 days later at a hospital in Chicago.
   ``Tanning is ordinarily done in a doctor's office with meters
which precisely measure the amount'' of exposure, said Ruman.
   ``She shouldn't have been sent out without the tightest of
controls, or specific written directions,'' Ruman said.
   Beyer does not have a listed home number and no one immediately
responded to a message left Saturday on her office answering maching.
   Under Indiana law governing medical malpractice lawsuits, the
case will be reviewed by a panel of three doctors who will rule
whether there was malpractice.
   If the panel decides there was malpractice, the plaintiff and
defendant can negotiate a settlement and the plaintiff can also seek
compensation from the state Patient Compensation Fund. The maximum
from the doctor and the fund is $500,000, insurance department
officials said.
   If the panel rules there wasn't malpractice, the plaintiff can
pursue the case in the civil courts.
