<HEAD>Demonstrators Protest Death Of Man To Be Extradited To US; Police
Chief Fired</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators burned
tires and barricaded streets Saturday during the funeral of a man
who allegedly killed himself shortly before he was to be extradited
to the United States.
   Police fired tear gas to disperse the protest in his hometown of
Cotui, 70 miles north of the capital. Two people were injured and 20
people were arrested, authorities said.
   Police said Daniel Mirambeaux, 42, jumped to his death Thursday
from the third floor of police headquarters shortly after being told
he would be extradited to New York City to face charges he killed a
police officer.
   President Joaquin Balaguer on Saturday fired Police Chief Maj.
Gen. Nelson Morillo Rodriguez, who was reportedly with Mirambeaux
minutes before his death. No reason was given for the firing.
   Police said Friday that Mirambeaux escaped from two guards who
were escorting him from the police chief's office to the airport and
jumped through a large hole in the wall near a third-floor staircase.
   Mirambeaux was buried in Cotui while youths burned tires and
blocked streets with stones and tree trunks.
   A youth was injured by fragments of a tear gas canister shot by
police to disperse the demonstrators, and one policeman was injured
when a protester pelted him in the face, police said.
   Mirambeaux's relatives blamed police for his death and said they
doubted he committed suicide. On several occasions Mirambeux said he
would rather die than return to the United States to face trial in
the Oct. 18 shooting death of New York policeman Michael Buczek
during a drug raid in Manhattan.
   Mirambeaux, who arrived in the Dominican Republic the day after
Buczek's death, was jailed in November for illegal possession of a
pistol.
   A special investigating commission on Saturday began
interrogating the two policemen who accompanied Mirambeaux from the
police chief's office before he allegedly bolted and jumped from the
third floor.
   The two officers have been suspended pending the investigation's
findings.
