<BYLINE>By ROBERT MOEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indians wearing feathered headdresses
danced, a peace pipe was passed and ice cream was the hot item
Saturday at the Party of the Century, marking North Dakota's 100
years of statehood.
   The opening of the four-day centennial event was marked by
speeches, a colorful Vietnamese dragon dance and the release of
hundreds of balloons into sunny skies as the crowd sang ``Happy
Birthday.''
   ``This is a great idea,'' said Marianne Nesvig, a visitor from
Menlo Park, Calif. ``It's a unifying effort. They really went all
out.''
   An estimated 15,000 people turned out, said Highway Patrol Lt.
Jim Hughes.
   During the festivities, six Indians wearing traditional clothing
and headdresses performed the dances of their ancestors, beating on
drums and chanting Indian songs.
   At one point, four Indians sitting in a circle passed a
ceremonial peace pipe nearly 3 feet long among themselves, turning
the pipe in a circle before handing it to the next person.
   With temperatures in the 90s, the ice cream booth quickly became
popular.
   ``We're busy enough,'' said ice cream booth attendant June
Miller, trying to keep up with the line of customers.
   The Folklife Festival at the Capitol and other activities
throughout the area and the state provided a way to celebrate the
people and land of North Dakota, Lt. Gov. Lloyd Omdahl told a crowd
of several hundred.
   ``We are here to properly recognize the development of a great
state from a raw and rustic territory,'' said Omdahl, who was
dressed in a top hat and tails from the 1880s.
   ``It's your centennial,'' added former Gov. Art Link, chairman of
the state Centennial Commission, which planned to spend $100,000 on
the celebration it labeled the Party of the Century.
   ``You, the people of North Dakota, have taken the challenge and
are demonstrating the commitment present 100 years ago,'' Link said.
   Organizers of the extravaganza expected up to 100,000 people
would come to Bismarck and neighboring Mandan, which together are
home to about 65,000 people, for the four-day affair.
   The Folklife Festival featured tents and booths displaying
crafts, food and music representing all facets of the state's ethnic
heritage. Sunday's festivities were to include a parade of
horse-drawn wagons from Bismarck to Mandan.
   Idaho also begins its centennial year this week, and the
year-long observance of 100 years of statehood starts with a long
list of July events.
   Gov. Cecil D. Andrus has proclaimed Monday to be Idaho Statehood
Day, urging citizens to fly the flag and take part in local
observances.
