<HEAD>Playboy King Marries Centerfold</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 23 grafs to UPDATE with details, quotes and color
from wedding; picks up 16th graf, ``The news ...'' Kimberly, Bjay, Resa
all cq.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Playboy publisher Hugh Hefner married
Kimberley Conrad, 1988's Playmate of the Year, in an outdoor
ceremony Saturday afternoon as helicopters chattered overhead and
photographers jostled for a better shot of the Playboy mansion.
   The 30-minute, non-denominational ceremony took place in front of
the wishing well where the 63-year-old Hefner, perhaps the nation's
best-known playboy, proposed to Miss Conrad, 26.
   The wedding was heralded by the sounds of trumpets. About 200
guests, including actors Bill Cosby and Tony Curtis, were on hand
when Hefner tied the knot.
   The ceremony was conducted by Charles A. Ara, who ``brought
comedic moments'' to the proceedings, said Bjay Turner, a Playboy
publicist.
   ``The grass isn't always greener on the other side,'' Ara
counseled the groom. ``It's greener where it's watered. Hef, water
the grass.''
   The ceremony brought together top stars and culture magnates, but
those interviewed declined to give it symbolic meaning.
   Asked if the gathering marked the end of an era, Curtis said, ``I
think it's the beginning of somebody's marriage.''
   Motown records founder Barry Gordy became flustered when asked if
the sexual revolution was over. ``Ahhh, I don't know,'' he
stammered. ``I can't... I can't comment on that.''
   Hefner's brother, Keith, was the best man. Miss Conrad's sister,
Resa Miller, served as matron of honor and her father, Robert,
escorted her down a long, white carpet.
   Miss Conrad wore a full-length gown designed by Jim Hjelm, of New
York, with a drop waist and brocade bodice with a demure straight
neckline. The chapel-length train was dotted with pearls.
   Hefner chose a 1940s-style look that included a single-breasted
black wool tuxedo with black satin lapels and matching vest.
   A duplicate was made in case of an emergency, said Rick Pallack,
a haberdasher to the stars who has outfitted Pat Sajak, Tony Danza,
Wayne Gretzky and Sylvester Stallone.
   ``It's a great honor for me,'' Pallack gushed. ``I mean, the man
has worn nothing but silk pajamas for 30 years.''
   Wedding guests munched on imported cheeses and smoked fish, and
danced to a 25-piece band.
   The guests included former playmate Shannon Tweed and her rock
star husband Gene Simmons, and actors Dick Van Patten, Robert Culp
and Don Adams.
   The newlyweds plan to honeymoon at the mansion. When asked how
long, Ms. Turner said ``probably a lifetime.''
   Miss Conrad already has gotten one of her wishes, with the
mansion's comely entourage politely dispatched from the 5.3-acre
Playboy Mansion in the city's Holmby Hills section.
   ``She's made it clear that this is her home and people just can't
wander in and out now like they always have,'' Playboy spokesman
Bill Farley said several hours before the ceremony. ``They must be
cordially invited.''
   Hefner passed on holding the traditional bachelor party before
the wedding, and Farley quoted him as saying: ``Bachelor party? I've
had a bachelor party for 30 years, why do I need one now?''
   Farley said the marriage captures the spirit of the 1990s.
   ``Hugh Hefner, the perennial bachelor, is getting married at a
time a lot of his magazine readers are getting married,'' he said.
``The trend for the 1990s is commitment.''
   Hefner was married once before, for 10 years to Millie Williams,
and they had two children _ Christie, 36, and David, 34. ``I am,
most important, excited about it because he's so happy,'' said Ms.
Hefner, who is chairman of Playboy Enterprises.
   Earlier Saturday, workers wound garlands of flowers around the
mansion's grand staircase, and a huge white tent was erected
alongside the home's exotic grotto.
   The news media were not invited to the event. An advisory issued
last week detailed how pictures by former White House photographer
David Hume Kennerly and a news release would be distributed. And a
half-hour of taped highlights of the wedding was to be shown on the
cable Playboy Channel's pay-per-view service July 15.
   Hefner was tamed in part by a mild stroke in 1986. He stopped
smoking his pipe and he switched to caffeine-free Diet Pepsi, but he
still wears his trademark purple silk pajamas day and night.
   He lifted the blinds on sex when he started his Playboy empire in
1953, a decade before his bride was born, with his famous men's
magazine featuring nude pictures of women accompanied by risque text.
   The magazine now has a circulation of 3.5 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
