<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 2316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-EcologyPact     07-01 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ecology Pact,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poland, East Germany, Czechoslovakia Sign Ecology Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland, East Germany and Czechoslovakia
signed an agreement Saturday to cooperate on environmental
protection, the state news agency PAP reported.
   Under the agreement, the countries are to set up constant
monitoring of air pollution. A tripartite government commission will
be established to supervise implementation of the agreement, it said.
   The agreement contains ``commitments to prevent further
degradation of the natural environment, particularly in border
regions,'' the agency said.
   Prime Ministers Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski of Poland, Ladislav Adamec
of Czechoslovakia and Willi Stoph, chairman of the East German
Council of Ministers met in the southwestern city of Wroclaw for the
signing ceremony, PAP said.
   The governments are concerned about the noxious effects on the
environment of sulphur dioxide and phosphorous oxides, the agency
said.
   Rakowski was quoted as saying: ``Degradation of the environment
in southwestern Poland: water, soil and air pollution has reached a
catastrophic state. ... A real threat has surfaced of the ecological
balance being tipped and the region turning into a desert.''
   The smell of burning brown coal used for fuel hangs heavy over a
number of cities in the region including the industrial center of
Katowice, one of the most polluted cities in Poland. Even clear days
are often hazy from industrial pollution.
   Scientists at the Polish Academy of Sciences said in a January
report that 12 million Poles live in areas afflicted by a complete
breakdown of the environment. They said urgent measures were needed
to clean up the ``dirtiest country in Europe.''
   The Rakowski government has permitted the closing of a
chromium-producing factory near Wroclaw because it was an
environmental hazard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
