<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 2317EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ProtestersReunion     07-01 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Protesters Reunion,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Antiwar Bomber Joins '60s Activists Reunion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose antiwar bomb shattered a
five-story campus building said he regrets the 1970 blast killed
someone but still feels he was right to protest the Vietnam War.
   David S. Fine, a University of Wisconsin student at the time, was
among veterans of the 1960s protest movement who gathered this
weekend for a reunion.
   He and three other men were put on the FBI's list of most-wanted
fugitives after their homemade bomb damaged a campus building,
killing a student and injuring several other people on Aug. 24,
1970. Several other people were injured.
   Fine, Karleton Armstrong and his brother, Dwight Armstrong, were
eventually arrested and received prison sentences. Leo Burt,
identified as the fourth participant, was never captured.
   The building had formerly housed the Army Mathematics Research
Center and was frequently a target of campus antiwar demonstrations.
Fine and other participants denied intending to harm anyone.
   ``Regardless of why the bombing happened and the feelings people
had about the center and the war in Vietnam, that in no way
justifies the death and destruction,'' Fine said in an interview
published Saturday.
   ``So I have a lot of regrets about that. Always have, always
will, I'm sure,'' he said.
   Weekend events included discussion groups with topics ranging
from Women in the 1990s to the Decline and Fall of Civil Rights.
   Fine, 37, who works in a law office in Portland, Ore., said he
worried about what kind of reception he would get in Madison.
   ``I'm not going to come back and attempt to justify things I was
convicted of which were very tragic,'' he said.
   ``I probably wouldn't contemplate doing something like that now
under the same circumstances,'' Karleton Armstrong said. ``But for
where I was at and where people were at the time, I thought it was
right.''
   The Madison native said he had no plans to attend the reunion but
would be on the campus selling fruit juice from a stand he has
operated for several years.
   Dwight Armtstrong is in prison in Indiana on a drug charge.
   Madison FBI agent John Frazer said Burt was dropped from the
most-wanted list years ago but remains a federal fugitive. Asked if
authorities would watch for Burt during the reunion, university
security chief Ralph Hanson said: ``I'm looking for him. I don't
expect him to show up.''
</TEXT>
