<SECOND>AM-BRF--Highway Landing,0127</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Takes Unplanned Detour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TILTON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A holiday traveler landed his small airplane
in the middle of an interstate when he ran out of gas.
   Matthew Thiele of Nashua landed his plane in the southbound lanes
of Interstate 93 near the Tilton exit, less than 20 miles north of
Concord, when he ran out of fuel shortly after 4 p.m., said state
Trooper Kevin Stevens.
   No one was injured and no accidents were caused by the impromptu
landing, Stevens said. The single-engine Champion airplane was
pushed to the side of the road so traffic could continue moving.
   Thiele took off from the interstate a little less than 2 hours
later after passenger John Damron of Nashua got fuel.
