<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 2324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh-Pakistan     07-01 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Pakistan,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslems Demand Repatriation to Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Pakistanis stranded in
Bangladesh since it broke from Pakistan 17 years ago demonstrated
Saturday to demand repatriation.
   Witnesses said 5,000 Urdu-speaking Moslems attended the rally
outside the Central Secretariat, the seat of government.
   The protesters, many carrying placards reading ``we want to go to
Pakistan,'' dispersed after they were blocked by riot police from
entering the secretariat.
   Nasim Khan, a leader of the nearly 250,000 Pakistanis awaiting
repatriation, said ``if our demand is not met soon, we will march
via India to reach Pakistan.''
   Bangladesh, a Bengali-speaking nation, is separated from Pakistan
by 870 miles of Indian territory.
   Bangladesh was the eastern wing of Urdu-speaking Pakistan when it
was formed in 1947 after gaining independence from Britain. It broke
away from Pakistan after a 1971 war.
   About 500,000 Urdu-speaking Moslems migrated in 1947 to East
Pakistan, as Bangladesh was then known, but after the war demanded
that they be sent to Pakistan.
   In the first phase of repatriation under a United Nations High
Commission for Refugees program about 250,000 were sent back, but
the program was halted when funding ran out.
   The remaining migrants live in disease- and crime-ridden shanty
communities set up in most cities in Bangladesh.
   A Jeddah-based charitable organization, Rabita-e-Alam-e-Islami,
is trying to raise $300 million from Islamic nations for the
repatriation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
