<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0598 07-01 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0598,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs separates moved as a0579 on Naidoo, a0576 on Brister, a0569
on Hendler and a0615 on Sole.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Most Rev. Stephen Naidoo</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Most Rev. Stephen Naidoo, Roman Catholic
Archbishop of Cape Town, died Saturday at his sister's home. He was
51.
   Naidoo, whose Cape Town archbishopric made him one of the most
senior members of the 2.5-million Catholic community in South
Africa, suffered from a heart condition and was resting in London on
the advice of his physicians.
   Naidoo was ordained a priest June 29, 1961 and spent 14 years
working abroad. He returned to his native country in 1974 and was
consecrated a bishop on Sept. 15 that year.
   An outspoken critic of Pretoria's apartheid policies, Naidoo was
not as public a figure as other churchmen, including Anglican
Archbishop Desmond Tutu and Allan Boesak, president of the World
Alliance of Reformed Churches.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Brister</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Tyler Brister, a filmmaker and arts
educator whose animated movies won awards at the Cannes Film
Festival, died Wednesday of complications of AIDS. He was 38.
   One of his first films, ``Spanish Peanuts,'' is a stop-action
animated chorus line of peanuts dancing to a Latin rhythm. It has
been shown on HBO, NBC's ``Saturday Night Live'' and won the Silver
Cup Award at Cannes.
   Brister, a native of Dover, Ohio, graduated with honors from the
Minneapolis College of Art and Design in 1973. He was an
artist-in-residence at schools throughout the country and taught
filmmaking and animation techniques.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Gary Hendler</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Hendler, a tax attorney who
worked for some of the biggest movie stars in Hollywood and later
became head of Tri-Star Pictures, died Thursday of cancer. He was 50.
   A specialist in entertainment and tax law, his clients included
Robert Redford, Barbra Streisand, Sally Field, Sean Connery, Goldie
Hawn, Michael Caine, Nick Nolte, Elton John and Ella Fitzgerald.
   He joined Tri-Star as president and chief operating officer in
1983, and under his leadership the fledgling studio turned out such
hits as ``The Natural,'' starring Redford, and ``Places in the
Heart,'' starring Miss Field.
   He resigned as the studio's boss two years later to become an
independent producer, a capacity in which he continued to work with
Tri-Star.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Alba Sole</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alva Sole, a U.S. Airmail Service pioneer
who delivered mail to Franklin D. Roosevelt and was a friend of
World War I ace Eddie Rickenbacker, died Thursday at age 99.
   In air mail's infancy, Sole would swoop down, aim his
canvas-covered biplane at two posts on the ground, fly between them
and snatch a mail pouch from a wire stretched overhead before
climbing back into the air.
   Highlights of Sole's career included flying mail to Roosevelt at
Warm Springs, Ga., and taking Roosevelt's son, Elliott, on plane
rides. He flew planes with Will Rogers.
   Sole was born in Wheeling, W.Va., in 1889 and as a teen-ager went
to work shoveling coal on a train. He landed a job as a mail clerk
on a train and worked his way up to become head of the postal
service's Atlanta office in 1933.
</TEXT>
