<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--ForgottenBoy     07-01 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Forgotten Boy,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Left Behind For Hours As Family Moves To New Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Awaad family was packed and ready to
move to their new home, so away they went. But they forgot just one
thing _ 4-year-old Mohammed.
   Valerie Cargo, whose husband manages the apartments where the
family lived, said the little boy was left behind for almost four
hours before his parents alerted police from their new home and sent
an older sister back to look for him.
   Cargo said she found Mohammed crying in his family's former
apartment Thursday afternoon. ``He thought everybody had left him.
He was pretty hysterical,'' she said.
   She said she didn't know where the Awaads had moved, so she took
the boy to her apartment.
   The Awaads had left in separate cars with their other four
children for their new home in Union City, a few miles north of
Fremont.
   Police said it wasn't until the parents compared notes later that
they realized Mohammed had been left behind. Officers said no
official report would be made about the incident. The boy and his
family were safely and happily reunited.
