<DOCNO> AP890701-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 0049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RetiringEditor     07-01 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Retiring Editor,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Editor Leaves With Street Beat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Heath J is cq in penultimate graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Detroit Free Press senior managing editor Neil
Shine ended his career Friday the same place he started it 39 years
ago _ on the street.
   When Shine arrived for his last day of work, the retiring
journalist found the contents of his office, including his computer,
telephone and coffee machine, set up on a sidewalk in front of the
Free Press building.
   ``The entire office was empty, not a stick of furniture, not a
picture, nothing,'' said Shine.
   The prank was the idea of three reporters who wanted to mark
Shine's last day.
   ``One lady thought it was a circulation promotion and I signed
her up for daily and Sunday. We need every subscription we can
get,'' said Shine. ``Some guy walked out of the building and thought
we'd gone bankrupt.''
   Shine couldn't speak long because customer service workers were
passing around passes for free kisses.
   ``Numbers 65 and 66 are waiting,'' Shine said. ``Duty calls.''
   Heath J Meriwether, Free Press executive editor, said Shine
wasn't really leaving the paper, since he would continue writing his
column twice a week.
   ``It is gratifying that a man who has meant so much to our
readers the last 39 years is being remembered in a way he'll
appreciate,'' said Meriwether. ``He started as a street reporter and
he's ending up on the street.''
</TEXT>
