<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 0638EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-Kimbrough Adv14-16   07-01 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Kimbrough, Adv 14-16,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, July 14-16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Charles Kimbrough Says `Murphy Brown' Character Really a Romantic</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Dial, the rigid, humorless anchorman on
CBS' ``Murphy Brown,'' is really a romantic at heart.
   ``The public side that he's developed is armor-plated,'' says
Charles Kimbrough, who ought to know. He plays the co-anchor on the
show's fictional TV newsmagazine ``F.Y.I.,'' which also features
Murphy Brown (Candice Bergen), Frank Fontana (Joe Regalbuto) and
Corky Sherwood (Faith Ford).
   ``Inside he's a dreamer. He probably grew up reading Richard
Halliburton's travel adventures and wanting to be just like Edward
R. Murrow. He seems older because his values are those of an older
time. It makes him uncomfortable to have to share the show with a
former beauty queen like Corky Sherwood.
   ``He seems gruff with no sense of humor. But he can loosen up
with his friends. ... The comedy comes from the fact that he's such
a stiff. I have a fondness for that part of him that's loving and
vulnerable.''
   The thing Kimbrough says he dreads most is the comparison of Dial
to Ted Baxter on ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show.''
   ``Jim's a good journalist. Ted Baxter was a very bad journalist.
Jim's a smart guy, Ted was pretty dumb.''
   The role is the first real television exposure for Kimbrough. He
has spent most of his acting career on the stage in regional and
repertory companies, and got his ``big break'' with his Broadway
debut in ``Cop-Out.'' He also was in ``Company'' and ``Sunday in the
Park with George.''
   ``I was mostly working in the theater and making money doing
commercials. I'd occasionally do a movie or a part on television.
When I was asked to do an audition tape for `Murphy Brown' I figured
it was just a ticket to oblivion. You sit in front of a camera and
they put a bright light in your face.
   ``I loved the script and I wanted to do it. After the audition
tape I walked in the rain, feeling very depressed. Three weeks later
they asked me to fly to Los Angeles. I found out I was competing
against one of my best friends. They put us up in the same hotel and
we laughed about it. We both wanted it a lot. I flew back to New
York and was doing a commercial on location in Long Island when they
called and said I had the part.''
   Kimbrough grew up in the Chicago area, where his only early
connection with the theater was an aunt, Emily Kimbrough, who with
Cornelia Otis Skinner wrote ``Our Hearts Were Young and Gay.'' The
book about two young women traveling in Europe was adapted for the
stage, and was made into a movie in 1944.
   ``I grew up listening to music and doing a lot of drawing and
painting. I went to Indiana University _ and I've never told this to
anyone _ because they had a great opera department. I thought it
would be wonderful to go to a school where I could go to the opera
on Saturday night.
   ``I tried out for a school play and got a part. My grade average
went from a `B' to a `C' overnight because I was closing the
pizzeria every night with people who liked what I liked.
   ``I was in a lot of plays but it was too scary to call myself an
actor. When I went to the Yale Drama School I took directing
instead, but I spent most of my time acting.''
   Kimbrough met his wife, Mary Jane Wilson, at Yale. After
graduating they landed roles in ``All in Love,'' a musical
adaptation of Richard Sheridan's ``The Rivals.'' ``I was making
Equity scale and taking home $37.32. Jane was non-Equity and took
home $10 a week. They paid us in cash so it seemed like more. After
that we got out of the business for a while.''
   Wilson taught college and Kimbrough worked at a record club, but
they both returned to the stage in the Chicago version of a Julius
Monk revue. That was followed by three years with the Hartford Stage
Co. and six in Milwaukee.
   Despite directing classes at Yale, Kimbrough says he hasn't spent
much time in that capacity. ``I directed a few plays but I hated to
be the unpopular one in the company. If you tell an actor what to do
I'd always worry about it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wkd Edns, July 14-16</NOTE>
