<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-89 0624EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Fireworks-China Adv03   07-01 1147</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fireworks-China, Adv 03,1181</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, July 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fireworks Booming For Now but Future Supplies Could Fizzle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   While millions of Americans twirl sparklers, set off firecrackers
and ooh and aah over Fourth of July fireworks displays, U.S.
importers are getting headaches worrying about future festivities.
   ``There certainly is considerable concern for the 1990 season,''
says John Conkling, executive director of the American Pyrotechnics
Association. ``Everybody is awaiting word from factories in China
about the status of future deliveries.''
   So, before the last wisp of smoke has cleared on July 4, many
fireworks firms will have placed next year's orders in anticipation
of a possible shortage due to China's precarious political and
economic situation.
   The Chinese, credited with inventing fireworks about 1,000 years
ago, make the bulk _ more than 75 percent _ of the stuff U.S.
consumers use during Independence Day celebrations.
   Giving people such fleeting thrills as they get from lighting
Roman candles takes U.S. companies months of planning, negotiating
and waiting for shipments _even in the best of circumstances.
   U.S. fireworks firms normally have their overseas ordering done
by the autumn of each year to allow enough time for foreign
factories to manufacture and ship the goods early enough for
distribution in the United States before July.
   Now, however, the uncertainty of Chinese supplies has companies
scrambling to keep from being caught short next Fourth of July, by
far the biggest time of year for the fireworks business.
   Current supplies should be enough to satisfy this season's
demand; most imported Chinese fireworks had already arrived in the
United States or left China's shores before the Beijing government's
bloody crackdown on pro-democracy activists.
   ``The shipments for this year started arriving in the United
States back in November of 1988,'' observed John D. Rogers, a
fireworks expert at the Consumer Product Safety Commission. ``So the
majority of them were already here or on the water.''
   Phil Grucci, a member of the family that runs one of the
country's biggest organizers of fireworks shows, says intermediaries
that handle his company's purchases abroad have advised Grucci not
to panic. Nonetheless, the Bellport, N.Y.-based Fireworks by Grucci
Inc. expects a slowdown in Chinese production.
   ``We've already placed our purchase orders (to China) now to try
to beat the rush,'' Grucci said. ``We usually don't make big orders
until August or September to overseas.''
   Firms like Grucci that specialize in aerial displays don't rely
on China as much as companies do that primarily provide fireworks
for consumer use. Besides what it imports from China, Grucci
supplements its own products with fireworks from numerous foreign
sources including Japan, Taiwan and other Far Eastern countries as
well as ones in Europe.
   Royce Trout, of Atlas Enterprises Inc. in Fort Worth, Texas, a
fireworks maker and importer that ships throughout the country, says
manufacturing in China's northern provinces is more likely to be
affected by political unrest than factories elsewhere in the country.
   This is because most of the turmoil seems to have flared up
around China's economically developed areas and educational centers,
he says.
   Potential production snarls won't hit all types of fireworks.
Factories assembling firecrackers, a highly labor-intensive task,
mainly are located in the more rural part of China's southern
provinces so firecracker shipments aren't likely to be disrupted,
says Trout.
   Adding to problems that might arise from developments on the
political front, Trout says he's been informed that several Chinese
factories are facing financial trouble.
   A lack of credit to cover material and other costs has put three
or four factories in Hunan Province in danger of closing. The
southeastern province annually accounts for about 15 percent of
China's total fireworks shipments to the United States, which came
to more than 50 million pounds in 1987, the most recent year for
which U.S. government figures were available.
   Tightness in availability of one of Atlas Enterprises' most
popular items probably reflects these financial difficulties. The
item is a type of ground spinner _ a category of fireworks that
China created _ that spews fiery blossoms as it gyrates on the
ground. Ground spinners are tubes packed with a an assortment of
fireworks producing multiple effects.
   ``I'm very, very worried about what kind of supply we'll get from
some provinces both from a political standpoint and a financial
standpoint,'' says Trout.
   People in the fireworks business say there are only a few
countries that could help fill a potential shortfall in Chinese
shipments. And, there are limits to how much places such as Hong
Kong, Taiwan and Macao, the Portuguese-administered territory off
China's southeastern coast, could compensate.
   Conkling of the pyrotechnics trade group says fireworks are an
important export for China.
   The country was becoming a powerful force in fireworks just
before former President Richard Nixon reopened trade with the
country in the early 1970s. It has come to dominate the industry
today, largely because its factories turn out products of acceptable
quality at unbeatable prices due to low labor costs.
   ``Fireworks is a legitmate science in China _ universities do
research into pyrotechnics and fireworks and this translates into
big business for the country,'' says Conkling.
   For years, China has kept fireworks prices down, very close to
the cost of production, to attract customers. But U.S. businesses
say that even before the political problems they were told to expect
price hikes of 15 percent to 30 percent for next season's orders as
the Chinese try to eke out more profit.
   U.S. retail sales of fireworks will total about $200 million this
year, the industry says.
   Government figures indicate China supplies about 76 percent by
weight of all fireworks brought into the United States but the
industry says the figures probably understate Chinese imports.
   As China's shipments have grown, the quality has been slipping,
possibly because newer factories aren't as familiar with U.S.
regulations. All imported fireworks must meet the same safety
standards as domestically made products.
   Trout, who also is president of the industry's trade association,
says the group has been working on a sort of self-regulatory program
to promote consistent quality, partly to account for advances in
fireworks since government regulations were written.
   Because of China's trade dominance, the U.S. industry has been
taking special care to see that the Chinese know what's expected of
them. The industry is preparing an improved translation into Chinese
of all the requirements, set down by several U.S. agencies.
   As part of the quality campaign, U.S. industry representatives
had scheduled a trip to China in late July and early August. Now the
campaign may have to be put on hold.
   ``We are quite concerned at this point as to how the situation in
China will affect our efforts to get this quality assurance program
in place,'' said Conkling. The meeting in China, he says, ``is very
much up in the air at this point.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
