<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv03 1stLd-Writethru 07-01 0796</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv03, 1st Ld-Writethru,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, July 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>Junk-Bond Mutual Funds: Tempting, But Dangerous For The Uninformed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf, Vanguard has ..., to CORRECT April figure and
percentage change for Vanguard fund.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors have been pouring money into junk-bond
mutual funds in recent months as interest rates available elsewhere
have fallen, but they may be unaware of the danger lurking in these
tempting, high-yield investments.
   ``Many people hear the word `bonds' and they think `safe,
conservative,''' said Neal Litvack of Fidelity Investments, operator
of one of the largest junk-bond funds. ``Junk bonds have a tendency
to dance to a different drummer.''
   That drummer is the state of the economy. Unlike investment-grade
corporate bonds, junk bonds face a greater danger of plummeting in
price in a recession.
   Junk bonds are bonds that carry a low credit rating as determined
by credit-rating agencies. Their low rating reflects the fact that
the companies that issued the bonds may be deep in debt or otherwise
poor credit risks.
   Junk bonds also are used to raise cash for many leveraged
takeovers, where the corporate raider takes on a great deal of debt
in order to pay for the target company.
   In contrast, investment-grade corporate bonds are considered a
conservative, safe investment because the issuing company is rated
financially sound and considered able to meet its debt obligations
even in a downturn.
   To make up for their extra risk, junk bonds pay a higher interest
rate. Junk bond mutual funds have been yielding 12 percent or more
recently, compared with about 9 percent for investment-grade bond
funds and 8 percent for Treasury bond funds.
   Litvack said the assets of Fidelity's junk-bond mutual fund
surged from $1.7 billion at the end of March to about $2 billion
last week.
   While most investment companies would be happy to see their
investment funds grow, Boston-based Fidelity is concerned. It
believes many of the new investors _ some of whom pulled money out
of other, safer Fidelity mutual funds _ don't know what they're
getting into.
   ``Right now there is a misperception about what drives the
performance of these securities,'' said Litvack, Fidelity's vice
president of marketing. ``Interest rates are not the primary driver
of these funds; it's much more a function of the economy.''
   With investment-grade bonds, declining interest rates usually
lead to higher bond prices. That's because bonds keep paying the
same fixed interest while rates available elsewhere are becoming
less attractive.
   But junk-bond traders are more concerned about the financial
health of the companies that issued the bonds. If the economy sours,
these companies would be at risk of not earning enough to pay the
interest on the bonds, or even of outright default.
   ``A lot of these (junk) bonds haven't been tested in a down
market,'' said Brian S. Mattes, a spokesman for the Vanguard Group,
another major mutual-fund operator.
   ``There could be a stampede out of the fund in a recession,'' he
said. ``There will be a lot of people running for the door at the
same time. In fact, the price may go down more because of that.''
   Vanguard has seen the assets of its junk-bond fund grow 13
percent in the past two months, from about $1.14 billion at the end
of April to about $1.29 billion last week. Some is from appreciation
and the rest from new investors.
   Mattes said Vanguard, based in Valley Forge, Pa., sent brochures
to its customers to warn them of the risks of its junk-bond fund.
   ``It should not be viewed as a short-term investment at all,'' he
said. Long-term investors would be at a lesser risk of losing
principal because they could ride out an economic downturn.
   Investors expecting declining interest rates should put their
money in Treasury funds, Litvack said.
   In fact, total return on Treasury bonds _ the total interest paid
plus any change in the bond prices _ exceeded that of the
higher-yielding junk bonds in the first five months of this year.
   The January-May return on seven-year Treasury bonds exceeded 6
percent, while Fidelity's junk-bond fund returned only 2.26 percent
and Vanguard's returned 2.12 percent due to major declines in the
price of these bonds as the economy slowed, according to Lipper
Analytical Services Corp.
   Litvack said junk-bond funds are not for investors saving for
retirement or other needs.
   One major mutual-fund company, Dreyfus Corp., said it is so
concerned about the risks of junk-bond funds that it doesn't sponsor
one.
   ``The underlying basis for junk bonds is that economic expansion
will continue forever, enabling highly leveraged companies to meet
their heavy debt burdens,'' said Howard Stein, Dreyfus' chairman and
chief executive.
   Dreyfus, he said, is not that optimistic.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
